<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Foreigners     10-04 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Foreigners,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record 7,196 Foreigners Arrested For Working In Japan Illegally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese police and immigration authorities
arrested a record 7,196 foreigners in the first six months of this
year for violating immigration laws by working in Japan, the
Immigration Office said today.
   The number of violators from January-June was up 24 percent from
the previous record of 5,802 in the corresponding period of 1987,
an official of the immigration office said.
   Those arrested this year, compared to the same period last year,
included 3,013 Filipinos, down from 4,436; 1,432 Bangladeshis,
sharply up from 139; 1,169 Pakistanis, up from 288; 727 Thais, up
from 561 and 447 South Koreans, up from 81, all compared with the
like period of 1987.
   Most of those arrested were deported, the official said.
   Last year, 11,307 foreigners were arrested throughout the nation
for working illegally.
</TEXT>
