<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PipeBomb     10-04 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pipe Bomb,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused of Trying To Bomb Wife In Scotland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former U.S. Marine munitions expert, who
sought a ``tough Irishman'' to deliver a bomb hidden in a tape
recorder to his wife in Scotland, has been arrested, police said.
   The bomb was set to explode when the play button was pressed,
Nassau County Detective Sgt. Daniel Severin said Monday.
   Charles Hili, 54, who is in the middle of a divorce, was
arrested after a man answered an advertisement Hili placed in the
Irish Voice newspaper Oct. 1, seeking a ``tough Irishman ... to
handle a confidential assignment,'' police said.
   An Irish-American man who answered the ad called police after
Hili told him his plan, Severin said.
   The man, who was not identified, met with Hili on Sunday as
police watched, the detective said.
   Hili, who lives in Elmont near this Long Island city, spelled
out his instructions and handed the man a tape recorder with a bomb
inside, police said.
   He told the man to fly to Ireland, take a ferry to Scotland and
deliver the tape recorder to his wife's home in Glasgow, said
Severin.
   Hili, a self-employed lumber buyer, made arrangements to pay the
man $2,000, Severin said.
   Hili was charged with criminal solicitation, criminal possession
of a weapon and conspiracy. First District Court Judge John Evans
ordered him held without bail.
</TEXT>
