<DOCNO> AP881004-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChangingtheRecord     10-04 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Changing the Record,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: What You Read Isn't Always What You Heard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Congressional Record is the verbatim
record of every word said on the floor of the Senate and the House
_ except for when it isn't.
   It is a congressional privilege to change the Congressional
Record when it suits.
   Sometimes it is only a matter of cleaning up a congressman's
grammar or misstatements of fact.
   Changes sometimes involve matters of substance, sometimes not.
   Sometimes they are made to soften a stinging phrase, or smooth
over an embarrassment.
   Former Sen. Barry Goldwater, R-Ariz., contends in his recently
published autobiography, ``Goldwater,'' that sometimes changes are
made for reasons of politics.
   An example, he declares, occurred several years ago on the
morning after a speech by Senate Democratic leader Robert C. Byrd
of West Virginia.
   Byrd, had, Goldwater said, ``used some frothy language that
wasn't particularly fitting for the floor.''
   ``I can't recall exactly what he was excited about, but his
anger poured out as if he had just finished a bad jug of West
Virginia moonshine.''
   ``God, I said to myself, I've got to get a copy of that speech
from the Congressional Record. He said some things that will really
hurt him. We'll send it along to the Republican party in West
Virginia.''
   But after a line-by-line search of the Record, Goldwater said,
Byrd's remarks were nowhere to be found.
   ``So I went back to the Senate reporter's room and asked,
`Where's all that stuff Byrd talked about last night.''
   ```Oh,' the reporter said, `he edited it out.'''
   Goldwater's conclusion: ``Today, some senators operate regularly
on this double standard _ saying one thing on the floor to capture
state or media attention, but deleting it from the official record
so their precise remarks cannot be used against them.''
   Changes _ large and small _ are made in the Record virtually
daily.
   A dispute flared on the House floor last week during
consideration of legislation to require a study of the federal pay
system to determine if women are being paid less than men for
comparable work.
   Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, told Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., that
the reason he did not know a detail about the bill was that he
rarely bothered to attend meetings of the House Post Office and
Civil Service Committee which had considered it.
   Burton said he served on many other committees and had higher
priorities ``and listening to the gentlewoman from Ohio at these
meetings is not one of my top priorities.''
   Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., angrily intervened, accusing the
congresswoman of ``smart-aleck remarks.''
   After an intervening vote, Rep. Mervyn M. Dymally, D-Calif.,
demanded that Solomon apologize.
   But here the words he said and the words recorded in the
Congressional Record part company.
   What Dymally was heard to say, and what he did say as confirmed
by a review of the television tape of the proceedings, was:
   ``If there is any decency left in the gentleman, he will come to
the floor here and ask that those words be stricken from the
Record.''
   Perhaps that was too strong.
   The Congressional Record version: ``If there is any courtesy
left in the gentleman, he will come to the floor here and ask that
those words be stricken from the Record.''
   In the end courtesy did prevail.
   The gentleman from New York already had apologized, the
gentlewoman from Ohio said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881004-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialDebate Bjt   10-04 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Debate, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Pledge to Debate Despite Sponsorship Withdrawal by
League</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis and George Bush are sticking
by plans to meet in a second presidential debate later this month,
despite the League of Women Voters' withdrawal as sponsors in a
dispute over control of format and other details.
   The bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates, sponsors of
the first presidential debate and Wednesday's debate between vice
presidential nominees, quickly stepped in Monday and agreed to take
over sponsorship.
   ``There is going to be a second presidential debate,'' said Bush
spokesman Mark Goodin.
   The second debate, viewed as an opportunity for Dukakis as he
trails Bush in most polls, was scheduled to be held in Los Angeles
on Oct. 13 or 14, depending on the length of the American League
baseball playoffs. The campaigns said they would stick to those
dates.
   Janet Brown, executive director of the commission, said it hoped
to keep the debate in Los Angeles and was seeking local groups to
help it finance preparations, which the League had estimated at
$500,000.
   But the League of Women Voters has rights to the Shrine Memorial
Auditorium in Los Angeles, where it was scheduled. And Vicky
Harian, the League's debates director, said ``I doubt very
seriously'' it would relinquish its rights.
   All sides said they would look elsewhere if a Los Angeles site
cannot be arranged.
   ``I want to go forward in Los Angeles,'' Dukakis said. ``The
agreement (with the Bush campaign) provides that if for some reason
the sponsor decides to pull out, we still go ahead. I want to go
ahead.''
   The commission agreed to follow the two campaigns' detailed
agreement for debate format and staging _ an agreement the League
denounced as a ``charade'' that would stiffle spontaneity and a
true exchange on the issues.
   ``We have no intention of becoming an accessory to the
hoodwinking of the American public,'' said Nancy M. Neuman, the
league's president.
   Neuman contended the campaigns have so controlled the format
that questioning by a panel of journalists will be subject to
``very clear restrictions in terms of what they can ask.'' When
pressed to back up her charge, she pointed to script approval
required for the moderator's remarks, and to her disagreement with
the pattern for follow-up questions by the panel and rebuttal by
the candidates.
   In a printed statement she did not read at her news conference,
Neuman said the agreement ``would perpetrate a fraud on the
American voter'' and ``add debates to their list of campaign-trail
charades devoid of substance, spontaneity and honest answers to
tough questions.''
   But the commission director rejected suggestions the format was
too controlled and pointed to the success of the first debate.
   The League's involvement in 1988 debates has been long at issue.
Spurred in part by discontent with the League's sponsorship of
debates in previous presidential elections, the Republican and
Democratic parties joined with the bipartisan Commission on
Presidential Debates to sponsor them this year.
   But sponsorship itself became one of the items at issue in
hardball debate negotiations between the Dukakis and Bush
campaigns. The campaigns ultimately agreed to two debates, one
sponsored by the commission and one by the League, plus a vice
presidential debate under commission sponsorship.
   At her news conference, Neuman acknowledged that at the heart of
their dispute was the League's lack of involvement in the agreement.
   ``The issue is, who's in control of the debate,'' she said.
   Bush campaign officials privately belittled the League's
complaints as ``nitpicking items'' and denied an attempt to control
questioning.
   One Bush campaign source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the League's action ``guarantees they're out of the debate
business for good. They made the mistake of misunderstanding their
role.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
