<DOCNO> AP881004-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Military Bjt   10-04 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Military, Bjt,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Rebuilds Army, Bolsters Revolutionary Guards After Defeats</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran is reorganizing its military forces
and seeking advanced weapons in the wake of disasterous defeats in
the war with Iraq that forced it to accept a United
Nations-sponsored cease-fire.
   ``The reconstruction of the armed forces has a very high
priority'' in the overall post-war reconstruction program, Defense
Minister Brig. Gen. Mohammad Hussein Jalali stressed last week.
   ``The Army and the Revolutionary Guards Corps must definitely be
strengthened,'' he said in an interview with Tehran's Kayhan daily.
   ``This does not mean reinforcement for an offensive, but rather
the prevention of probable aggression and for defense.''
   Asked if Iran's unconditional acceptance of the U.N. Security
Council's cease-fire resolution will ease a U.S.-led arms embargo
that caused major problems during the 8-year war, Jalali replied:
``Not yet.
   ``But there have been some signs. The world has now realized
that Iran's cause has been genuine.''
   Diplomatic sources have said that the Iranians are badly short
of combat aircraft, tanks, radar and other sophisticated weaponry.
   Even before the Iraqi victories, the Iranians were believed to
be chronically short of heavy weapons.
   The Iraqis claim they captured much of Iran's operational armor
in a series of offensives between April and August that retook all
the territory the Iranians had seized in the previous six years.
   U.S. sources in the Persian Gulf reported that when the Iraqis
scored one of their key battlefield victories shortly before July
20, the Iranians hastily withdrew tanks based on Sirri and Abu Musa
islands in the southern gulf and rushed them to the front.
   One source said the move ``showed how desperate the Iranians
were for supplies and weapons. They didn't have much of anything
left.''
   The speed with which the Iranians were driven back surprised
even the Iraqis. Iranian resistance, mainly by the Revolutionary
Guards, appeared to collapse rapidly as the Iraqis regained the
offensive after years of static defense.
   The Iranians' abrupt acceptance of U.N. Resolution 598, the
basis for the Aug. 20 cease-fire, stunned many Iranians, including
the military, said businessmen who were in Tehran at the time.
   ``Several of the young men in my family were at the front and
they couldn't believe it,'' said one Iranian, in Nicosia to attend
a seminar.
   ``They knew things weren't going well, but they were absolutely
speechless. They couldn't understand how it all caved in so fast.
Some were relieved that the dying was over. But some were extremely
bitter.''
   ``They argued that if we were going to accept (Resolution) 598,
why didn't we do it while we still occupied Iraqi territory, while
we had something to bargain with? A lot of people are asking such
questions,'' the businessman said, speaking on condition he was not
identified.
   There have been indications that the Revolutionary Guards, known
as Pasdaran, have been blamed for Iran's defeats.
   The corps was originally formed as a paramilitary force to
safeguard the Islamic revolution. But it was thrust into a military
role by Iraq's invasion in September 1980 and eventually eclipsed
the regular army which had been built up by the shah and was
distrusted by the hierarchy.
   Iran's Parliament last month dismissed Mohsen Rafiqdoust, the
government minister in charge of the corps. He was replaced by Ali
Shamkhani, 33, deputy commander of the corps' ground forces.
   But Iranian leaders have publicly defended the Pasdaran.
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini told corps commanders at a military
seminar last month: ``You are my closest and dearest aides.''
   A unified military command set up by Parliament Speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani, named acting commander-in-chief by Khomeini last June
in a bid to reverse Iran's battlefield defeats, has been reshaping
the armed forces.
   The reorganization has centered on the 350,000-strong
Revolutionary Guards.
   But moves to merge the guards with the 200,000-man regular army
have been shelved.
   ``The Pasdaran have become very powerful and they're not going
to surrender that easily,'' one Western analyst noted.
   But the parallel chains of command that so bedeviled the
Iranians during the war have been streamlined to produce what
Rafsanjani hopes will be a more cohesive Iranian military machine.
   Rafsanjani told the Pasdaran that they must temper their Islamic
zeal with conventional military training and discipline.
   ``You must pay attention to the hierarchy and to orders,''
Rafsanjani cautioned them.
</TEXT>
