<DOCNO> AP881004-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Democrats-Gingrich     10-04 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats-Gingrich,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats, Angered by Gingrich, Target Georgia Republican</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mention Rep. Newt Gingrich to stalwarts of the
Democratic Party and they vow through gritted teeth to do
everything in their power to unseat the Georgia Republican.
   ``You've got a guy in Georgia who's trying to destroy the
Democratic Party,'' said Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., chairman of
the House Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee. ``That's his
sole mission in life. There's a price to pay for that, and the
price is return to the private sector.''
   Traditionally, the DCCC has come to the aid of promising
Democratic challengers, providing campaign funds and advice. But in
David Worley's campaign to replace Gingrich, the committee is
leaving no stone unturned.
   In January, the DCCC filed mail fraud charges against Gingrich
and a political action committee he heads _ Conservatives for Hope
and Opportunity. The complaint to the U.S. Postal Service received
widespread publicity, but no action was taken against Gingrich or
the PAC.
   Then in May, on the same day Gingrich filed an ethics complaint
against House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, the committee accused
the Georgia Republican of accepting $13,000 from a group of wealthy
friends in 1977 to write a book he never produced.
   The object of the committee's attention is a conservative,
five-term representative who does not shrink from the opportunity
to attack Democrats.
   Gingrich has accused Wright of improperly using his position for
financial gain, including the allegation that the House speaker
made unduly high royalties on his book. A House ethics committee is
investigating the complaints.
   And last month, Gingrich called Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis ``nuts,'' and accused the candidate of being a
``left-winger'' who opposes weapons systems supported by Republican
George Bush.
   The Dukakis campaign dismissed Gingrich's comments as ``typical
of his nasty approach.''
   Gingrich's opponent for the House seat _ Worley _ is a
29-year-old attorney from Jonesboro making his first bid for public
office.
   After a close Democratic primary win in August, Worley received
$5,000 from the committee to pay off his primary debts and the
promise of another $5,000 for the fall campaign.
   The amount is the maximum the committee can provide in direct
contributions, but legally it also can give up to $40,000 in
``coordinated expenditures'' for such services as polling and voter
identification. Anthony said that amount would be determined by the
committee's ongoing assessment of Worley's chances of defeating
Gingrich.
   In his campaign arsenal, Worley has incorporated the committee's
charges of mail fraud and the book allegations against Gingrich as
well as a claim that Gingrich wants to abolish Social Security.
   That allegation stems from a plan Gingrich proposed which calls
for people under 40 to get no Social Security retirement, but
require them to put 10 percent of their incomes into individual
retirement accounts.
   Worley also has accused Gingrich of missing 70 percent of his
House committee meetings and of ignoring the concerns of his
constituents while traveling the country to promote his own
conservative agenda.
   Gingrich acknowledges that he is potentially vulnerable on that
issue, but said the voters in his suburban Atlanta district
understand that his role as a national spokesman for the GOP right
helps him better represent them in Congress.
   ``I think that's what you want in a congressman, to take local
problems and understand their national implications and speak out
on how we can change things in America so that we are changing
things in the 6th District,'' Gingrich said.
   Anthony said Worley is beginning to ``score some good points
against Gingrich,'' but he conceded that a Democratic victory in
November would be an upset.
   And if Worley fails, there's always 1990, Anthony said.
   ``Sometimes it takes a four-year effort to knock off an
incumbent,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
