<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Libya Bjt   10-04 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Libya, Bjt,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gadhafi's Opening To Chad Another Sign Of Moderation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya's decision to re-establish diplomatic
relations with Western-backed Chad is another sign that Col.
Moammar Gadhafi is moving toward moderation, or at least wants to
be seen that way.
   The Libyan leader has been having a hard time removing the label
of terrorism attached to his regime. Just last week, the top U.S.
anti-terrorism official accused Libya of continuing to support Abu
Nidal, a Palestinian blamed for engineering several spectacular
attacks, including a commando strike this summer on a Greek cruise
ship that killed nine people.
   Gadhafi is keen on improving relations with the United States,
which led a campaign in early 1986 to convince the West to join an
economic boycott to punish Libya for its alleged support of
international terrorism.
   But last Friday, the West German government cited recent
``positive changes'' in Libya when it announced it is sending an
ambassador back to Tripoli. The post had been vacant since spring
1986, shortly after a bombing of a Berlin disco, an attack that
U.S. officials blamed on Gadhafi. The U.S. administration responded
with bombing raids on the Libyan cities of Tripoli and Benghazi.
   In an interview with The Associated Press last month, Gadhafi
expressed confidence that Libya-U.S. relations will improve after
January, when President Reagan leaves the White House.
   Gadhafi's turnabout regarding Chad is one of several foreign and
domestic changes indicating that he may have decided that he will
get more mileage out of moderation than intransigence.
   In dealing with Chad, for example, Gadhafi ``passed from (a
policy of) conquest to negotiation,'' commented a European diplomat
who has been monitoring developments in Libya for years.
   After years of bitter fighting in the deserts of northern Chad,
Libya and Chad announced on Monday that they have restored
diplomatic relations and said they will settle their border dispute
in a responsible and understanding manner.
   In the interview with the AP on Sept. 5, Gadhafi said he was
willing to negotiate on the status of the Aouzou Strip, a
45,000-square-mile stretch of land possibly rich in minerals that
borders the two countries.
   More than once Libya had labeled Chad's President Hissene Habre
as a stooge of ``imperialist'' France and the United States, which
backed Chad in the conflict.
   The diplomat said Gadhafi's foreign policy had been feeling the
influence of Libyan Prime Minister Omar al-Muntasser, considered a
moderate. He was named to the post in a Cabinet shuffle earlier
this year.
   A West German foreign ministry official, in explaining why Bonn
decided to upgrade its diplomatic relations, cited Gadhafi's
freeing of many Chadian prisoners this summer as well as ``internal
reforms.''
   This year Gadhafi has called for the abolitin of the death
penalty in Libya, freed some political prisoners from Libyan jails
and loosened economic restrictions, even giving his blessing to
black market enterprises.
   Gadhafi has been paying special attention to forging solid ties
with his North African neighbors. He restored relations with
Tunisia in December after a two-year hiatus following Libya's
expulsion of more than 30,000 immigrant workers. Looming largely in
that move were economic considerations _ Libya depends heavily on
the workers for farm and other manual labor.
   Economic considerations also figure in Libya's links with
Western European countries. For example, wanting to expand its
economic base beyond crude oil sales, Libya recently opened up a
chain of gasoline distributorships in Italy.
   As for West Germany, Libya is its No. 2 oil supplier, after
Britain.
   Terrorism remains the biggest hurdle in Gadhafi's proclaimed
quest for better foreign relations.
   ``We hope that has changed for the better, but we will have to
wait and see,'' said the Foreign Ministry official last week.
   West Berlin authorities have said they have no concrete
indications that Libya was involved in the disco attack and said
they suspect Syria instead.
   The Reagan administration is firm on holding Gadhafi to blame
for many major terrorist attacks.
   Its No. 1 counterterrorism official, L. Paul Bremer, said last
week that the 1986 U.S. bombing raids and Western pressure has
caused Libya to ``drive the terrorism'' into ``different channels,
so that instead of using diplomats and business,'' Gadhafi is
``doing it more through surrogates, like Abu Nidal and the Japanese
Red Army,'' a terrorist group which claimed the bombing a club in
Naples, Italy, in April. A U.S. servicewoman was killed.
   Gadhafi denies he sponsors terrorism. But Abu Nidal is reported
frequently in Tripoli.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Frances D'Emilio, a correspondent in Rome, also
reports on Libya and interviewed Gadhafi there in September.
</TEXT>
