<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Refugees     10-04 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Refugees,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Commissioner For Refugees Appeals for $120 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. high commissioner for refugees said the
organization needs $120 million to meet its budget this year and
appealed to U.N. members to pay and increase their contributions.
   Jean-Pierre Hocke addressed the commission's executive committee
at the opening of its annual meeting Monday. He said the agency had
increased its 1988 budget from $377.5 million to $420.7 million in
September because of ``developments in Ethiopia, Malawi, Rwanda and
Hong Kong.''
   He said the organization has received only $300 million and
needs more than $120 million to cover costs.
   During the one-week meeting of the 43-nation executive board the
delegates are to approve the 1989 budget for the commission.
   Judith Kumin, a spokeswoman for the commission, said the 1989
goal is a budget of $400 million.
   The commission attempts to aid the world's estimated 12 million
refugees. According to U.N. statistics, more than 5 million are
refugees from the war in Afghantistan and nearly 5 million are
Africans fleeing from conflicts and food shortages.
   Most of the others are from southeast Asia and Central America.
</TEXT>
