<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SKorea-Future     10-04 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SKorea-Future,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Roh Calls For New Era After Olympics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo today hailed the
Olympic Games as a major turning point in Korea's history and
declared he would launch new efforts to reunite the peninsula and
build full democracy.
   In a speech to the National Assembly, Roh said he would keep an
election promise to let voters pass judgment on how well his
government has kept its promise of democratic reforms, but he did
not say what form the assessment would take.
   Roh said the Olympics, which ended Sunday, were a major success
for South Korea and would help provide impetus for further progress.
   ``We are opening a new chapter of history in which Korea should
achieve both unification and prosperity and emerge as a major
player on the world scene in the 21st century,'' he said.
   The peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
U.S.-supported South Korea at the end of World War II. North Korea
invaded South Korea in 1950 and a truce in 1953 re-established a
demilitarized zone dividing the country.
   North Korea boycotted the Olympics after its demand to co-host
the games was rejected.
   Roh, in the nationally televised speech, said it was time to
overcome the divisions of the past and called for a major effort to
build a democratic system and share the nation's prosperity.
   He said he would present a new plan to build ties with the North
but gave no details.
   Roh repeated an offer made in July to visit Pyongyang, the
capital of North Korea, for a summit meeting with President Kim Il
Sung to discuss ``all pending issues.''
   The two Koreas are to resume talks Oct. 13 on trying to reduce
tension. Negotiations in August failed to make any progress.
   ``I will endeavor to bring about a spring of reconciliation
between the South and the North, which have remained in a deep
freeze for 40 years,'' Roh said.
   The Soviet Union, China and most other communist nations
participated in the Olympics and Roh said that provided an
opportunity for South Korea to build ties with the communist world
that ease tension with the North.
   He also said South Korea would maintain its close ties with the
United States, Japan and other allies. ``The United States is an
ally with whom we have been defending the peace and freedom of the
Korean peninsula,'' he said.
   But Roh also said the threat of war with the North still existed
and the ``security situation on the Korean peninsula and in
northeast Asia remains as grave as ever.''
   Roh vowed to introduce full democracy. ``The authoritarian rule
that caused public anxiety, tension and distrust and strife for the
past four decades has unmistakably been abolished,'' he said.
   He said radical students that have staged frequent
anti-government demonstrations were seeking ``a violent class
revolution.''
   ``They are thus attempting to overthrow our free democratic
system through violence and other illegal acts. Such activities
cannot be tolerated anymore,'' he said.
   The president expressed confidence in the country's economy and
predicted exports would reach $90 billion by 1992, compared to
$47.3 billion last year. He announced a budget for 1989 of $27
billion _ an 11 percent increase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
