<1ST_LINE>r w PM-VeteransAppeals     10-04 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Veterans Appeals,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passage Near on Bill Allowing Veterans' Appeals in Federal Courts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is moving to break a decades-long
stalemate with legislation that would allow veterans to go outside
the Veterans Administration to appeal denial of benefits.
   The House voted 400-0 Monday for a bill that would allow
veterans, for the first time in 170 years, to appeal VA denials to
a federal court.
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., said arrangements have been worked
out with the Senate to write a compromise bill in a conference
committee. The Senate has passed its own version of the legislation.
   Rep. G.V. Montgomery, D-Miss., the chairman of the House
Veterans Affairs Committee, said his panel has been trying to
change the appeals process since 1952.
   Standing in the way, he said, was a lack of consensus among
veterans' groups _ who are now in agreement.
   The House legislation would establish a new Court of Veterans
Appeals. As passed Monday, the House bill would abolish the
existing Board of Veterans' Appeals _ part of the VA and currently
the last resort for veterans unhappy with decisions to deny them
benefits.
   Edwards said the compromise would retain the board but make it
independent of the VA. The court would be established, but the
number of judges would decrease from the 65 envisioned in the House
bill to seven under the proposed compromise.
   Decisions of the new court could be appealed to the existing
U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit on any legal matter,
but not on factual findings.
   The legislation also would end a Civil War-era law that limits
attorney's fees for veterans' claims to $10 per claim _ making it
difficult for veterans to hire lawyers other than those provided by
the VA.
   The House bill would prohibit attorneys from charging any fee in
connection with an application for benefits. However, once the VA
denies a claim, a veteran could hire and pay a reasonable fee to a
lawyer.
   A copy of the fee agreement must be filed with the new court,
which could order a fee reduction if a judge finds the amount
excessive.
</TEXT>
