<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TreasuryBills     10-04 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields Mixed on Short-Term T-Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities were mixed at the government's latest auction.
   The Treasury Department on Monday sold $7.0 billion in
three-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.23 percent, the
same rate as last week. Another $7.0 billion was sold in six-month
bills at an average discount rate of 7.46 percent, down from 7.48
percent last week.
   The rates on six-month bills were the lowest since they sold for
7.34 percent on Sept. 19.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.47 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,817.20 and and 7.86 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,622.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 8.18 percent
last week after averaging 8.07 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
