<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush'sBack     10-04 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush's Back,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Iowa Recovery Gives Him Foothold in Upper Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush suffered his deepest
embarrassment at the very beginning of the campaign in a
humiliating third-place showing in the snows of Iowa, but
politicians of both parties concede he's rebounded and has become
competitive.
   ``It's a horse race now,'' said Iowa Republican Chairman Michael
Mahaffey, voicing a general consensus that the race with Democrat
Michael Dukakis is a virtual tossup in the state.
   ``George Bush is very highly competitive, there is no doubt in
my mind about that,'' said Democratic Sen. Tom Harkin.
   Dukakis is still favored in Iowa, Minnesota and Wisconsin in the
upper Midwest, according to an Associated Press survey of political
leaders, independent analysts and public opinion polls.
   But the degree to which Bush has gained momentum in Iowa is
remarkable in a state where GOP strategists only a couple of months
ago were publicly worrying that a Bush disaster would ripple down
the ticket and damage congressional and legislative candidates.
   His poor showing in the Feb. 8 precinct caucuses, coupled with a
drought-starved farm economy, caused Democratic glee and even
brought three campaign stops from Dukakis, though the state has
only eight electoral votes.
   The tenor has changed.
   ``Republicans are euphoric,'' said Larry Pope, a Drake
University law professor who maps GOP legislative election tactics.
``Our candidates' chances are improving because of Bush's chances.''
   From a more than 2-1 deficit in June, the latest poll published
by the Des Moines Register showed Bush trailing only 47 percent to
42 percent just after the Republican convention.
   That comeback caps a drive that began in the winter when Bush
was crushed by Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, and even ran behind
television evangelist Pat Robertson.
   Politicians offer a variety of reasons for Bush's resurgence,
with many reminding that Dukakis didn't fare all that well in the
precinct caucuses, either, running third behind Missouri Rep.
Richard Gephardt and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon.
   Bush, they argue, is no longer running against Midwesterner
Dole, but faces Easterner Dukakis.
   ``George Bush and the Republican Party are a pretty known
quantity and Mike Dukakis isn't,'' said George Wittgraf, who runs
Bush's efforts in the state.
   Others argued that the wounds are only now beginning to heal
among GOP activists who waged an intense and occasionally bitter
campaign. But Pope said Bush is recovering from the bashing
inflicted by the Democrats, not his fellow Republicans.
   Others argued that Bush suffered because his close attachment to
President Reagan, whose farm policies have drawn criticism in Iowa.
   ``Reagan is not popular in Iowa and Bush's attachment was a real
problem during the winter,'' Pope said. ``As Bush has developed his
own persona, he's gotten stronger in Iowa.''
   That strength is even more visible in the farm states of Kansas
and Nebraska, which borders on Iowa, according to the AP survey.
Democrats also concede Dukakis is probably slightly behind in
neighboring Missouri. Dukakis seems to be favored in the Dakotas.
   Democratic consultant Paulee Lipsman argued that the Bush forces
in Iowa were jolted into a new campaign style by their winter
surprise. ``They weren't going to make the same mistake twice,''
she said.
   Mahaffey, however, noted that Iowa hasn't backed a Democratic
presidential candidate since the 1964 Lyndon Johnson landslide.
   ``There is still some inclination of Iowans at the presidential
level to vote for Republicans,'' Mahaffey said. ``I don't want to
say it's a Republican state.''
</TEXT>
