<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-BlackLung     10-04 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Black Lung,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Hears Complaint On Miners' Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of American coal miners are not
compensated for black lung disease because the Labor Department
used an arbitrary cutoff in deciding who can get benefits, a lawyer
for the miners said.
   The denials were contrary to the intent of a 1977 federal law
intended to make it easier for miners to receive disability
payments, attorney Paul March Smith told the Supreme Court on
Monday.
   Smith asked the justices to uphold a March 1987 ruling in which
the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ordered the Labor Department
to review claims of some miners who were denied benefits in the
late 1970s and early 1980s.
   The order applied to black lung disease victims who had worked
less than 10 years in the mines and who had failed to exhaust
administrative remedies or had missed deadlines for filing court
appeals.
   Coal mine operators have said the appellate court ruling could
cost the industry $13.6 billion in additional payments if it is
applied nationwide.
   ``The government estimates that 94,000 cases could be
reviewed,'' Smith said. ``Not all of those would get black lung
payments. But it is in the several tens of thousands that would
benefit.''
   Miners afflicted with black lung disease or pneumoconiosis, a
lung disorder caused by breathing coal dust for a long period of
time, receive compensation for their disability through a special
fund administered by the federal government.
   Smith argued that Congress ordered the Labor Department in 1977
to come up with new criteria for determining eligibility for
benefits because too many claims were being denied and ordered it
to review, using the new standards, claims which it rejected
previously.
   Some longtime miners then received benefits, but Smith said the
department refused to approve claims for less experienced miners
unless they provided indisputable evidence that their disability
was caused by on-the-job exposure to coal dust.
   ``The reviews were meaningless,'' he said. ``If they didn't have
10 years in the mine, they were categorically excluded from
benefits. ... It was giving with the right hand and taking away
with the left.''
   Lawyers representing the federal government and mining companies
argued that no miners who deserve benefits are being denied black
lung disease payments.
   ``The Department of Labor ... delivered billions of dollars of
benefits to hundreds of thousands of claimants, many of whom do not
have black lung disease,'' said Mark E. Solomons, a lawyer for the
coal companies.
   Donald B. Ayer, the deputy solicitor general for the Justice
Department, said Congress wanted miners to get fair treatment but
it opposed payment of benefits unless the disability was proven
through a careful medical review.
   The Supreme Court is expected to announce a decision sometime
next year.
</TEXT>
