<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Chile Bjt   10-04 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile, Bjt,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worried Chileans Stock Up On Food Before Presidential Referendum</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chileans stocked up on foodstuffs,
candles, batteries and other basics before Wednesday's referendum
on right-wing Gen. August Pinochet's presidency, fearing that
violence may follow the vote.
   ``I know nothing and don't care about politics, but I don't want
to go hungry,'' said Delia Maluf, a middle-aged housewife at a
supermarket in Providencia, a fashionable residential neighborhood.
   Several supermarket managers reported a steep rise in buying in
recent days, but said the situation did not seem extreme.
   ``I'd call it worry buying, not panic buying,'' Alejandro Baeza,
manager of the Unimarc supermarket in the southern Santiago
middle-class neighborhood of La Florida, said.
   Shoppers were reported purchasing mostly non-perishable
foodstuffs, fearful they will be left without refrigerators since
blackouts are a common occurrence in Chile in times of political
tension.
   Candles, flashlights and batteries were in high demand, the
managers said. At least one manager reported his store had run out
of candles by the weekend.
   Opposition leaders and Roman Catholic Church sources said Monday
they are afraid that pro-government agents may provoke violence
during the referendum in which Pinochet seeks eight more years in
power.
   Several polls have put the opposition ahead of the former coup
leader.
   In Washington, U.S. State Department spokesperson Phyllis Oakley
expressed the Reagan administration's ``serious concern'' over the
alleged plans to call off the balloting.
   A 16-party opposition coalition said in a written statement that
it had evidence Pinochet supporters planned ``blackouts and clashes
with the people to interfere in the delivery of (voting) results.''
   Church officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also said
they learned of possible plans for violence in a bid to make the
vote's results invalid.
   In addition, the military government has repeatedly warned of
purported plans by Communists and other radical leftists to trigger
disruptions on the day of the vote. But it gave assurances it will
maintain order.
   The government has also stressed the acute food shortages that
occurred during the leftist government ousted by the military in
1973, hinting that a similar situation may develop in the event of
an opposition victory in referendum voting.
   In the referendum, 7.4 million registered voters are to vote
``yes'' or ``no'' on a proposal by the military commanders that
Pinochet remain in power until 1997.
   If a majority vote ``yes,'' the 72-year-old ruler will start a
new eight-year term next March. If most vote ``no,'' an open
presidential election will be called and he must hand power over to
the winner in March 1990.
   Several shoppers in Santiago supermarkets admitted they were
worried over what may happen and were doing some emergency buying
in the stores.
   Some shopkeepers said the date _ at the beginning of the month _
may also be a factor in increased shopping activity, since most
workers were just paid their salaries. But they acknowledged the
increase was well above previous months.
   Supermakets reported sales increased from 25 to 100 percent in
recent days.
   ``Sales in our stores have doubled since mid-last week,'' said
Ivan Jara, manager of Marmentini Letelier, a chain of low-price
supermarkets with five stories in middle- and working-class
neighborhoods.
   Marta Bueno, a mother of six buying at one supermarket, said,
``Im worried, you hear so many things. I'm especially worried about
the children.'' Among other supplies, she bought six two-kilogram
(4.4 pound) cans of powdered milk.
   Lautaro Alvarez, a 44-year-old computer specialist, said he was
making additional purchases ``because if things get ugly afterward,
I don't want my wife to go out in the street.''
   Several supermarket operators said they had to reorganize their
stocking schedules, but were having no supply problems.
   ``Suppliers are speeding up deliveries when necessary,'' said
Ricardo Ulloa, executive of one of Chile's largest supermarkets. He
said his sales have gone up by 30 percent ``during the last 10 days
or so.''
</TEXT>
