<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     10-04 0831</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Sizeable Price Increases Recorded in Wake of Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most food prices stayed fairly level this
summer despite the drought that hammered U.S. croplands, but
sizeable increases were recorded for a few products, according to
consumer advocates.
   ``Our survey suggests that in late July and early August there
was no extensive price gouging,'' Stephen Brobeck, executive
director of Consumer Federation of America, said in a statement
released Monday. But he said there were heavy increases in June.
   The group along with Washington-based Public Voice for Food
Health and Policy released initial results of price monitoring they
said was designed ``to try to head off drought-related price
gouging.''
   The Agriculture Department has been moving to ease concern about
possible steep price increases as a result of the dry spell.
Assistant Secretary Ewen M. Wilson has been estimating a 3 percent
to 5 percent increase in the food price index this year compared to
a forecast of 2 percent to 4 percent before the picture was altered
by the broiling sun and shortage of rainfall.
   For next year, the department has been forecasting
drought-related increases of perhaps 2 percent on top of an
expected rise of 2 percent to 4 percent in the consumer price index
for food.
   Some members of Congress have been skeptical. The General
Accounting Office has been monitoring food prices at the request of
Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., and Senate Agriculture Committee
Chairman Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.
   In unveiling the survey by the consumer groups, Ellen Haas,
executive director of Public Voice, said the ``first price checks
give us some reason to be concerned that some food prices may be
rising contrary to economic experts' opinions.''
   ``In particular, we question recent beef price increases and the
rapid increase in some wheat products,'' she said.
   Brobeck said ``the good news is that between July and August,
most surveyed prices stayed the same or declined.''
   ``The bad news is that 29 percent rose and typically these
increases were quite large,'' he said.
   In the survey, 14 Consumer Federation member groups monitored
prices at major supermarket chains in 16 areas of the country. The
organizations said that comparisons of two sets of prices revealed:
   _More beef prices rose than fell. Sirloin prices rose at 35
percent of the markets and declined at 25 percent of them. The
median increase was 14.1 cents a pound and the median decrease 9.0
cents. Economists say beef prices should have been falling because
skyrocketing feed prices accelerated the slaughter.
   _Milk and butter prices were raised more often than lowered in
the period, but the increases were in the range of 3 percent to 5
percent. ``Eighty percent of the stores in the sample did not
change their price of ice cream.''
   _Prices of some wheat products went up faster than expected as
did those for fresh fruits and vegetables. But median price
decreases for corn and broccoli were typically larger than
increases, even though more stores hiked them than reduced them.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's bankers are adding muscle to the
push for increased federal funding for rural development projects.
   ``Policies which encourage public and private investment in
rural America are a vital ingredient in rebuilding the economic
base of the farm community,'' American Bankers Association Murry
Lull told a recent hearing held by the congressional Joint Economic
Committee.
   Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.,
also has been talking up rural development and may attempt to move
legislation when lawmakers return to Capitol Hill next year.
   The Agriculture Department already pours substantial resources
into rural development and the idea of major new programs has
failed to catch fire in a time of budget retrenchment. But the
campaign for programs is building again.
   Lull, president of Smith County State Bank and Trust Co., Smith
Center, Kan., said banks ``must play a central role in this
investment process by providing credit to assist new businesses, to
encourage diversification in agricultural production and to fund
improvements in education and community infrastructure.''
   He suggested Congress consider guaranteeing loans to stimulate
rural growth and at the same time protect the nation's banks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The campaign for rural development and the
fall political campaign are scheduled to join forces Oct. 10 when
Under Secretary of Agriculture Roland R. Vautour holds a town
meeting on the issue in Columbus, Ohio.
   In announcing the event, the Agriculture Department said Rep.
Chalmers P. Wylie, R-Ohio, who is campaigning for reelection, ``is
scheduled to appear with Vautour.''
   It said the meeting is one in a series designed ``to elicit
views of local citizens on rural development issues.'' It said
Columbus was chosen as the site of the meeting ``because of its
proximity to a large number of rural communities in Ohio.''
   ``Town meetings are an excellent opportunity for me to hear
first-hand what rural Americans are doing to revitalize their local
economies,'' Vautour was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
