<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Listeners of radio station WHOS-AM may have
gone to sleep with the gospel song ``Beautiful Heaven,'' but they
woke up to ``The Devil In Disguise'' and nothing but other Elvis
Presley tunes.
   Gary Kaye said he and other station staff members were surprised
when general manager Mack Bramlett announced the immediate switch
to an all-Elvis format Monday morning. The format is similar to
that adopted recently by Cincinnati station WCVG-AM.
   ``It was just suddenly sprung on us,'' said Kaye, who was music
director under the old gospel format, but hasn't been assigned new
duties yet.
   Kaye said the 24-hour station had received favorable listener
response for its gospel music, but apparently that did not impress
advertisers.
   Bramlett was out of the office Monday and could not be reached
for comment.
   About a dozen callers Monday said they preferred the old format,
Kaye said, while more than two dozen said they liked the Elvis.
   ``For the first day, that isn't a bad response,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one is going to confuse Jim Turner
with presidential candidates George Bush and Michael Dukakis, and
Turner says that's a good thing.
   Turner portrays presidential hopeful Randee of the Redwoods on
MTV, which broadcasts music videos and other programs for cable
television subscribers.
   His slogan: ``Just Say Whoa!''
   ``I'm not a very serious candidate, and it's doubtful ... that I
will be president,'' Turner said, indicating that a Turner victory
would be a bad sign of the nation's sanity.
   The 35-year-old comedian entertained about 70 students Monday on
the steps of the Old Capitol on the University of Iowa campus.
   In a slap at GOP vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle, Turner
said he ``joined the Marines to avoid the National Guard.''
   Turner also copied Dukakis' practice of reminding voters he is
the son of immigrant parents, saying his mother ``came to America
via Greece, India, Pakistan and eventually parts of Nebraska.''
   Turner was asked the date of Pearl Harbor day, which Bush
mistakenly referred to as Sept. 7.
   ``Today. Tomorrow. Every day. You know, today is the first day
of the rest of the Pearl Harbor days of the rest of your life.
Think about that,'' Turner said.
</TEXT>
