<DOCNO> AP881004-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-German-Campaign     10-04 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-German-Campaign,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worried Germans Launch Campaign To Keep US-European Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germans concerned about Soviet popularity
among their fellow citizens have launched a campaign to convince
young people on both sides of the Atlantic of the value of
U.S.-West European ties.
   German-American efforts to bridge differences since World War II
and stand up to Soviet aggression in Europe have been ``an
unbelievable success story,'' Guenter Diehl, former Bonn government
spokesman and diplomat, told key members of Congress on Monday.
   However, Diehl said, younger Germans appear oblivious to the
importance of the accomplishments.
   ``Things that we have done are taken for granted,'' including
the establishment of freedom in much of Western Europe, he said.
   ``The United States is carrying a tremendous burden'' by
continuing to station 200,000 troops in Germany, said Johannes
Steinhoff, a decorated Luftwaffe fighter pilot during World War II
who subsequently served as an adviser to the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   Even though Europeans contribute to their own defense, U.S.
support is vital, Steinhoff said.
   Steinhoff said there is little appreciation among young people
for the daring and sacrifice of the American airlift that broke the
1948-49 Soviet attempt to cut off West Berlin from Western Europe.
   Diehl and Steinhoff, at a luncheon, announced a newspaper
advertising campaign in West Germany and the United States under
the slogan ``Friendship in Freedom.''
   The ads, featuring criticism of the Communist-built Berlin Wall
and praise for NATO for fostering peace and prosperity in Western
Europe, are aimed at both young people and at reassuring their
parents who may be suffering from doubts in the wake of Soviet
public-relations successes.
   The ads are to start Oct. 11.
   ``This initiative was founded by concerned citizens who, after
suffering dictatorship and war, came to experience the values of
friendship in a very personal way,'' said a statement from the
group.
   Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., chairman of the House Foreign Affairs
subcommittee on Europe, said he had been startled by public opinion
poll results from West Germany indicating widespread belief that
the Soviet Union, rather than the United States, was the peacemaker
in Europe.
   Polls in West Germany also show that Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev draws far more favorable ratings among the general public
than President Reagan.
   ``Gorby, as we like to call him, ... has been making a
disarmament proposals every two months'' and appealing to a natural
human desire for change, said Diehl.
   Gorbachev is following an old Soviet strategy of trying to
neutralize Germany, he said.
   But, Diehl said, the Soviets have problems in their public
relations because of the vast deployment their forces in East
Germany, estimated at 380,000 troops. No one believes the Soviet
claim that they are there to defend against an attack from the
West, he said.
   Among the founding members of ``Freundshaft in Freiheit''
(Friendship in Freedom) were Diehl, the chairman; department store
owner Alphons Horten, vice chairman, and banker Gernot Ernst,
treasurer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881004-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Murano     10-04 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Murano,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Congressman Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CEBU CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramon Durano, a former
congressman, business leader and one of the country's most colorful
politicians, has died of cancer, his family announced. He was 82.
   Durano, who died Monday, virtually owned Danao, a city of 60,000
north of Cebu. Many Danao residents were born in Durano's hospital,
worked in his factories, retired to his home for the elderly and
were buried in his cemetery.
   Durano was born Dec. 24, 1905 to a prosperous Cebu family. He
was elected to the House of Representatives from Cebu in 1949 and
served until President Ferdinand Marcos abolished the legislature
in 1972.
   In January, Durano was elected mayor of Danao, defeating his son
Thaddaeus in a bitter campaign.
   Durano was a longtime rival of the Osmena family, Cebu's other
major political dynasty. Election battles between the two clans
were often marked by violence and allegations of massive
vote-buying on all sides.
   In his autobiography, Durano described himself as a political
realist.
   ``I must say that like a determined boxer in the ring, a
politician must know how to defend himself, know his opponent's
weak and strong points and slug it out as expected of him,'' Durano
said.
   During his term in Congress, Durano was involved in at least
four fistfights with rivals on the House floor.
   He remained a devoted follower of Marcos, describing him in his
autobiography as the greatest leader the Philippines ever produced.
   He is survived by his wife Beatriz, three daughters and two sons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
