<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Durano     10-04 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Durano,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Congressman Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix slug.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CEBU CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramon Durano, a former
congressman, business leader and one of the country's most colorful
politicians, has died of cancer, his family announced. He was 82.
   Durano, who died Monday, virtually owned Danao, a city of 60,000
north of Cebu. Many Danao residents were born in Durano's hospital,
worked in his factories, retired to his home for the elderly and
were buried in his cemetery.
   Durano was born Dec. 24, 1905 to a prosperous Cebu family. He
was elected to the House of Representatives from Cebu in 1949 and
served until President Ferdinand Marcos abolished the legislature
in 1972.
   In January, Durano was elected mayor of Danao, defeating his son
Thaddaeus in a bitter campaign.
   Durano was a longtime rival of the Osmena family, Cebu's other
major political dynasty. Election battles between the two clans
were often marked by violence and allegations of massive
vote-buying on all sides.
   In his autobiography, Durano described himself as a political
realist.
   ``I must say that like a determined boxer in the ring, a
politician must know how to defend himself, know his opponent's
weak and strong points and slug it out as expected of him,'' Durano
said.
   During his term in Congress, Durano was involved in at least
four fistfights with rivals on the House floor.
   He remained a devoted follower of Marcos, describing him in his
autobiography as the greatest leader the Philippines ever produced.
   He is survived by his wife Beatriz, three daughters and two sons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
