<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-BBC     10-04 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-BBC,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BBC Delays TV Documentary On Anti-Terrorist Army Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British Broadcasting Corp. has delayed
transmission of a television documentary about Britain's elite
anti-terrorist army unit that was to have been aired Monday night.
   The film will be broadcast ``in the coming weeks'' after changes
are made, said a BBC spokesman.
   It was approved by eight senior executives and lawyers in the
BBC's news and current affairs team, but was withdrawn Saturday
night after BBC Director General Michael Checkland and his deputy,
John Birt, decided it needed more work, a BBC spokesman said.
   The documentary on the top-secret Special Air Services, or SAS,
was pegged to last month's inquest into the March 6 killings by SAS
commandos of three unarmed Irish Republican Army members in the
British colony of Gibraltar, the BBC said.
   The trio were on a car-bomb mission, and a Gibraltar coroner's
jury in Gibraltar ruled Friday that the killings were lawful.
   Checkland and Birt were ``happy with the themes the program
addresses but they feel more work is needed to prepare it for
transmission,'' said the spokesman, requesting anonymity. He would
not say what changes were envisaged.
   The program by ``Panorama,'' the BBC's premier current affairs
show, ``considers the issues raised by the Gibraltar inquest but
examines the accountability of the SAS primarily in Northern
Ireland,'' the spokesman said.
   The government has denied IRA claims that it operates an
officially sanctioned ``shoot-to-kill'' policy against IRA suspects.
   The program examined the rules of law and engagement of army and
SAS soldiers in Northern Ireland, and interviewed an SAS officer
who explains the soldier's dilemmas in facing a guerrilla.
</TEXT>
