<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TextileBill     10-04 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Textile Bill,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Textile Veto Headed for House Challenge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's veto of textile and apparel
import curbs is headed for a test of muscle in the House with bill
opponents and supporters both ready for a battle.
   ``We have the best chance that we've ever had'' for a veto
override, Rep. Butler Derrick, D-S.C., said Monday. But he added,
``I'm not sure'' textile forces have galvanized enough support in
the face of an energetic administration lobbying campaign.
   Bill supporters planned to initiate their override attempt today.
   Reagan described the bill as ``protectionism at its worst'' and
vetoed it on Sept. 28. Industry supporters are now attempting to
override that veto and pass the bill into law over the president's
objections.
   Designed to protect American industry from foreign competition,
the bill would freeze textile and apparel imports at 1987 levels
this year and limit growth to 1 percent annually thereafter.
   It also would freeze nonrubber footwear imports at 1987 levels
with no provision for growth later. It would guarantee higher
quotas to countries that buy American farm goods, establish a
one-year pilot program under which the government would auction off
import licenses and create a special quota for foreign-made silk
neckties.
   Textile forces would have to rally two-thirds of the lawmakers
present and voting to their side to be successful in their override
effort. If they succeeded in doing so in the House, they would then
have to repeat the accomplishment in the Senate.
   Reagan vetoed a similar measure in 1985 and the House the
following August was unable to muster the two-thirds needed to
override. Indeed, the industry has never been able to obtain such a
margin in years of skirmishing.
   Critics of the legislation say they are completely confident
there will be no override of the president's veto.
   ``I think it will be sustained,'' said Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla.,
the chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee's trade
subcommittee and one of the fiercest critics of the legislation.
   ``It's a lousy, stinking bill that we've voted on five times
already,'' Gibbons said in a telephone interview Monday night.
``It's a lousy, stinking piece of selfish economics.''
   He said the bill is being kept alive by ``a lobby that lives on
the myth that foreign competition is driving them out of business.''
   Sponsors of the measure point to a 17 percent growth in imports
since the start of the decade and add that the situation is getting
worse. They say 29,000 jobs were lost in the textile and apparel
industries last year while textile producers' earnings sank 12
percent in the first quarter of 1988.
   Opponents say the industry already is heavily protected by 1,400
quotas covering 42 countries and that earnings were up 9 percent
last year with 21,000 new jobs created in an industry that is just
emerging from a wave of modernization. They say import restraints
would merely trigger retaliation against U.S. exports while raising
prices and narrowing consumer choices.
   The final round of the long-running battle is being fought
against a backdrop of presidential and congressional elections in
the textile-producing areas of the South. It is punctuated by
warnings from some of the bill's sponsors that voters fearful of
losing textile industry jobs will exact a price at the polls for
the veto.
   In any case, Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., has already said
that if the override effort fails he will introduce a new version
of the import restrictions next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881004-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     10-04 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamil Militant Threats Prevent Filing Of Nominations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Threats from Tamil separatists have
succeeded in stopping anyone from filing nomination papers for
provincial elections in the northern and eastern provinces of Sri
Lanka, election officials said.
   In addition, six of the government's eight administrative
offices in the north and east did not function Monday after Tamil
militants threatened officials not to open offices, deputy
Elections Commissioner Lakshman Silva said.
   Tamil radicals shot and injured V.K. Sivagnanam, special
commissioner of the Jaffna Municipal Council, and killed two
civilians in Jaffna, 200 miles northeast of the capital Colombo, a
Tamil journalist said.
   He said the two Tamils died in clashes between rebel militant
groups in front of Jaffna hospital.
   Sivagnanam was attacked by members of the most militant Tamil
group, Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, when he was in his office,
the journalist said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Tamil militants have been waging a guerrilla war for an
independent state in the north and east of the island since 1983.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus and make up 18 percent of the
island's 16 million people, claim they are discriminated against by
the mostly Buddhist Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the
population and control the administration and military.
   Elections to provincial councils in the north and east of the
island, where Tamils are in a majority, form part of an
India-brokered peace agreement signed in July 1987 to end the
island's ethnic war.
   Tamil militants initially agreed but later reneged on terms of
the agreement.
   Monday was the first day for nominations to be filed to elect 71
representatives to the northern and eastern provincial councils.
Elections are scheduled for later this year.
   Election offices in northeast Trincomalee town and eastern
Ampara town were open Monday to receive nominations despite threats
from Tamil militants. Deputy Election Commissioner Silva said no
nominations were received.
</TEXT>
