<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     10-04 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Officials Say Veep Qualifications Not Debate Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic strategists say the public will
decide that Lloyd Bentsen is a better candidate than Republican Dan
Quayle even if he has trouble getting that across in Wednesday
night's vice presidential debate.
   ``Most people have already decided that Bentsen is more
qualified than Quayle. I don't really believe that's the issue of
this debate,'' said George Christian, former press secretary to
President Johnson and a long-time Bentsen adviser.
   Christian was one of about a dozen people prepping Bentsen
Monday at an Austin hotel for his meeting with Quayle. Bentsen
planned to travel to the debate city of Omaha, Neb., tonight.
   Bentsen was kept mostly away from reporters. His only public
appearance Monday came when he tossed around a football with some
former University of Texas stars at a picture session for the news
media.
   ``I think we're relaxed for it. I think we're ready for it,''
Bentsen said. Was he nervous? ``I'm not nervous,'' he said.
   His staff, while expressing great confidence in Bentsen, said he
was stuck with the burden of expectations for Quayle that are so
low, and Quayle is so telegenic, that Bentsen can't win.
   ``We have enormous confidence that while Dan Quayle has good
television skills ... when it comes to the judgement of which of
these two men, Lloyd Bentsen and Dan Quayle, and which of these two
tickets is best qualified'' Bentsen as the advantage, said Susan
Estrich, campaign manager for the Democratic ticket.
   ``Sure, I expect that Sen. Quayle will acquit himself reasonably
well in this debate format,'' Christian said. ``But I don't think
that's going to detract from the fact that Sen. Bentsen is far more
qualified by experience and judgment ... to be a better vice
president than Dan Quayle.''
   Campaign press secretary Mike McCurry expressed dissatisfaction
with what he said would be a low standard for measuring Quayle's
success.
   ``We'd hope the high bar would be set a little higher than being
passively coherent for 90 minutes,'' he said.
   Bentsen held a dress rehearsal for the debate on Monday, with
Rep. Dennis Eckart playing Quayle and staffers playing reporters.
He planned to work most of today, and part of Wednesday, reviewing
and working on strategy for the session, McCurry said.
   ``He's clearly very comfortable with the substance of his
answers,'' said McCurry.
   Estrich, McCurry and others said one of the biggest efforts was
to get Bentsen to boil down his statements to fit into the
restricting format of a television debate. But not a lot of time
was spent concocting ``one-liners,'' they said.
   ``I think one thing we found in the last debate, frankly, is
that the one-liners were not what made the difference for those
watching the debate,'' said Estrich.
 
</TEXT>
