<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Children     10-04 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Children,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prospects For Child Legislation Look Poor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospects appear bleak for enactment of a
legislative package promising parental job leaves, child care and a
crackdown on child pornographers, despite its survival of a
critical test in the Senate.
   Republicans loath to take responsibility for killing the
``children's agenda'' joined Democrats Monday in voting to allow
the Senate to proceed with action on the package.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, told his GOP colleagues they would
have other chances to halt the triple-barrelled package.
   ``Anyone who wants to stop the process can do so,'' he said.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas said drug abuse and
tax corrections bills are more urgent priorities for Congress to
complete before it adjourns in a week or two.
   But Dole added, ``I don't want tomorrow morning's headlines to
report that Republicans are frustrating the efforts of Democrats on
child care legislation ... or parental leave.''
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., sponsor of two of the three
parts of the package, said strengthening the family could help
lessen drug problems among children later in their lives. And he
described the tax bill as little more than a candy store filled
with corporate goodies.
   ``I'm a recipient of some of those goodies in my state, but
you'll never convince me that that bill is more important than
parental leave or child care,'' Dodd said.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said he was trying
to get an agreement for quick action on the children's package
despite a multitude of GOP amendments in the wings.
   The elements of the package include:
   _Dodd's parental and medical leave bill guaranteeing employees
of firms with more than 50 workers at least 10 weeks of unpaid,
job-protected leave on the birth, adoption or serious illness of a
child, or the serious illness of the employee. The U.S. Chamber of
Commerce and other business interests opposed to mandated benefits
are waging a fierce drive against the bill.
   _A child pornography and obscenity measure creating new crimes
and punishments in those areas in order to help prosecutors crack
down on people who sell, distribute, produce or possess such
materials. Sponsored by Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., it was added
to the Dodd measure 97-0 last week.
   _A $2.5 billion child care bill aimed at helping low-income
Americans pay for child care; expanding the supply of child care;
and assuring minimum standards of health, safety, staff training
and staff ratios at child care homes and centers. A compromise
reached by Hatch and Dodd, it would later include an increase in
the earned income tax credit for poor families.
   Once approved, the package would have to go the House. If the
House didn't pass the same version, negotiators would have to work
out the differences. But Byrd insisted there was still time for the
children's bills to clear the 100th Congress, due to adjourn this
weekend or next weekend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
