<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-What'sNext     10-04 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-What's Next,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlantis Next Up On The Launch Pad</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Discovery back from the first
post-Challenger mission, NASA is aiming to accelerate its launch
schedule to 14 flights by 1993, when it hopes to begin building a
space station.
   But the agency insists it will never again put schedules ahead
of safety.
   The Rogers Commission that investigated the Challenger explosion
in 1986 criticized NASA for putting too much pressure on itself to
meet a tight launch schedule and said that could lead to lapses in
safety.
   ``The shuttle missions are booked up to the horizon,'' shuttle
director Richard Truly said following Discovery's return to Earth
on Monday. ``Our job is to safely build the launch rate up so we
can meet that challenge.
   ``But if we find it's not safe to launch 14, we won't do it,''
he said.
   The next shuttle flight is set for late November, when Atlantis
will be launched on a secret Defense Department mission.
   Seven flights are planned next year, 10 in 1990, 9 in 1991 and
13 in 1992.
   Starting in 1993, the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration hopes to launch the first of 22 flights over four
years to carry up segments of a permanent manned space station.
   The schedules in 1992 and beyond will require a fourth shuttle
now being built to replace Challenger, destroyed in an explosion 32
months ago.
   Discovery's flight received intense worldwide attention because
it was the first post-Challenger mission. It will be far different
for the Atlantis liftoff in late November.
   Because the spacecraft will be carrying a classified Defense
Department payload, the Pentagon will try to shroud it in as much
secrecy as possible. But as officials learned on two earlier
military shuttle missions, it's difficult to do that when thousands
of people who are used to an open NASA policy work on a program
that is highly visible.
   Discovery will be returned here Sunday, ferried atop a Boeing
747 jetliner, to be readied for a flight scheduled for Feb. 18. It
will carry a Tracking and Data Relay Satellite identical to one
deployed from its cargo bay six hours after launch last Thursday.
   Here is the rest of NASA's schedule for 1989:
   April 28: Crew of Atlantis to dispatch the Magellan spacecraft
which is to orbit Venus and map its surface.
   July 1: Columbia on a classified Defense Department mission.
   Aug. 10: Discovery on a classified Defense Department mission.
   Oct. 12: Crew of Atlantis to dispatch the Galileo spacecraft to
orbit the planet Jupiter and drop a scientific probe into its
atmosphere.
   Nov. 13: Crew of Columbia to deploy a communications satellite
and retrieve for return to Earth a research satellite placed in
orbit on a 1984 shuttle mission.
   Dec. 11: Discovery on a classified Defense Department mission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
