<HEAD>Deaver Files Appeal of Conviction for Lying to Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential aide Michael K. Deaver has
filed a formal appeal of his conviction that he lied under oath
when questioned by a grand jury and a House subcommittee about his
lobbying activities.
   The former deputy White House chief of staff was given a
suspended three-year sentence and a $100,000 fine last month by
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson.
   The judge also ordered Deaver to perform 1,500 hours of
community service and barred him from lobbying the federal
government for pay during a three-year period the former White
House aide was placed on probation.
   The formal notice of appeal, signed by Deaver and his lawyer,
Herbert J. Miller Jr., was filed Monday in U.S. District Court.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Most Americans Favor More Fuel-Efficient Cars, Poll Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two-thirds of Americans believe they will see
another energy crisis that will bring back gasoline lines, but
nearly 75 percent oppose a gasoline tax increase to discourage
consumption, according to a poll commissioned by environmentalists.
   The survey released Monday also found that 90 percent of
Americans believe the government should require automakers to build
cars that are more fuel-efficient.
   When asked if cars should be required to average 45 miles per
gallon in the year 2000, a position some environmental groups have
endorsed, the poll respondents split 82-15 in favor.
   The Analysis Group Inc., a New Haven, Conn.-based polling firm,
telephoned 1,000 registered voters from Sept. 10-14 for The
Communications Consortium, a public relations firm representing
environmental groups. The margin of error in the poll is about
three percentage points.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Many Pesticides Undetected in Food Supply, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A research arm of Congress says federal
agencies charged with checking the nation's food supply can't
detect half the pesticides permitted to be used.
   The Office of Technology Assessment reported Monday that the
government's testing methods can only detect 163 of the 316 active
pesticide ingredients that are allowed in limited quantities.
   Diane Baxter, staff scientist for the National Coalition Against
the Misuse of Pesticides, said the lack of coverage in routine
monitoring ``worries us very much.''
   Food is checked by the Food Safety Inspection Service of the
Agriculture Department, which analyzes meat and poultry; the
department's Agricultural Marketing Service, which analyzes eggs;
and the Food and Drug Administration, part of the Health and Human
Services Department, which analyzes all other foods.
</TEXT>
