<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Working For Strikers In Nagorno-Karabakh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers of the Interior Ministry are delivering
food, repairing buildings and working fields in Nagorno-Karabakh,
where Armenians remain on strike to press ethnic demands, Tass
reported.
   In a Monday dispatch, the news agency said industrial
enterprises are closed. Public transportation and freight hauling
also remain shut down with the exception of a few taxi services, it
said.
   The soldiers ``deliver foodstuffs to Stepanakert and rural areas
of the region, protect water intake facilities, repair and
modernize the premises in which they have been temporarily
quartered,'' it said.
   ``Besides, at farmers' request soldiers help a number of farms
with agricultural work,'' the dispatch said.
   Tass said the strike continuted to paralyze Stepanakert, the
major city of Nagorno-Karabakh, but that farm work was being done
in rural areas.
   Nagorno-Karabakh, a predominantly Armenian region, is part of
the Soviet republic of Azerbaijan but residents have been agitating
since February for annexation by the neighboring Armenian republic.
   Armenia has supported the demands, but Azerbaijan and the
central government have rejected them.
   Shooting incidents, arson and other acts of violence that broke
out in Nagorno-Karabakh on Sept. 18 led to deployment of the
soldiers, a curfew and a ban on public meetings.
   Thirty-two people were killed in ethnic rioting in the
Azerbaijani city of Sumgait at the end of February and beginning of
March.
</TEXT>
