<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-04 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar And Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost ground against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices edged down on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 133.15 yen, down 0.75 yen from Monday's
close of 133.90 yen. After opening at 133.37 yen, the U.S. currency
ranged between 133.00 and 133.43 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost another 44.51 points or
0.16 percent, following Monday's 154.60-point loss, to close at
27,501.02. The index lost 134.42 points at the end of the morning
session but recovered somewhat in the afternoon.
   ``The Dow Jones' lower close overnight (in New York) initially
set the tone of the Tokyo trading,'' said an analyst with Nomura
Securities.
   Despite good economic factors around the market that should
increase share prices, the Nikkei remained lower due to ``shrinking
investment motivation,'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   ``The gloomy atmosphere all over Japan has made participants
pessimistic,'' the dealer said, referring to Japanese Emperor
Hirohito's serious illness.
   Other dealers said the index began recovering as participants
bought steels, but uncertainty remained in the market before the
release of U.S. unemployment figures that encouraged participants
to stay on the sidelines.
   The U.S. unemployment rate for September is to come out Friday.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 950 million
shares.
   ``The dollar fell in trading that was dominated by
dollar-selling,'' said Mitsuhiko Kinugasa with the Daiwa Bank in
Tokyo.
   ``Institutional investors did not buy as much dollars as we
thought, and the currency kept falling,'' he said, adding that
market participants also became cautious as the release of the U.S.
unemployment figures approaches.
</TEXT>
