<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Savimbi     10-04 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Savimbi,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebel Leader Offers Cease-Fire, Prisoner Swap With Cubans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi offered to halt
armed attacks on the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops in Angola if
Cuba ceased hostilities against his forces, the British
Broadcasting Corp. reported.
   Savimbi, head of the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola, or UNITA, also proposed a swap of Cuban and UNITA
prisoners taken in the rebels' 13-year-old civil war against the
Marxist government in Luanda, according to a UNITA press statement
reported by the BBC on Monday.
   The statement quoted from a radio broadcast in which Savimbi
urged Cuba to pressure the Angolan government to negotiate directly
with the rebels ``for the formation of a government of national
unity in Angola.''
   Savimbi, whose South African military allies withdrew from
Angola last month as part of a U.S.-sponsored regional peace
settlement, has said he fears a Cuban-Angolan offensive will
destroy his strongholds in the southeastern portion of the country.
   ``It would be bad if Cuban troops, who came to Angola under the
pretext of being internationalists, are one day branded as
colonialists ... who came to replace the Portuguese to kill
defenseless Angolans,'' the BBC quoted Savimbi as saying.
   The Angolan government took power with Cuban assistance after
Portugal withdrew from the country in the mid-1970s. It has since
refused to talk with the UNITA rebels.
   UNITA, backed by South Africa and the United States, is not
party to peace talks in Brazzaville, Congo, among Angola, South
Africa and Cuba.
   Pretoria has called on Cuba to join it in a total troop
withdrawal and has held out the promise of independence for
Namibia, or South West Africa, which South Africa has ruled since
World War I. The Angolan government has insisted that the Cubans
remain for four years.
   ``A revolutionary government such as that of Cuba cannot say
that its forces are in Angola to fight against South African troops
... when the South Africans are no longer in Angola,'' the BBC
quoted Savimbi as saying.
</TEXT>
