<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-India     10-04 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-India,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Delegation Arrives to Discuss Summit, Bilateral Issues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian Foreign Secretary K.P.S. Menon arrived
today for talks expected to pave the way for the first Sino-Indian
summit in 28 years.
   Indian Embassy officials, speaking on condition of anonymity
said bilateral issues, including a proposed visit by Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi, will be on the agenda during Menon's five-day stay in
Beijing.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency, in an earlier report from
New Delhi, said Gandhi would come to China before the end of the
year.
   Relations between the world's two most populous nations have
long been cool because of India's pro-Soviet slant, China's close
ties with Indian rival Pakistan and an unresolved border dispute.
   The disagreement over large tracts of mountainous, sparsely
populated land along the 2,400-mile border erupted into fighting in
1962 and has been a primary source of strain since.
   Border talks begun in 1981 have been largely fruitless, but the
two sides now appear ready to play down the territorial issue in
the interest of better all-round relations.
   ``The Chinese have toned down their public comment'' on the
border dispute, one Indian official said. ``We have seen improving
relations in the past year.''
   The late Premier Chou En-lai was the last Chinese head of
government to visit New Delhi in 1960. No Indian prime minister has
visited Beijing since the late Jawaharlal Nehru in 1954.
</TEXT>
