<HEAD>Haitian Hijackers Arraigned on Air Piracy Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Haitian soldiers who stormed aboard an
American Airlines jetliner bound for New York were ordered held
without bail after their arraignment before a U.S. magistrate on
air piracy charges.
   The three, who appeared before the judge Monday, plan to seek
political asylum in the United States, according to their
court-appointed lawyers.
   A complaint filed by the U.S. Attorney's office accused Nicolas
Normil, 23, Jean Charleston Bienaime, 23, and Edouine Noel, 24, of
boarding the flight in Port-au-Prince on Saturday and demanding
they be taken to the United States.
   Each was carrying a loaded automatic assault rifle that they
surrendered once the plane was airborne, said the complaint. No
injuries were reported.
   Saturday's incident occurred during a period of political
turmoil in Haiti, and defense lawyers said the three fled the
country because they feared for their lives.
   The air piracy charges carry 20-year sentences.
