<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Killings,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Deaths Reported In Riot-Torn Pakistani City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IQBAL JAFFERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HYDERABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have rounded up about 150
people as they investigate bloody ethnic-related shooting sprees
that began Friday in Hyderabad and spread to Karachi, a newspaper
reported today.
   More than 215 died people died in Hyderabad and Karachi, 100
miles to the southwest, during five days of bloody clashes between
Indian immigrants called Mohajirs and Sindhi separatists seeking
independence for the southern province of Sind.
   The official Pakistan Times newspaper said foreigners were
included among those arrested. They were not identified.
   Meanwhile, the death toll in the violence continued to creep up
today as police said eight people were killed during a curfew break
the day before.
   There were no immediate reports of renewed shooting when police
allowed people out of their homes for two hours this morning.
   President Ghulam Ishaq Khan ordered police roadblocks around
Hyderabad, where more than 160 people died and Karachi, Pakistan's
largest city, where more than 50 died.
   Ishaq Khan, after a visit Monday to both cities, said the
24-hour roadblocks were being set up to put a lid on further
violence as well as search out suspects in the recent killings.
   The army, which has been patrolling the cities in armored
personnel carriers, will back up police at the roadblocks, he said.
   The president also called for a legislative overhaul that would
lead to greater gun control, according to the official news agency,
APP.
   Both Hyderabad and Karachi, with eight million people, have been
the scene of violent ethnic clashes between Indian immigrants and
Sindhi separatists.
   The militant Sindhis are members of the Jeay Sind Movement.
   The Mohajirs, who comprise more than 40 percent of the
provincial population, have formed the Mohajir Quami Movement to
seek recognition as a fifth nationality in addition to the Sindhis,
Punjabis, Baluchis and Pathans.
</TEXT>
