<HEAD>Scandinavian Airline Makes Deal With U.S. Carrier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Scandinavian Airlines System, SAS,
has concluded a cooperation deal with a major U.S. carrier, company
officials said.
   Reports here and in Cophenhagen on Monday identified the U.S.
company as the Houston-based Texas Air, which owns Eastern Airlines
and Continental Airlines.
   Details about the deal will be announced at a news conference at
New York's Plaza Hotel later today, SAS information director Knut
Lovstuhagen said, refusing to confirm the reports.
   The spokesman said only that the deal was ``extensive.'' A trade
source who declined to be identified said the agreement covers
Atlantic routes and U.S. domestic routes to which SAS has long
sought access, probably including landing rights in Miami.
   The Scandinavian flag carrier, which is 50 percent owned by the
governments of Sweden, Denmark and Norway, has tried to develop a
``global axis'' strategy.
   But negotiations on several other deals fell through last year,
including talks with the Belgian national carrier SABENA, with
British Caledonian and with Aerolinas Argentinas.
