<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was slightly lower in thin European
trading this morning and dealers said it was likely to remain
steady during the week.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   Foreign currency traders said they were waiting for Friday's
scheduled release of U.S. unemployment figures for September.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.75 yen to a closing 133.15. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 133.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8599 West German marks, down from 1.8608
   _1.5780 Swiss francs, down from 1.5785
   _6.3340 French francs, down from 6.3350
   _2.0977 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1010
   _1,386.50 Italian lire, down from 1,397.95
   _$1.2096 Canadian, down from $1.2104
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6955, slightly cheaper for
buyers than late Monday's $1.6990.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price
for gold of $397.35 a troy ounce at midmorning, unchanged from late
Monday's bid price.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $397.00, down slightly from $397.75
bid late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $4.32 to close at a bid $402.23.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.22 a troy
ounce, unchanged from late Monday.
