<2ND_LINE>PM-Florida Primary,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters To Choose Democratic Senate Nomination</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls open at 7 a.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Longtime rivals Bill Gunter and Rep.
Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay vied today for the Democratic nomination
to succeed Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., who is leaving the Senate
after three terms.
   Florida Republicans were picking three congressional candidates.
   The winner of the bitterly contested Democratic Senate runoff
will meet Republican Connie Mack III in the Nov. 8 general election.
   Both MacKay and Gunter men say the race is close, an assessment
reinforced by a newspaper poll last week showing MacKay with a
slight lead heading into the final week.
   But the close race was not expected to pack voting booths.
   Dot Joyce, of the Florida Division of Elections, predicted an
overall voter turnout of 25 percent.
   The election was Gunter's third try at the Senate and the second
for MacKay, who is in his third congressional term.
   Gunter, Florida's insurance commissioner since 1976,
unsuccessfully sought his party's nomination in 1974, but won the
Democratic primary and runoff in 1980 before losing to Republican
Paula Hawkins in the general election. Gunter, 54, defeated MacKay,
55, in the 1980 party battle.
   Voters also were chosing party candidates to run for a variety
of other posts, including insurance commissioner, secretary of
state, and federal and state House seats.
   L.A. ``Skip'' Bafalis and former Lee County Commissioner Porter
Goss sought the GOP nomination in the 14th Congressional District,
where Mack vacated the seat once held by Bafalis to run for the
Senate.
   The GOP runoff victor faces Democrat Jack Conway, a retiree who
was the first national president of the government watchdog group
Common Cause.
   Clifford Stearns, a hotel and restaurant operator, met Jim
Cherry, former head of the state Farmers Home Administration, in
the 6th District GOP race.
   The winner faces Democratic state legislative veteran Jon Mills
in the general election to succeed MacKay.
   In the 11th District, Republicans chose between Bill Tolley or
Rod Borum to challenge five-term incumbent Bill Nelson, who already
plans to run for the Democratic gubernatorial nomination in 1990.
</TEXT>
