<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hirohito 1stLd-Writethru   10-04 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0445,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Discharges More Blood But Condition Remains Stable</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with another blood transfusion,
details. No pickup. Changes byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito was given another blood
transfusion today to combat internal hemorrhaging but remained in
stable condition and was feeling well, an imperial spokesman said.
   The 87-year-old Hirohito, who fell ill Sept. 19 after internal
bleeding caused him to vomit blood, received a 0.4 pints of blood
this afternoon after he discharged a small amount of blood Monday
night, said Iwao Miyao, vice grand steward of the Imperial
Household Agency.
   Miyao added that the world's longest-reigning monarch remained
in serious but stable condition and managed to watch a 15-minute
daily television drama series in the afternoon.
   Crown Prince Akihito, the emperor's son, and his wife Princess
Michiko were among the many family members who visited the ailing
monarch at his bedside in his official residence, the Fukiage
Palace.
   Hirohito has been bedridden and under intensive care by palace
physicians since his internal hemorrhaging began. He is being fed
intravenously and has not been able to eat solid food except for
two small ice cubes and a few spoonfuls of porridge in recent days.
   News reports said physicians were trying to increase the flow of
intravenous nutrients, including glucose and protein, to combat
Hirohito's frailty.
   With today's transfusion, the emperor has received 10.92 pints
of blood since the onset of the crisis.
   Many reports also have said Hirohito has pancreatic cancer, but
palace officials have neither confirmed nor denied the reports.
   Nearly 4 million people have thronged to the palace from around
the country to wish the emperor a speedy recovery. Scores of
festivals, events and even state visits by foreign dignitaries have
been canceled. Cabinet ministers have also scrapped plans for
overseas trips in deference to the emperor.
   Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno said today Japan may request South
Korean President Roh Tae-woo to postpone a scheduled visit next
month, a ministry official said.
   Under the Constitution, the emperor is a symbol of the state
with little real power. His duties, which include receiving foreign
dignitaries and placing official seals on government documents,
have been taken over by the 54-year-old Akihito.
</TEXT>
