<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0713EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-Bomb     10-04 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Bomb,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Bombs Explode, German Group Claims Responsibility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOLZANO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two powerful bombs exploded early today in
this province troubled by ethnic tensions, damaging windows and
parked cars and demolishing a railroad pylon, police said. No
injuries were reported.
   Ein Tyrol, a German-speaking extremist group seeking to reunite
the Alto Adige province with Austria, claimed responsibility in a
leaflet, officials said.
   The first bomb went off around 4:15 a.m. in front of a railroad
workers' residence in Chiusa, 18 miles from Bolzano, the provincial
capital.
   A second bomb went off an hour later about three miles away,
knocking down a pylon supporting an electrical line for the state
railroad.
   A series of bombings in recent months have plagued this
province, which was stripped from Austria at the end of World War
I. The violence stems from tensions between the 300,000 German
speakers and the 125,000 Italian speakers in the region.
   Terrorists have attacked residences of railroad workers in the
past. Most state jobs in the area are held by Italian speakers.
   The leaflet found at the site of the first blast threatened
further attacks and ``special treatment'' for ``Italian
parasites,'' police said.
   The Alto Adige is officially bilingual and legislation enacted a
few years ago gives the German speakers the upper hand in gaining
jobs and housing.
   During World War II, dictator Benito Mussolini lured workers
from all over Italy to the region north of Venice with promises of
better conditions.
</TEXT>
