<HEAD>Troops Wound 22, Hospital Officials Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with violence today, schools
reopening, Shamir pledge to expand settlements. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian accused of collaborating with the
Israeli authorities shot and seriously wounded another Arab today
in the occupied West Bank, Arab hospital officials and witnesses
said.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir vowed at an election rally in the
West Bank to expand Jewish settlements throughout the occupied
territories, an Israeli newspaper reported.
   In Arab east Jerusalem, about 3,000 students returned to their
fifth- and sixth-grade classrooms after a four-month closure aimed
at preventing anti-Israeli activism in the schools.
   Officials at Nablus' Rafidiyah Hospital said Mufeed Nueirat, 26,
was shot twice in the face and shoulder by another Arab acused of
cooperating with Israel.
   The army said it was checking the report.
   Palestinian witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the shooting in the West Bank village of Maythaloon, about 55 miles
north of Jerusalem, was apparently the result of a feud between the
two Arabs.
   The witnesses said Nueirat was shot with an Israeli-made Uzi
submachine gun. Palestinians who cooperate with Israel are assigned
such weapons for self defense.
   In leaflets circulated last month, uprising leaders ordered
Palestinians to attack and kill all suspected collaborators. Seven
Arabs accused of cooperating with Israel have been killed since the
uprising began on Dec. 8.
   Since Dec. 8, at least 280 Palestinians and six Israelis have
been killed.
   Mithkal Natour, director of Jerusalem's Arab education board,
said the opening of schools followed last week's successful return
to classes of students in the first through fourth grades. ``There
have been no problems and we expect no violence,'' Natour said.
   Secondary schools in Jerusalem as well as more than 800 schools
and universities attended by about 300,000 students in the West
Bank remain closed as part of an army effort to prevent violence.
   In the Gaza Strip, elementary schools are open but all 27 high
schools have been closed.
   Palestinians protested the extended closures throughout the
occupied lands Monday. The Arab schools were to have remained open
throughout summer to make up for lost school time, but were closed
by Israeli authorities in June.
   The Jerusalem Post reported today that at an election rally in
the Jewish settlement of Ariel, Shamir vowed his Likud Party would
increase Jewish settlements throughout the West Bank.
   Only six Jewish settlements have been built since the formation
in 1984 of the coalition government of Shamir's right-wing Likud
bloc and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres' left-of-center Labor Party.
   According to Housing Ministry figures, the 131 existing
settlements have been expanded since 1984 at a rate of 1,500
housing units a year.
   About 65,000 Israelis live in the occupied territories along
with 1.5 million Palestinians. Israel captured the West Bank from
Jordan and the Gaza Strip from Egypt during the 1967 Middle East
war.
   On Monday, Israeli troops shot and wounded 22 Palestinians in a
sweep of more than a dozen West Bank villages, according to Arab
hospital officials.
   The army confirmed that 11 Palestinians were wounded in violence
Monday, and troops imposed or extended curfews on eight refugee
camps and areas in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, confining more
than 150,000 Palestinians to their homes.
</TEXT>
