<HEAD>New Company Policy Forbidding Employees to Wear Beards Draws
Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COVENTRY, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union officials at a chemical plant are
objecting to a new policy requiring workers who wear respirators to
shave their beards.
   ``I think it's terrible,'' said Robert Ellis, Teamsters Local 64
steward at the American Hoechst Celanese Corp. chemical plant, who
said the policy intruded into workers' personal lives.
   Three employees with beards were suspended since the policy went
into effect Saturday, but were reinstated Monday after agreeing to
shave, said David Velmosky, the company's manager of human
resources. More than 90 percent of those with beards have shaved
them off, Velmosky said, although he wasn't sure how many people
that was.
   The policy is based on a U.S. Occupational Safety and Health
Administration standard, plant officials said.
   ``If you have a beard, it's going to be very difficult if not
impossible to get a good seal,'' said Fred Joseph, OSHA industrial
hygiene supervisor.
   American Hoechst Celanese employs 756 people in Coventry, 400 of
them union members.
