<HEAD>Toddler Reunited With His Mother In Austria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomats and Red Cross officials
reunited a 2{-year-old Romanian boy with his pregnant mother, who
had fled the Soviet bloc to seek political asylum in Austria.
   The toddler, separated from his mother for the past four weeks,
was picked up in Budapest, Hungary, by a car of the Austrian Red
Cross and taken to Styria province Monday, where his mother is
staying at a boarding house, the Austria Press Agency reported.
   No names or details of the Romanian woman's escape were
disclosed by authorities. They also would not say how the woman and
her son were separated.
   The woman, who is in her seventh month of pregnancy, was
completely surprised by the arrival of her son, because she had not
been told by officials of the project in order avoid emotional
strain. The boy had been in a Budapest child care center.
   The Austrian Interior Ministry quickly granted an entry visa for
the Romanian boy, although his mother's request for asylum has not
yet been acted upon, the news agency said.
   The action was possible with the cooperation of the Austrian
Embassy in Budapest and the Hungarian mission in Vienna as well as
the two countries' Red Cross societies.
