<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ForestFires     10-04 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forest Fires,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Loggers Rescued From Oregon Fire, Yellowstone Calming Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helicopters had to be used to rescue
loggers threatened by a forest fire burning in the hills of
west-central Oregon, a spokesman for the state Department of
Forestry said.
   Elsewhere, fires that have charred about 1.6 million acres in
and around Yellowstone National Park still are not fully contained
by fire lines. But a 12,000-acre arson fire that destroyed one
house in the San Bernardino Mountains east of Los Angeles has been
contained, fire officials said.
   Oregon forestry spokesman Doug Decker said he was unsure how
many loggers were rescued from the Marten Ridge Fire, which had
burned 120 acres east of Springfield by late Monday. There were no
injuries but a new log loading machine was destroyed, he said.
   He said helicopters would resume dropping water and retardant
today.
   The fire started Monday on an active logging operation on
Weyerhauser Co. land about 28 miles east of Springfield, Decker
said. The cause was under investigation.
   No changes have been reported in days on the fires in
Yellowstone, but fire managers do not want to predict when they
might be able to call the blazes completely contained, much less
controlled.
   Crews continue to be released from the fire lines, said park
spokeswoman Sandi Robinson. She had no figures on how many
firefighters remain in the park.
   Park officials are growing concerned about the spread of a
noxious weed made possible by the flames that have opened up dense
forest, said Jim Sweaney, western district resource management
coordinator in the park. The plant, spotted knapweed, can choke out
other plants.
   ``There are a lot of areas where sunlight is hitting the ground
for the first time in 100 years,'' he said.
   Near Rancho Cucamonga, Calif., a 12,000-acre fire in the San
Bernardino Mountains that has cost nearly $2 million to fight has
been contained, but fire officials said they don't expect to
extinguish it until Thursday.
   ``It's really important we get all of the hot spots because the
wind could pick up a spark,'' U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman
Lindsay Maierhofer said.
   The fire, set by an arsonist Wednesday, was fanned last week by
gusty Santa Ana wind blowing at up to 60 mph. The fire closed
nearby Interstate 15 for a time and forced hundreds of people to
evacuate homes.
   One ranch home was destroyed. Property losses totaled about
$250,000, officials said.
</TEXT>
