<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ProducerMurder     10-04 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Producer Murder,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four People Charged in 5-Year-Old Slaying of Producer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men and a woman have been charged in
the 1983 killing of New York theatrical producer Roy Radin, who
authorities said was embroiled in a soured finance deal for the
movie ``The Cotton Club.''
   Deputy District Attorney David Conn said the murder was a
contract killing and that movie producer Robert Evans, whose
credits include ``Chinatown'' and ``The Marathon Man,'' was a key
figure in the film's financial negotiations.
   The prosecutor said Evans' testimony ``is going to become
important at some point'' and his participation in the deal remains
under investigation. However, Sheriff's Homicide Capt. Robert Grimm
stressed that Evans is not a suspect in Radin's death.
   Charged with Radin's May 13, 1983, murder were Karen De Layne
Greenberger, described by one sheriff's spokesman as a former
cocaine dealer, and William Molony Mentzer. Also charged were Alex
Lamota Marti and Robert Ulmer Lowe. The complaint alleged they
killed Radin ``for financial gain.''
   The complaint alleged special aggravating circumstances, which
could result in the death penalty if the defendants are convicted.
   At the time of Radin's death, there were rumors the slaying was
linked to cocaine, but Conn said Monday, ``That will not be the
subject of our prosecution.''
   Conn alleged the Radin slaying resulted from a dispute between
Radin and Ms. Greenberger about a plan to raise $35 million from
investors in the Puerto Rican government for production of the
``The Cotton Club.''
   The 1984 film about a Harlem speakeasy, starring Richard Gere,
reportedly cost $47 million to produce, and was met with generally
lukewarm reviews.
   The prosecutor said Radin was introduced to Evans by Ms.
Greenberger, and Radin became a middleman in the Puerto Rican
negotiations. But a dispute developed between Radin and the woman
over a finder's fee she demanded, Conn said.
   On May 13, 1983, he said Radin stepped into a limousine rented
by Ms. Greenberger ``with the intention of going to a restaurant
and discussing the business arrangement further. He never arrived
at the restaurant.''
   On June 10, a forest ranger discovered Radin's body in a stream
bed at the end of a road in a rural part of Los Angeles County,
about 65 miles north of Los Angeles. He had been shot in the back
of the head.
   The complaint, based on new evidence, was issued Sept. 22 but
was sealed for fear of the safety of an informant who has since
been relocated, Conn said.
</TEXT>
