<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Tyson 1stLd-Writethru a0490 10-04 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Tyson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tyson Manager Says Champ To Undergo Another Psychiatric
Examination</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 7th graf, `Tyson's fit ...,' to add
background on Givens' quote during interview with ABC. Picks up 8th
graf, `Tyson was ...' A version also moving sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavyweight boxing champion Mike Tyson will
undergo another psychiatric examination following a weekend rampage
that left glass strewn around his New Jersey mansion, according to
a report published today.
   ``Mike is back on track,'' manager Bill Cayton said in an
interview published in New York Newsday.
   Cayton said Tyson, 22, would visit ``a world-renowned
psychiatrist'' today to get a second opinion on a diagnosis the
boxer is manic-depressive.
   He said Tyson did not mention Sunday's incident, in which the
boxer reportedly hurled a sugar bowl, an andiron, and chairs
through windows of his Bernardsville, N.J., mansion.
   Cayton, who has had a rocky relationship with Tyson since the
champion's marriage to actress Robin Givens eight months ago, said
Tyson came to his office around Monday along with welterweight Mark
Breland before heading to Breland's Long Island training camp.
   ``When he got here, he came bounding up the stairs and gave me a
really big hug,'' Cayton said. ``He was very warm. Very friendly.
... It was like old times. Mike is going to be OK,'' Cayton said.
   Tyson's fit of anger was sparked by interviews given to Barbara
Walters by his wife and her mother, Ruth Roper, that were broadcast
Friday on ABC's ``20-20,'' according to the Daily News and New York
Post.
   Givens, with Tyson seated next to her, had told Walters she was
``very, very much afraid'' of the boxer because of his ``extremely
volatile temper.''
   Tyson was also angry that Givens was going to California to
begin filming her TV series, ``Head of the Class,'' the News today
quoted an unidentified friend as saying.
   Givens was in California Monday with her mother. Givens is
expected to spend five days a week on the set until April,
according to Warner Bros.
   Tyson refused to say what triggered his tirade, but told the
News, ``I'm going through a difficult time right now. It doesn't
look good. ... I'm hurt because I'm in love. I'm still in love.''
   Police said that they handled Sunday's incident like any other
such case and that, as far as they were concerned, the matter was
closed.
   ``This is a domestic violence incident not unlike many others,
except for the fact that it involves a public figure,''
Bernardsville police Chief Thomas J. Sciaretta told a news
conference Monday.
   Sciaretta, revealing few details, said no one was injured or
arrested and that Givens did not want to sign a domestic violence
complaint.
   The chief said Tyson ``has done nothing wrong. It's his home.
He's entitled to do anything he pleases provided no one is
injured.''
   ``I took it (an andiron) from the fireplace and threw it through
the window,'' Tyson told the News in an interview from Breland's
gym in Queens. ``So what? I paid for it. It's my house.''
   Cayton said Tyson wants to go ahead with his twice-postponed
title defense against Frank Bruno of Britain, which is scheduled
for December.
   Last month, Tyson crashed his car and was knocked unconscious,
forcing the postponement of a boxing match and sparking news
reports that the boxer threatened to kill himself prior to the
accident. In August, Tyson broke a bone in his hand during a street
fight with boxer Mitch Green.
   After the car accident, Tyson was evaluated by a psychiatrist at
the urging of Givens and Roper. He was diagnosed as a
manic-depressive and lithium carbonate was prescribed.
</TEXT>
