<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hamadi 3rdLd-Writethru a0537 10-04 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0537,a0529,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Testifies That Stethem Lived 10 Minutes After Shooting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs with testimony from Navy diver, other
details; PICKS up 12th graf pvs, `Flight 847's ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Navy diver testified today
he feared confessed hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi was about to shoot
him before a flight attendent intervened.
   ``He (Hamadi) had a chrome-plated automatic pistol in his hand.
He pointed it directly in my face and pulled back the hammer,''
Tony Daniel Watson told Hamadi's air piracy and murder trial.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is accused in the June 1985
hijacking of a TWA jetliner in which Navy diver Robert Stethem was
killed and 39 Americans were held captive for 17 days.
   Watson, 30, told the court that Hamadi took him to the front on
the plane after it was hijacked and threatened him with a pistol.
   ``I was very afraid I would be shot, but Uli Derickson pleaded
with him in German,'' Watson said.
   Mrs. Derickson, the chief flight attendant, has been credited
with negotiating with Hamadi in German in attempts to prevent
mistreatment of the passengers.
   Watson also told the court that he recognized the picture of a
man now jailed in France as one of the men who came aboard the
plane during a Beirut stop and held him hostage.
   Watson was shown the picture of a man identified in court
records as Fuad Ali Salah.
   ``I saw him twice while we were being held captive in Beirut,''
Watson said.
   Salah was arrested March 27, 1987 in France on suspicion of
taking part in bombings in Paris, according to evidence introduced
in court.
   Watson, dressed in a gray suit, said he was still in the Navy,
but did not give his rank or residence, in keeping with court
guidelines intended to protect witnesses.
   Hamadi listened intently to the testimony with one arm propped
on the desk in front of him, his chin resting in his left hand.
   Earlier today, American physician Michael Clark told the court
that he performed a second autopsy on Stethem at the request of the
FBI in 1986.
   Clark said he was asked to perform the autopsy to find out
whether other injuries to the 23-year-old sailor had been
overlooked during a preliminary autopsy done after his death in
June 1985.
   He said his 1986 autopsy did not find injuries that had been
overlooked, but confirmed previous testimony that Stethem had lived
between three and 10 minutes after he had been shot in the head.
   Other witnesses have testified that Stethem, of Waldorf, Md.,
was thrown onto the runway immediately after being shot.
   Flight 847's pilot, John Testrake, told the court several weeks
ago that he believed Hamadi was the gunman.
   Other witnesses have said they believed the other hijacker,
identified by a U.S. indictment as Hassan Ezzeddine, was the killer.
   Hamadi, who has admitted being one of the hijackers, has denied
killing Stethem.
   Hamadi was arrested at the Frankfurt airport in January 1987
after customs officials found explosives in his luggage.
   In the week that followed his arrest two West German businessmen
were kidnapped in Beirut. Both have since been released.
   Hamadi's older brother, Abbas Hamadi, is imprisoned in West
Germany. He was convicted earlier this year by a Duesseldorf court
of conspiracy in the abduction of the two West Germans in an effort
to pressure the West German government to release his brother.
   West Germany denied a U.S. request for the extradition of
Mohammed Hamadi, saying he would be tried on the same charges here.
</TEXT>
