<2ND_LINE>PM-Cadets Stricken, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0541,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Academy Graduate Defends Training</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with 35 cadets attending rally;
other quotes, further background on training; and to CORRECT that
rally organizer Griswold graduated in 1988, sted 1986. Picks up 9th
graf pvs, `Griswold defended...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AGAWAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-five graduates of a police academy
that is under investigation for an epidemic of illness among cadets
gathered today to defend their instructors and institution.
   ``This is where you separate the men from the boys and the women
from the girls,'' said Michael Gonnello, of the West Springfield
police force. Gonnello was among alumni who met at the academy to
show their support.
   He and others criticized the state for removing the two state
police instructors accused of overworking cadets and discouraging
them from drinking water after 16 cadets required medical attention
last month for dehydration and related problems. The two
instructors were running their first course, although they had
assisted in others.
   ``These troopers know their job,'' said Jerry Millar of the
Amherst police force. ``The only problem we had was that they
didn't have time to teach us. The last few weeks they had to cram
in a lot.''
   One of the rally organizers, Colleen Griswold, said earlier that
women trainees who accused instructors of calling them ``pregnant
sows,'' couldn't possibly be telling the truth.
   ``I'll eat my combat boots if one of the females can come to me
and say that is true,'' said Griswold, an Amherst police officer
and a 1988 graduate of the academy in this city just south of
Springfield.
   The school was closed for a time after the cadets fell ill. The
most seriously ill, Timothy Shepard, 25, of Pittsfield, required a
liver transplant after collapsing on his first day Sept. 19 and
remained in critical condition today. The others suffered
dehyrdration and kidney failure, doctors said.
   Shepard's sister-in-law said this morning that there were signs
he was coming out of a coma. She said he started to turn his head
Monday and appeared to recognize his mother and his pregnant wife.
``We've seen some good signs ...,'' she said. ``We're praying and
hoping.''
   Some cadets said they went through 10{ hours of exercise with
relatively little water. Their police chiefs have said water was
available, but the cadets may have hesitated to break ranks to ask
for it.
   On Monday, the state Department of Public Safety ordered its
police academies to stop using pushups and other exercise as
punishment in training cadets.
   John Barrett III, mayor of the small western Massachusetts town
of North Adams and chief critic of the training program, has said
an investigation indicated that instructors had taunted women
cadets by calling them ``pregnant sows'' and ``baby makers,''
singled out two male trainees as ``class idiots'' and meted out
excessive punishment, forcing cadets to walk like ducks and lie
like cockroaches with their arms and legs in the air for long
periods.
   Academy officials have said that training was meant to be
stressful, but not abusive, to prepare recruits for the insults and
other stresses that go along with police work.
   Griswold defended her instructors, including John Richardson.
   ``I find it very hard, if not impossible, to believe he
(Richardson) would ever have said something like that,'' said
Griswold, whose class at the academy ran from October 1987 to
January 1988.
   She denied there had been any abuse of cadets.
   ``All I know is what happened to me,'' Griswold said. ``I never
missed a day and I was never sick.''
   As the only woman in her class, she said, ``I never felt
discriminated against for a second.''
   Richardson and another instructor, trooper Charles Gilmore, bade
farewell to their class Monday as they prepared to turn the cadets
over to another pair of state troopers.
   The two men asked to be reassigned Friday because of the
attention the academy has received since members of their class
began collapsing two weeks ago.
</TEXT>
