<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SenateDemonstration     10-04 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Senate Demonstration,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brief Demonstration Interrupts Senate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators chanting ``Housing Now'' briefly
interrupted Senate proceedings today before being carried out of
the chamber by doorkeepers and police detectives.
   ``We need to stop business as usual,'' an unidentified woman
shouted from the visitors gallery overlooking the Senate floor,
where Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., had just finished speaking. She
began shouting ``Housing Now'' and was joined by several other
women, who were quickly grabbed and carried out of the chamber.
   The Senate had just begun a quorum call and only a few senators
were on the floor at the time. The demonstration was over in about
a minute.
   Protesters, who maintain Congress should make more money
available for housing for the homeless and the poor, have staged
demonstrations around Capitol Hill offices over the past week. Last
week, several were arrested for refusing to leave the office of
Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II, D-Mass. Others were arrested when they
walked into the office of Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and began
removing furniture, saying they wanted Helms to know what it was
like to be evicted.
   Capitol police were still investigating today's incident and
names of those removed from the Senate chamber were not immediately
available.
</TEXT>
