<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0457 10-04 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Bush Failed as Vice President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede CHICAGO</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing changes throughout; no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis said today that
Republican rival George Bush had failed every assignment as vice
president and that American business has suffered as a result.
   ``We cannot build a strong and vibrant economic future for
America on a mountain of debt, and the American business community
knows that,'' Dukakis said in a speech at Northwestern University.
   The Democratic nominee also said he supports ``reasonable
limits'' to curtail what he called a ``merger and acquisition binge
that continues to sweep the country.''
   The Massachusetts governor voiced confidence that he is
``beginning to turn this race around'' after trailing Bush in most
national polls, but said the contest was ``tough and competitive.''
   He compared the upcoming election with the outcome of the 1960
race in which John F. Kennedy won a narrow victory over Republican
Richard Nixon.
   Suggesting that history might repeat itself, Dukakis reminded
his audience that Illinois had gone for Kennedy by a mere 8,800
votes _ or about one vote per precinct _ in a state of 10 million.
   The Democratic candidate, highlighting trade issues, accused
Bush of embracing an economic policy of drift which permitted large
U.S. trade deficits to accumulate unchecked.
   ``George Bush thinks we need a president who blames American
workers and corporations for the trade deficit,'' Dukakis told a
receptive audience of about 1,000 students and business leaders.
   If elected, he said, he and running mate Lloyd Bentsen of Texas
would work with labor and management to ease the trade deficit and
make ``the label `Made in America' a symbol of quality and value
and durability all over the world.''
   Dukakis said the country is losing business and trade markets to
foreign competitors at a record rate. ``Cite these facts, and
George Bush will say you're downgrading America,'' he said. ``My
friends, if we disregard these facts, we endanger America.''
   Dukakis said the vice president had failed his assignments on
promoting U.S. sales in Japan, regulatory reform, drug
interdiction, international terrorism and banking reforms.
   ``Mr. Bush was given five important missions by this
administration and he failed every one. And that was before they
asked him to pick a running mate in this election,'' Dukakis said,
referring to GOP vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle.
   In Chicago on Monday, Dukakis promised to enforce civil rights
laws, provide same-day voter registration and work for statehood
foer the District of Columbia.
   Speaking to a mostly black audience at the Regal Theater on
Chicago's South Side, the Democratic nominee accused the Reagan
administration of turning back the clock on civil rights.
   ``We're going to aim high and enforce the civil rights laws of
this country, not veto them; we're going to have a Justice
Department that will inspire us, not embarrass us; and we're going
to have an attorney general who understands what the word justice
means,'' Dukakis said.
   A Democratic administration, according to Dukakis, would
``support the affirmative action programs that (Republican vice
presidential candidate) Dan Quayle voted against.''
   In his speech, Dukakis paid tribute to the late Mayor Harold
Washington and praised former rival Jesse Jackson as a ``great son
of Chicago'' whose ``sun still shines brightly over all of
America.''
   Dukakis spokesman Dayton Duncan said Jackson, who was
campaigning for the Democratic ticket on the East Coast, was unable
to join Dukakis. However, the aide said a Dukakis-Jackson joint
appearance was planned for later this month.
   From here, Dukakis headed for a tour of a Jeep plant in Toledo,
Ohio, and was attending a private fund-raising dinner in
Washington, D.C., tonight. He was returning to Boston, where he
will spend all day Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
