<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0473 10-04 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0473,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kinnock Insists Labor Must Adopt New Policies To Win</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Kinnock speech, details;
PICKS up 10th graf pvs, `The new ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Neil Kinnock, facing
left-wing accusations that he is betraying socialism, insisted
today that his Labor Party must adopt new economic policies if it
is to win power.
   He said the party must be ``serious about nuclear disarmament''
but made no flat promises to scrap British atomic weapons
unilaterally.
   To critics who criticize a party policy review designed to move
the party closer to the center, Kinnock said, ``There is no
concession to Thatcherism as great as letting it win again.''
   Most delegates applauded. But groups of leftists, who say he is
seeking to win votes with a watered-down version of Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's conservative program, sat silently.
   Kinnock ordered the party policy review after Labor's third
successive election defeat in 1987.
   On the issue of unilateral nuclear disarmament, Kinnock said
today:
   ``When we conclude our review next year and resolve upon our
policy for fighting the next general election, that policy must be
serious about nuclear disarmament, serious about defense.''
   He avoided using the word ``unilateral,'' but said that unless
Labor won power, the Conservatives plan to deploy the new
generation of Trident sea-launched missiles ``will be completed and
deployed and, in addition, other systems will be multiplied under
the guise of modernization.''
   The 46-year-old Welshman was addressing more than 1,000
delegates in this north England resort on the third day of the
weeklong convention, which began with his crushing victory for the
party leadership over left-winger Tony Benn.
   On Monday, the conference endorsed the first stage of a policy
review which emphasizes emphasizes the role of capitalism while
promising greater state control of the economy.
   The review, the first stage of a two-year process, includes
dropping a commitment to renationalize all state-owned industries
sold by Mrs. Thatcher and also accepts some of her drastic curbs on
the powers of labor unions.
   Ron Todd, leader of the transport workers' union, the biggest in
the country and whose support was crucial to Kinnock, warned Monday
night that the Labor Party leader had not been given ``a blank
check.''
   The new proposals released last spring also stipulate tax rate
ceilings of 50 to 60 percent, compared with 86 percent under the
last Labor administration which lost power to Mrs. Thatcher in 1979.
   Mrs. Thatcher cut the top rate of income tax soon after winning
power and this year, in a second major reduction, slashed the top
rate from 60 to 40 percent.
   The rest of the policy review is due to be published next
spring. Final decisions on the whole package will be made at
Labor's 1989 convention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
