<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Proposes Volunteer Program</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 12 grafs new with Bush program; pick up 4th graf pvs bgng
``The journey...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today proposed
a volunteer program to spur young people into community and social
services such as helping the needy and drug abusers.
   Youth Engaged in Service to America, with a $100 million federal
pricetag and chaired by the president, ``will work with existing
youth programs, and will put an emphasis on programs that are
started in our schools,'' Bush said in a morning speech to the
business-oriented Comstock Club.
   Bush has tried to portray himself as a caring presidential
candidate who wants to help the unfortunate, while the Democrats
have depicted him as a wealthy man out of touch with the country.
   Bush acknowledged that some children are ``living lives of utter
desolation ... and we have yet to find a way to help them.''
   The federal funds would be set up as a matching program to
generate the same amount in provate donations.
   ``The best of the existing volunteer programs will be expanded
and new programs will be developed. The end result I hope is that
citizen service will become a real and living part of every young
American's life,'' Bush said.
   He suggested awarding high school or college credit for youth
volunteerism under the program.
   As examples, he said young people could help poor children,
women with abusive husbands, or immigrants who don't speak English.
   ``I want our affluent to help our poor,'' he said. ``I want our
young to help our elderly ... I want the young men and women of our
tree-lined suburbs to get on a bus, or the subway, or the metro,
and go into the cities where the want is.''
   The YES to America program mostly would work in partnership with
community efforts and programs already in place, such as Peace
Corps, the California Conservation Corps and other community-based
volunteer programs, according to Bush campaign adviser Loret Ruppe,
director of the Peace Corps.
   Bush pledged Monday to commit the nation to development of a
manned space station by 1996, telling an outdoor rally in
picturesque northern California the space program ``brings us
together.''
   The speech in Redding, deep in timber country, followed a
high-visibility trip to the California desert Monday that let the
vice president share the spotlight with the returning Discovery
space shuttle and five astronauts.
   The journey from Washington to California to welcome the
Discovery back from its four-day voyage was officially billed as a
vice presidential trip. But Bush's campaign paid for the travel to
vote-rich California, a crucial battleground in the November
election.
   Bush told the crowd of about 5,000 that he would ``commit this
nation to the development of an operational space station by the
year 1996.''
   ``This goal is achievable, sensible ... and we will meet that
goal,'' Bush said.
   Though taking a few customary swipes at his Democratic opponent
Michael Dukakis, Bush said he mostly wanted to talk about space. He
said he is ``fully and utterly committed to the U.S. space program,
and utterly committed to the peaceful exploration of near and far
space.''
   Bush noted President Reagan had said that space is a place
``where mankind may be liberated from hunger and want and
oppression.''
   ``But I would add that it has long seemed to me that while the
higher purpose of our space program is science and progress, there
is another purpose,'' he said. ``The U.S. space program gives us a
lift. It brings us together.''
   He also reiterated his proposals for a National Space Council,
to be chaired by the vice president, that would make
recommendations on the future of space exploration.
   He said the National Aeronautics and Space Administration should
be looking toward Mars. ``The way I see the logical order is this:
first the shuttle then the space station,'' he said. ``First the
moon, then perhaps Mars.''
   The made-for-TV scene at Redding was the kind his campaign
stages with near perfection.
   When singer Lee Greenwood closed the rally by singing ``I'm
Proud to Be an American,'' cheering people waved American flags as
the sun sank in the background. Bush, a wide smile across his face
as he sang along with the refrain, ``God Bless the USA,'' standing
with a little girl in a Brownie outfit and in front of high school
cheerleaders clad in white and purple.
   But one large banner raised briefly at the back of the crowd
testified to a cash crop that has brought considerable wealth in
surrounding California areas. ``Legalize Marijuana,'' it said.
   Bush's welcoming handshake to the shuttle crew as they stepped
off Discovery gave the vice president a chance to share in the
positive publicity generated by the first shuttle mission since the
deadly Challenger explosion close to three years ago.
   He watched the landing from a high wooden platform constructed
on the dry lake bed where the shuttle touches down.
   ``Because of you our space program is back in the game,'' Bush
told the returning astronauts at Edwards Air Force Base.
   Bush said the seven members of the Challenger shuttle crew were
``cheering from above'' at the successful mission.
</TEXT>
