<2ND_LINE>PM-Tanker Fire, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0573,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tanker Burns; Fumes Force Evacuations, Closing Of Highway In
Louisiana</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with number of injured now put
at five; four of them hospitalized. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `We
have...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JENNINGS, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker truck carrying hazardous chemicals
overturned and caught fire early today on Interstate 10 near here,
spewing toxic fumes and forcing an evacuation and the closure of
the highway, police said.
   Five people were injured in the collision, includeing four who
were admitted to a hospital, said Trooper Paul Wood. None of the
people was identified.
   Authorities said they had no idea how long the evacuees would be
out of their homes. State police spokesman Ronnie Jones said they
numbered more than 500.
   ``From our point, the situation is under control. It's a just a
matter of letting the fire burn out,'' he said.
   State Police Lt. Herman Rogers said the 6:20 a.m. accident
involved two trucks, one of which was carrying 4,600 gallons of
toluene, a flammable liquid that gives off toxic fumes when
burning. Toluene is used in the manufacture of TNT and other
compounds. It is also called methyl benzene.
   In two other compartments, the truck was carrying petroleum
naptha and naptha distillate, both also toxic and flammable.
   The other truck was carrying pipe. All five of those injured
were in one or other of the two trucks, Wood said.
   ``We have a toxic cloud heading towards Jennings. Interstate 10
is closed down. We are trying to advise listeners ... do not go
towards the Jennings area,'' state trooper Darrell Fontenot told
KTQQ radio in nearby Sulphur, La.
   Parish Sheriff's spokesman Al Hebert said all schools in the
southwestern Louisiana city of about 12,000 people were closed
because of the accident.
   Rogers said I-10 was closed to traffic in both directions near
the Acadia-Jefferson Davis parish line, and vehicles were being
diverted to other highways. Jones said he expected the freeway to
be closed all day.
   Officer Calvin White said air space was restricted up to 600
feet above and three miles around the fire site.
</TEXT>
