<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     10-04 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Calls For Summit With North Korean Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo on Tuesday
renewed his proposal for talks with his North Korean counterpart,
Kim Il Sung, and said he was ready to cooperate to end the
confrontation on the divided Korean Peninsula.
   ``I make it clear that I am willing to visit (the North Korean
capital of) Pyongyang to meet with (Kim Il Sung), if the North is
agreeable,'' Roh said in the nationally televised speech to the
National Assembly.
   Roh also announced an annual budget of $27 billion, up 10.9
percent.
   Roh's speech drew cool response from the main opposition group,
Kim Dae-jung's Party for Peace and Democracy, which accused the
government of continuing to hold political prisoners.
   About a dozen opposition members boycotted Roh's speech. Others
remained seated and refused to clap their hands when the president
walked into the hall.
   Opposition leaders criticized the government for releasing what
they said was just one-tenth of political prisoners under a special
amnesty Monday. More than 1,000 prisoners were released, including
52 political offenders.
   The government says all political prisoners have been freed
except for dissidents convicted of violent crimes or communism.
   Hailing as a turning point South Korea's successful role as host
for the Olympics, Roh said he would renew efforts to improve
relations with North Korea during his single five-year term in
office, which ends in 1992.
   ``During my tenure, I will endeavor to bring about a spring of
reconciliation between the South and the North, which have remained
in a deep freeze for 40 years,'' he said.
   The 56-year-old president, who was elected in December, did not
disclose unification proposals but said he was willing to meet Kim
``at any place and at the earliest possible date to discuss any and
all issues.''
   The Korean Peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
pro-Western South Korea in 1945, at the end of World War II. The
two sides fought a war in the 1950s, and the United States still
maintains 42,000 troops in the South. Parliamentary officials of
the two Koreas are to resume unification talks Oct. 13 at the truce
village of Panmunjom near the border. The last round of talks in
August ended without any progress.
   In early September, Kim said he would not meet Roh unless the
South accepts North Korea's unification formula, which calls for
the two Korean states to keep their different political and social
systems while operating as one nation under a confederation. The
North Korean leader also demanded that the two countries'
legislatures issue a joint non-aggression agreement.
   Seoul officials rejected the demands as a ploy to weaken South
Korea and eventually unify the peninsula under communist rule.
   Roh said his country would soon propose a new unification
formula which would be ``practicable and acceptable to both
sides,'' but he gave no details.
   Roh also said South Korea, which has recently exchanged trade
offices with Hungary and Yugoslavia, would continue trying to
improve relations with the Soviet Union and other communist
countries.
</TEXT>
