<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Deportation-Abuse     10-04 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deportation-Abuse,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nigerian Girl To Be Sent Home; Loses Court Fight To Stay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old Nigerian girl has lost her
court fight to stay in the United States and will be returned to
her native country despite her claims that her father will abuse
her.
   U.S. District Judge William Cambridge on Monday denied a court
order sought to prevent Omalara Oyesiji's deportation. She was
taken into custody as she left court.
   Her court-appointed guardian, attorney Susan Koenig-Cramer, had
sought the court order. Cambridge also declined to delay the
effective date of his decision so Mrs. Koenig-Cramer could appeal.
   Miss Oyesiji came to the United States in March 1987 with her
stepmother after her father, a doctor from Lagos, Nigeria, enrolled
in courses at the University of Nebraska Medical Center.
   The girl ran away from home in September 1987, alleging her
father had abused her physically, according to court records. She
was placed in a youth group home in Bellevue and remained there
after her father and stepmother returned unexpectedly to Nigeria
last December.
   The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service began
deportation proceedings in March, contending she had entered the
country only because her father was studying here. When he left,
she also should be required to leave, immigration officials said.
   Miss Oyesiji appeared at a deportation hearing in April and was
given until July to depart voluntarily. In July, immigration
officials declined her request for an extension of time to appeal.
   Mrs. Koenig-Cramer filed two actions in federal court to delay
the deportation, and the action was held up until Monday's hearing.
   During the hearing, Miss Oyesiji testified that her father had
beat her and her younger brother when they lived in Nigeria and in
Omaha.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Paul Madgett said Miss Oyesiji's
attorney failed to prove immigration officials abused their
discretion when they denied her request for an extension of time to
leave voluntarily. That is the only basis which the judge had to
block the administrative decision, Madgett said.
   James M. Cole, immigration service district director, said the
U.S. consul general in Lagos has been notified of the case and told
about the abuse reports. The consulate was asked to notify Nigerian
authorities ``so she will not be placed in an abusive situation,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
