<DOCNO> AP881004-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Debate-League Bjt   10-04 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate-League, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>League Departure May Hurt Future Debates</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fight over a second presidential debate
that erupted this week between the League of Women Voters and the
candidates could lead to no debates at all in 1992.
   In 1976, 1980, 1984 and now 1988, face-to-face confrontations
between the presidential candidates have highlighted the fall
campaigns.
   It is that very success that may spell an end to the encounters.
   Debates are so important that campaigns do everything they can
to control them. In this grab for control, the campaigns of George
Bush and Michael Dukakis crushed the fragile institutional
structure that had grown up around the debates.
   The campaigns moved forcefully this year to dictate every detail
of the debate process, down to the height of the lecterns and the
seating of reporters in the hall.
   There was a report in The Washington Post on Tuesday that this
control extended to a Bush campaign effort to strong-arm moderator
Jim Lehrer in the middle of the first debate last month to change
the line of questioning.
   League president Nancy Neuman said Monday her group could not be
a party to such ``manipulation'' of the debate process and withdrew
its sponsorship of the debate scheduled next week in Los Angeles.
The campaigns are now scrambling to line up the debate there
anyway, using the screen of the debate commission they control
through the party committees.
   But control of podium height and camera angles is not the key
element of a campaign's influence on debates.
   Whether to debate at all is the key.
   Incumbent presidents _ and candidates leading in the polls _
often don't want to debate, knowing that a single misstep can
derail a campaign that was otherwise headed for victory.
   ``I think we're probably lucky, as Americans, that this race is
as close as it is,'' said Democratic consultant Robert Squier on
NBC's ``Today'' show. ``Because if this race were not close, I
think whoever was ahead would not be showing up in Los Angeles.''
   Debates have occurred in four straight presidential elections
because the pressure for debates was so strong that even the
candidates could not resist it.
   Part of this pressure came from the media, editorializing for
debates. Part of it came from campaigns that decide they can
benefit from debates.
   And part of the pressure has come from those institutions with a
stake in the debates. The primary institution has been the League,
sponsor of the debates in 1976, 1980 and 1984.
   The television networks have also had an institutional stake.
They sponsored the 1960 debates and offer frequently to take on the
role again. The League had barely withdrawn on Monday before the
networks offered to take on the sponsorship role.
   The political parties tried to grab an institutional role in the
debates, setting up a commission that sponsored the first one last
month and which is trying to put together the second one now.
   But that commission is a creature of the parties _ and thus of
the campaigns. Its continued existence is very much in doubt,
depending on the political needs of the winner of the November
election.
   And after the experience of 1988, it is by no means certain that
the League will want to dive back into the debate morass again.
   In 1992 there will be an incumbent president _ named Bush or
Dukakis _ running for re-election.
   The challenger will call for debates, early and often.
   The question is whether the incumbent can be forced into a
debate by a drumbeat of pressure from a neutral entity _ such as
the League.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Evans Witt is a Washington-based political writer
for The Associated Press who has written about presidential debates
since 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
