<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PostalPlans     10-04 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal Plans,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Service Sets $12.9 Billion Development Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service announced a $12.9
billion program Tuesday for investment in new facilities, buildings
and equipment over the next five years.
   The spending, including nearly $450 million for new vending
machines, lobby equipment and other customer service projects, was
approved by the agency's board of governors, meeting in Richmond,
Va.
   Some of the spending will compensate for projects shelved last
fall when Congress ordered postal spending curtailed in the 1988
and 1989 fiscal years in an effort to lower the overall total of
the federal budget.
   The new five-year plan includes $4.2 billion for new, automated
mail processing equipment to help cope with the rising tide of mail.
   Mail volume, currently about 160 billion pieces annually, is
expected to top 225 billion by the year 2000.
   The plan also calls for spending of $6.7 billion for purchase or
repair of several major mail facilities across the country, $1.2
billion for customer service and administration projects and $443
million for purchase of new vehicles.
   While the governors approved the overall plan for the five-year
period, individual projects will still require review by the board.
</TEXT>
