<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Amnesty-US     10-04 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty-US,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty Cites United States For Executing Mentally Retarded
Prisoner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Amnesty Report, Bjt
^EDS: For release at 8:01 P.M., OCT. 4, time set by source.
Wednesday cq in lede.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International criticized the United States
on Wednesday for executing a man diagnosed as mentally retarded and
for jailing a church worker who smuggled Salvadoran aliens into the
country.
   In its annual global survey, the international human rights
organization said 25 murderers were put to death by lethal
injection, electrocution or in the gas chamber in eight states last
year.
   A total of 1,982 prisoners were under sentence of death in 34
states in December 1987, it said.
   The London-based group opposes the death penalty on grounds it
is inhuman punishment.
   Its annual report said that John Brogdon, who was executed in
Louisiana on July 30, 1987 for the rape and murder of a child, had
been diagnosed as mentally retarded with a mental age of 10.
   Billy Mitchell, executed in Georgia on Sept. 1, 1987, also was
reported to have been suffering from a serious mental disorder, the
report said.
   It said Edward Earl Johnson, a black youth convicted of killing
a white police officer, was executed despite ``substantial doubts''
about his guilt raised by defense lawyers. Further evidence in
support of Johnson's innocence has emerged since his execution in
Mississippi on May 25, 1987, the report said.
   Amnesty International said it wrote to the governors of Georgia
and nine other states to protest ``marked racial disparities in
death sentencing'' after a Supreme Court ruling on the issue in
April 1987.
   The court voted 5-4 to deny an appeal on behalf of a black
prisoner, Warren McCleskey, which cited a study showing black
defendants convicted of killing white victims in Georgia were
several times more likely to receive death sentences than those
convicted of killing blacks.
   Amnesty said it adopted church worker Stacey Merkt as a prisoner
of conscience after she was convicted in 1985 of transporting and
conspiring to transport illegal aliens.
   Merkt started serving an 18-month sentence in Janaury 1987 but
was released in April to serve the rest of her sentence under house
arrest, which was lifted three months later, it said.
   Amnesty International, which defines a prisoner of conscience as
a person imprisoned for non-violent political activity, said it
believed the Salvadoran aliens were in danger of being imprisoned,
tortured or unlawfully executed if sent back to their homeland.
   Amnesty said it found ``serious inadequacies'' in the
investigation of alleged mistreatment of prisoners at Marion
maximum-security prison in Illinois in November 1983. It
recommended that the authorities conduct an independent inquiry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881004-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GlobalCompetition     10-04 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Global Competition,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Group Urges Changes To Boost U.S. Competitiveness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States must revamp outdated
government regulations and tax policies to boost the ability of
American businesses to compete internationally, a new study
concluded Tuesday.
   The Committee for Economic Development, a group of 200 U.S.
business leaders and educators, said that too often American
politicians characterize increased global trade as a threat rather
than an opportunity.
   ``As a result, they do not recognize the need to reform outmoded
policies that were developed in an era when most Americans felt
they had little stake in foreign economic developments,'' the
report said.
   The study said that an increasingly integrated world economy
posed problems for American businesses and workers. It said special
attention was needed for retraining workers in declining industries
and improving the U.S. education system.
   ``In a highly integrated global economy, a nation that falls
behind in the education and training of its labor force will not
remain a leading economic power,'' the report said.
   The group singled out the 1986 Tax Reform Act as one example of
legislation enacted with little attention to its impact on the
ability of U.S. companies to compete abroad. The group criticized
the elimination of various tax benefits for business investments,
saying these changes had raised the cost of capital in the United
States.
   Tax overhaul supporters argued that the changes eliminated
loopholes and lowered overall tax rates, thus creating a fairer tax
structure.
   The study said that a host of U.S. budget and tax policies as
well as federal regulations need to be revised.
   In addition to changes in the tax code to boost capital
investment, the report recommended changes in the international
regulation of financial markets, better protection for U.S.
copyrights and patents and a review of the impact anti-trust laws
have on the ability of American corporations to compete
internationally.
   The study, titled ``New Dynamics in the Global Economy,'' was
written by Isaiah Frank, an economics professor at Johns Hopkins
Univeristy, and William J. Beeman, a vice president at the Council
for Economic Development.
   Owen B. Butler, retired chairman of the Proctor & Gamble Corp.,
is head of the non-profit council. The council receives support
from businesses, foundations and individuals.
</TEXT>
