<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     10-04 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forces Kill 12; Opposition Leader Asks Amnesty International For
Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces killed 12 people caught
looting or stealing Tuesday, government radio said, and an
opposition leader appealed to Amnesty International to help bring
democracy to Burma.
   State-run Radio Rangoon said soldiers opened fire on a group of
people looting a food warehouse in Rangoon and killed 10. Soldiers
killed two more people caught stealing iron roofing in another part
of the capital, the report said.
   The deaths brought to more than 440 the number of people
officials say have died since military officers seized control
Sept. 18 and cracked down on anti-government demonstrators and
looters.
   Anti-government strikes that began in August have seriously
disrupted supplies of food and other items to the capital.
   In a letter to Amnesty International, Tin Oo, a former defense
minister and the vice chairman of the opposition National League
for Democracy, cited the killing of demonstrators, denial of labor
union rights and removal from office of many government officials
for taking part in recent anti-government protests.
   Copies of the letter were distributed to reporters.
   ``All the opposition leaders are now facing arrest and other
punitive measures,'' the letter said. ``We therefore request you to
do your best for the restoration of human rights and democracy in
the country.''
   Opposition leaders and Western diplomats in Rangoon say some
lower-ranking opposition leaders have been arrested.
   Under threat of dismissal, government employees reported to work
Tuesday, but by midday many workers had returned home, some saying
there was no work to do.
   The government ordered all civil servants to return to their
jobs Monday, ending a monthlong general strike _ the first mass
labor agitation since former ruler Ne Win seized power in 1962 and
instituted a military-backed, one-party system.
   Ne Win resigned in July and was replaced by Sein Lwin, a
hard-line military leader. He, too, resigned after massive
pro-democracy protests in August and September, and was replaced by
Maung Maung, a civilian. Saw Maung, the current leader, ousted
Maung Maung.
   Students continued sporadic demonstrations against military rule
in residential areas of east Rangoon on Tuesday, but no arrests
were reported.
   Tin Oo said the government had not yet responded to a request by
the National League for Democracy for a meeting with authorities to
discuss proposals for free elections.
   The government has promised general elections and allowed
political parties to register, thus formally breaking the monopoly
on power held by the Burma Socialist Program Party since 1962.
   However, that party, now renamed the National Unity Party, is
solidly entrenched and has a nationwide organizational network.
   State radio also reported Tuesday that the head of a
U.S.-supported guerrilla group fighting the Laotian communist
government was killed Sept. 19 in a clash with Burmese troops.
   The report identified the group as the Laotian Liberation Army
and said documents seized included a U.S. alien resident card and
an Illinois driver's license. It did not say whose name was on the
license or identify the guerrilla.
   The guerrilla was killed near Mong Pyak, about 20 miles west of
the Laotian border, the report said. The troops also seized a U.S.
flag and documents of a group called the Southeast Asian Freedom
Organization detailing plans to liberate communist nations such as
Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos.
</TEXT>
