<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Senate-Justice     10-04 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate-Justice,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Confirms Top Justice Department Aides</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted Tuesday to confirm nominees
for three top Justice Department posts, including replacements for
the two men who resigned last March 29 to protest the continued
tenure of then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   In voice votes, the Senate approved Harold G. Christensen as
deputy attorney general, Frank Keating as associate attorney
general, the No. 3 post in the department; and Edward S.G. Dennis
Jr., as an assistant attorney general in charge of the criminal
division.
   Christensen replaces Arnold Burns, who resigned out of concern
that Meese's continued tenure in the face of a criminal
investigation of his personal activities was hurting the
department's operations.
   Dennis succeeds William F. Weld, who resigned with Burns. Weld
testified in July to Congress that he felt Meese had probably
violated the federal gratuity law because he had accepted a number
of items of value from longtime friend E. Robert Wallach and had
performed official acts on Wallach's behalf.
   Meese wasn't indicted, but independent counsel James McKay
concluded the attorney general had probably twice broken a federal
conflict-of-interest law as well as tax laws.
   Keating, a former assistant Treasury Department secretary,
replaces Stephen S. Trott, who left the Justice Department earlier
this year to become a federal appeals court judge.
   Christensen, who is a lawyer from Salt Lake City; Keating and
Dennis, who is a former U.S. attorney in Philadelphia, all have
been filling their positions on an acting basis for several months.
</TEXT>
