<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BlackBias     10-04 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Bias,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fired White Officer Wins $450,000 From Black City Council</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white policeman who said his firing
by Riviera Beach's black-dominated government was racially
motivated has won a $450,000 settlement.
   The City Council agreed Monday night to settle a lawsuit filed
by Steven J. Langevin, who was dismissed in 1983.
   Langevin, who is white, claimed the city used him as a scapegoat
after complaints about a June 1983 traffic stop involving the son
of an influential city official. The complainants, city manager,
police chief and all five members of the council were black.
   A Palm Beach County Circuit Court jury agreed in 1986 with
Langevin's claim and awarded him $540,000. An appellate court last
year upheld the decision, but the state Supreme Court said last
week it would hear the city's appeal.
   That encouraged Langevin's attorney to negotiate the settlement,
City Attorney Thomas Palmer said. At Palmer's urging, the council
unanimously approved the settlement.
   ``It was all something that happened long ago,'' Councilman
James Goode said. ``The question now is to settle it in the
cheapest way.''
   Palmer said the council should approve the settlement because if
the city lost the appeal, it might have to pay more than $1 million.
   Langevin and other officers stopped a car driven by Derrick
McCray, son of an influential city official and civil rights
activist, while searching for a robbery suspect.
   Then-City Manager William Wilkins fired Langevin on July 13,
1983. He was rehired briefly, because the case had not been
referred to a police review board, and was fired again Aug. 27.
   Wilkins, citing several incidents besides the traffic stop, said
he dismissed Langevin because of actions that ``contributed to the
tarnishing of the professional image'' of the department.
   Langevin did not seek reinstatement to the force.
</TEXT>
