<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     10-04 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Demand Government Resign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 Yugoslav workers
demanding the resignation of the government demonstrated Tuesday in
front of the Parliament and tried to force their way inside.
   Protesters chanted ``We are going in!'' but hundreds of police
stationed in front of the building stopped them from entering.
   The protesters marched about 10 miles from an industrial
Belgrade suburb to the legislature to protest low wages and falling
living standards.
   Demonstrators booed and jeered Deputy Premier Milos
Milosavljevic and Parliament President Dusan Popovski when they
tried to address the crowd. The workers dispersed peacefully after
four hours following an address by Serbia's Communist Party chief,
Slobodan Milosevic.
   ``Your demands are the demands of the entire Yugoslav working
class,'' said Milosevic, who promised that personnel changes would
be demanded at an Oct. 17 Central Committee session. ``You can be
sure that we will not betray you.''
   Workers of several enterprises, including an engine and tractor
factory at Rakovica, six miles south of Belgrade, put down their
tools and staged the march, demanding a 100 percent wage increase.
   According to a statement read by one of their leaders,
demonstrators also demanded ``an urgent session of the Parliament,
which should unseat the government of Premier Branko Mikulic.''
   Yugoslavia has been faced with increasing social and labor
unrest in the face of the worst economic crisis in the country's
post-war history. Inflation is running at 217 percent, and the
foreign debt is $21 billion.
   The labor unrest has worsened since May, when government
austerity measures imposed hefty wage cuts and allowed substantial
price increases.
   According to figures published by the state Tanjug news agency
Tuesday, salaries in Yugoslavia have dropped by 24 percent this
year and living standards of Yugoslavs have plunged to the level of
mid-1960s. The Rakovica workers earn about $100 a month.
   Before being interrupted, Milosavljevic only managed to say ``I
understand the grievances of the workers,'' and that the government
was willing to resign if parliament decides accordingly.
   ``You don't understand anything ... how much is your salary?''
the crowd yelled back at him.
   Officials claim there is no alternative to the market-oriented
program worked out together with the International Monetary Fund if
the country wants to lower inflation and revive its faltering
economy.
   Adoption of the program was a condition set by the IMF and other
creditors for rescheduling Yugoslavia's foreign debt and obtaining
new credits.
   However, the government is negotiating with the IMF on ways to
amend the program by allowing wage increases for profitable
companies.
   The demonstrators calmed down after Milosevic urged them to
return to work. They agreed, chanting ``We Believe You, Slobodan!''
and ``Workers Are With You!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
