<DOCNO> AP881004-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1711EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Women-Cooking     10-04 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women-Cooking,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey: Most Women Like to Cook</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighty-one percent of American women like to
cook, but 56 percent don't like cooking every day, according to a
survey released Tuesday.
   Eighty-four percent accept cooking as one of their
responsibilities, according to the survey done for Vogue, Glamour,
Mademoiselle, Self and Bride's magazines. But three-quarters of the
respondents want to get the task done as quickly as possible.
   Eighty percent also do the food shopping alone _ whether or not
they are employed outside the home, it said.
   The study also divided American women into four groups, with
significantly different attitudes toward food, shopping and cooking.
   _Traditional homemakers, who make up 31 percent of all women,
believe it's the husband's job to support the family.
   _Displaced homemakers, 26 percent of all women, have
unfulfilling jobs out of financial necessity, or because of divorce
or separation, but would rather be a full-time homemaker.
   _Committed careerists, 33 percent, who ``see marriage and
child-rearing as an interruption of their careers.''
   _Free spirits, 11 percent, who don't fit any of the other
categories. Most reside in large, urban areas, are relatively
young, employed, and divorced or separated. Many are minorities.
They have the shopping habits of traditional homemakers but cook
like committed careerists.
   Mark Clements Research Inc., and National Family Opinion Inc.,
conducted the study for Conde Nast Publications. It mailed 2,500
questionnaires on Dec. 4 and got back 1,825 by Jan. 12 from women
18 to 65 years old. The sampling error was plus or minus 2.4
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
