<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Protest     10-04 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Protest,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Appeals For Calm As Students Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Tuesday warned that
political demonstrations could hinder talks between authorities and
labor leaders demanding the legalization of Solidarity.
   About 1,000 students and university employees rallied at Warsaw
University in support of legalization of the banned trade union
federation and of the Independent Association of Students.
   The students raised the Solidarity banner on the main gate of
the university and chanted ``Solidarity!''
   University employees and faculty members also demanded pay
raises of 60 percent to compensate for inflation and complained
about poor teaching facilities.
   In his weekly news conference, government spokesman Jerzy Urban
said demonstrations and announcements of new Solidarity chapters
run counter to building ``a climate of reason, realism and mutual
trust.''
   ``Organizers of such events (demonstrations) should ask the
question: Do they make the process of agreement easier or more
difficult? If they bother to think, they should conclude they make
it more difficult and will play a role of blockers,'' Urban said.
   Authorities agreed to hold talks with labor representatives on
the future of Solidarity after a wave of strikes ended Sept. 3.
Urban said progress had been made in preparing for the talks, which
mediator Andrzej Stelmachowski said will probably begin Oct. 17.
   Solidarity, led by Lech Walesa, was crushed by security forces
in 1981 and outlawed in 1982.
   The demonstration took place on the university grounds in front
of the library, where university rector Grzegorz Bialkowski told
the demonstrators: ``I am here together with you not only because I
thought employees have the right to gather legally and express
their opinion about their problems, but also to prove to you I want
to be together with the university community,''
   The protesters dispersed peacefully after about an hour.
</TEXT>
