<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Floods     10-04 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Floods,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>40 Feared Dead When Boat Capsizes In Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boat ferrying people from a flooded
village in eastern Pakistan capsized Tuesday and 40 people were
believed dead, police said.
   Rescuers recovered the bodies of 15 people who came from
Kalakhatei village, about 18 miles northeast of Lahore.
   A week of flooding in Pakistan's eastern Punjab province has
claimed the lives of 36 people, excluding Tuesday's victims,
according to official figures. But officials with a variety of
relief agencies said the casualty figure is closer to 200.
   Heavy rains in the mountainous Kashmir and Jammu areas triggered
the flooding. Rivers flowing from these mountains are beginning to
recede, local authorities said, but the Sutlej river is threatening
villages in the southern part of Punjab. The area hardest-hit by
the waters is the southern city of Bahawalpur.
   Government agencies said about 3,000 villages have been affected
by the flooding and almost 2 million people stranded.
   Health officials in villages near Lahore fear that lack of
sanitary conditions may result in an outbreak of cholera and
typhoid. The officials said thousands of people have been
vaccinated against the diseases.
   The army has delivered food packages to stranded flood victims
and the government has allocated $3 million toward aid for flood
victims.
</TEXT>
