<HEAD>Carlucci Honors Defense Employees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci honored 13
civilian Defense Department employees Tuesday with Outstanding
Handicapped Employee of the Year awards, saying they had made
``invaluable contributions to national security.''
   ``I am proud of DOD's posture as a leader among federal agencies
regarding the employment and advancement of handicapped
individuals,'' Carlucci added.
   The 13 honorees, employed at a variety of installations across
the country, included men and women who have overcome such
handicaps as blindness, deafness, cerebral palsy and spinal cord
injuries.
   One of this year's winners, Kathryn Elizabeth Porter of
Waynesboro, Pa., now is a clerk-typist with the Defense
Investigative Service in Washington and ``overcame a hearing
impairment, mild cerebral palsy, double sclerosis and a congenital
hip malfunction,'' the Pentagon said.
   Another honoree, Shannon M. Keenan, ``was born with a severe
hearing loss and with cerebral palsy.''
   ``She conquered both and today is a military pay examiner with
the Department of Military Affairs, Minnesota National Guard in St.
Paul, Minn.,'' the department said.
   Other honorees included Francis J. Boyle of the Defense
Logistics Agency in Alexandria, Va.; John F. Clark of the Defense
Mapping Agency in St. Louis; Patrick N. DeViney of the Army and Air
Force Exchange Service in Dallas; John H. Ebaugh of the Defense
Nuclear Agency in Bethesda, Md., and Myra Frank of the DOD
inspector general's office in Arlington, Va.
   Also, Alice E. Gehl of the defense secretary's staff in
Washington; Ronald W. Malik of Chanute Air Force Base, Ill.; James
G. Matte of Fort Hood, Texas; William P. McGee of the Defense
Contract Audit Agency in Columbus, Ohio; Susan K. Povinelli of the
Navy in Washington, and Robert C. Rakas of the Defense
Communications Agency in Washington.
