<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TankerFire     10-04 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tanker Fire,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trucks Collide, Fire Results In Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JENNINGS, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two tractor-trailer rigs collided Tuesday,
igniting a tanker truck fire that spewed poisonous smoke and forced
the evacuation of about 500 people, state police said.
   The fire burned itself out six hours later and residents in this
southwest Louisiana town were allowed to return home.
   Five people who were in the two trucks were reported injured,
and four were admitted to a hospital, said Ronnie Jones, a state
police spokesman. The victims' identities and conditions were not
immediately available, he said.
   He said police did not know how the accident happened because
they had not been able to interview the injured.
   The tanker truck was carrying 4,600 gallons of toluene, an
industrial solvent, and naptha, a cleaning solution, Trooper Paul
Wood said. Both chemicals are toxic and flammable, he said.
   The second truck was carrying steel or concrete netting, Jones
said.
   The tanker fire burned itself out on the Mermentau River Bridge
six hours after the 6 a.m. accident on Interstate 10, about one
mile east of Jennings, Jones said. Jennings is about 100 miles west
of Baton Rouge.
   ``The product burned much like a wick would do in a lamp of oil,
burning on top and consuming the product,'' he said.
   More than 500 people who evacuated a three-mile area were
allowed to return home after noon, Jones said.
   ``They were evacuated out of an abundance of caution,'' said
Wood.
   The westbound lanes of I-10 were opened after noon. But the
eastbound lanes were to remain closed until the bridge could be
cleaned and inspected by the state Department of Transportation and
Development, Jones said.
   Jones said the bridge did not appear to sustain serious damage.
   ``It did not appear to us that any of the product was burning on
the bridge itself,'' Jones said. ``It remained in the tank while it
burned.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
