<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1944EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MarijuanaLands     10-04 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marijuana Lands,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interior Agents' Destruction of Marijuana Plants Leaps During
Summer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Department on Tuesday said its
agents had destroyed 51 percent more marijuana plants this summer
than they did in all of 1987.
   A department announcement said law enforcement officers were not
sure whether the increase ``meant that drug activity actually is
increasing on federal lands or whether it merely reflects the
department's intensified enforcement efforts.''
   The department is in charge of the national parks, battlefields,
monuments, seashores and recreation areas; Indian reservations;
wildlife refuges and other public land, mostly in the West.
   The statistics do not include the national forests of the
Agriculture Department's Forest Service. All spokesmen for law
enforcement officers of the Forest Service were out of town, their
office said.
   Interior agencies seized and destroyed 166,000 marijuana plants
from mid-June to mid-September this year compared with 110,000
plants in all of last year, the department said.
   Department officers eradicated plants at 432 sites this summer,
a number spokesman Alan Levitt said represented a substantial
increase over activity in 1987 though he did not have a comparable
department-wide figure for the previous year.
   By way of example, he said, the Bureau of Land Management dealt
with 234 sites this summer vs. 232 in all of 1987.
   The statement quoted Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel as
saying he was ``delighted by the Interior Department's contribution
to the anti-drug campaign.''
   Hodel said visitors deserve credit for increased detection and
were directly responsible for many cases, including the largest
one, the destruction of 20,000 plants just outside the boundary of
Hawaii Volcanoes National Park in August.
   Agents are finding ``fewer large open fields, but many smaller,
well-concealed plots consisting of a few dozen to several hundred
plants,'' often hidden under a forest canopy to avoid detection
from the air or camouflaged with netting, Hodel said.
   For the first time, Interior agents are using the LANDSAT IV
satellite to locate ``high potential areas'' for enforcement, the
department said.
   The agents report that growers seemed to be suffering from the
drought just like legitimate farmers.
   One site in Yosemite National Park in California yielded 1,500
feet of polyvinyl chloride tubing that was feeding water from a
makeshift dam to five separate plots.
</TEXT>
