<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1621EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Sunia 1stLd-Writethru a0587 10-04 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sunia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0587,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Samoan Delegate to Congress Draws 5-15-Month Term</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 9th graf, ``Under federal,'' to CORRECT that Sunia
eligible for parole sted release after five months</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Samoa's former delegate to Congress
drew a five-to-15-month prison term Tuesday for participating in a
payroll-padding scheme that prosecutors say earned him $39,000.
   Fofo I.F. Sunia, a Democrat who served almost four terms in the
House, was sentenced on his guilty plea to conspiring with his
chief aide, Matthew Iuli, to defraud the government of $130,920
through false payroll claims.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Harris rejected a defense contention
that Sunia passively accepted proceeds from a scheme started by
Iuli without his direct knowledge.
   ``It is inconceivable to me with your obvious abilities ... that
you weren't familiar with what was happening,'' the judge told
Sunia. ``What happened here is a very serious matter _ the padding
of a congressional payroll over an extended period of time.''
   Before he was sentenced, Sunia told the judge: ``I have come to
understand the meaning of shame (and) fear. I have made apologies
to my people and I hope they will forgive me.''
   Sunia, who said he was prepared to accept whatever punishment
the judge imposed, offered to teach in American Samoa as community
service in lieu of imprisonment.
   Sunia, 51, said he wanted to ``help continue to build a better
community and begin to atone for the wrong that I have done.''
   The former lawmaker, who could have received a five-year
sentence and a $250,000 fine, has agreed to pay restitution of
$65,000 under the terms of the plea bargain he made with
prosecutors.
   Under federal parole guidelines, Sunia would become eligible for
parole after serving five months.
   According to the charge to which both Sunia and Iuli pleaded
guilty on Aug. 3, 78 paychecks were issued between February 1983
and August 1986 to people falsely listed as members of Sunia's
staff.
   Prosecutors said Iuli, who received a three-month prison
sentence on Monday, used some of the proceeds to reimburse himself
for expenses he incurred working for Sunia.
   Other money was used to entertain constituents who expected
Sunia to pay for their hotel accomodations and meals while they
were visiting the nation's capital, according to prosecutors.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Andary said Sunia's case was
different because the former lawmaker ``did receive a very
substantial personal benefit from this scheme.''
   Andary said Sunia ``betrayed the trust that was put in him by
the people of American Samoa'' by approving the scheme and
pocketing some $39,000 from the ghost employee scheme.
   The money Sunia took helped him purchase a house, a car and pay
for air travel for his family to and from Samoa, Andary said.
   Defense attorney Earl J. Silbert urged Harris to take into
consideration Sunia's passive personality, which he contended
explained the defendant's failure to question the source of the
money he received from the scheme.
   Quoting from a letter written to the judge by a Samoan, Silbert
said: ``A high chief never questions where things come from.''
   But Andary said this explanation was ``a way to avoid
responsibility by way of putting the full blame on Mr. Iuli.''
Sunia ``is consciously trying to avoid his own involvement in the
offense.''
   Sunia resigned his seat in Congress on Sept. 6, the day before
the House ethics committee was to hold a disciplinary hearing on
his case. As a delegate, he was allowed to vote in legislative
committees but not on the House floor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
