<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Chile     10-04 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Chile,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Welcomes Chilean Assurances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Tuesday it had
received and welcomed assurances from Chile that the outcome of a
plebiscite on President Augusto Pinchoet will be ``respected.''
   ``We are, of course, very hopeful,'' spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
said. ``We will continue to closely monitor events in Chile.''
   The voting on Wednesday is on whether to accept or reject the
general's bid for another eight years in the presidency. If he
fails to get a majority, Pinochet is supposed to call free
elections at the end of next year.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz met last week in New York
with Chilean Foreign Minister Ricardo Garcia and underscored the
United States favored a free and fair election.
   Other U.S. officials have made similar statements.
   Mrs. Oakley, at the State Department's daily briefing Tuesday,
said an ``official commitment'' had been provided by the Chilean
embassy in Washington and the Ministry of Interior in Santiago
``that the plebiscite will be carried out as scheduled and that its
result will be respected.''
   But she said ``concerns'' expressed by her Monday about the
circumstances surrounding the voting were based on ``sound
information.''
   Meanwhile, U.S. Ambassador Harry G. Barnes Jr., who will end his
assignment in November, told The New York Times in an interview in
Santiago that he would leave happier if Pinochet were defeated in
the plebiscite.
   ``I look forward to coming back in March 1990, when the first
democratically elected president would be inaugurated, if the `No'
wins, rather than having to wait until 1997,'' the 62-year-old
ambassador was quoted as saying.
   Barnes, who was an also-ran last year in the selection of a new
U.S. ambassador to the Soviet Union, is nearing the end of a
38-year diplomatic career.
   ``At this point,'' he said, ``I think the `No' will win if the
process doesn't get interrupted. That opens the way to free
elections. Our whole approach has been to promote a rapid return to
democracy, so it would be a nice way to leave, knowing that step
had been taken.''
   The Times said Barnes was credited with helping to make
possible, through continued U.S. pressure, a relatively free
campaign environment and reasonable assurance of an honest
proceeding on Wednesday.
   Mrs. Oakley, asked about the interview, said ``I simply am not
aware of those remarks,''
   She also reiterated that ``what we have said all along is that
we are in favor of a process, of a plebiscite, of a free expression
of the Chilean people. We have never expressed in any way our
opinion on what that vote ought to be. That remains clearly our
position.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
