<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1950EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RapeRecant     10-04 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rape Recant,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Rapist Seeks Pardon Based On New Scientific Evidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted rapist Gary Dotson should be pardoned
because new scientific evidence proves he was imprisoned ``for a
crime that never happened,'' his lawyer said Tuesday.
   In 1985, his accuser, now a New Hampshire housewife, said she
lied in 1977 when she said Dotson raped her.
   New high-technology DNA tests of blood and semen have
``concluded positively that Mr. Dotson is eliminated, excluded from
the forensic sample found in Cathleen Crowell Webb's panties,'' his
attorney, Thomas Breen, told the Illinois Prisoner Review Board
during a clemency hearing.
   But the Cook County state's attorney's office said a pardon
should not be granted because the tests were not reliable and would
not be admissible in Illinois courts.
   ``It is important that Dotson not be given the extraordinary
measure of pardon without more information on this new scientific
technology,'' said Assistant State's Attorney Gayle Shines.
   Paul Klincar, chairman of the Prisoner Review Board, said the
panel would make a recommendation to Gov. James Thompson in two to
three weeks and the governor would make the final decision.
   The governor commuted Dotson's 25- to 50-year rape sentence in
1985 to time served but rejected a request for clemency, saying he
did not believe Mrs. Webb's recantation.
   Dotson was released from prison in August after serving six
months for a parole violation and is enrolled in a residential
alcohol rehabilitation program. He was not at the hearing Tuesday.
   But his attorney said the new tests prove ``Mr. Dotson was in
fact arrested, convicted and sentenced for a crime that never
happened.''
   Dotson was convicted of rape in 1979. He had served six years
when Mrs. Webb came forward and said she had made up the story
while a suburban teen-ager to conceal a sexual encounter she had
had with her boyfriend.
   Genetic tests conducted by Dr. Edward Blake, a California
forensic expert, on Dotson's sperm and blood and semen on Mrs.
Webb's underwear showed the semen could have come from 5 percent of
the male population, but not from Dotson, Breen said.
   Blake's tests were different than DNA examinations performed on
the underwear earlier this year in England, Breen said. The British
tests were inconclusive because the 11-year-old sample was too old
to yield results.
   Mark Stolorow, director of research and development for the
Illinois State Police Division of Forensic Services and
Identification, said he agreed with Blake's findings.
   But Shines argued that Dotson might not have left semen in the
underwear.
   ``If the board determines that Dotson was not the donor of the
semen, that does not mean that Mrs. Webb was not raped,'' she said.
``Just as you don't need fingerprints to prove a robbery occurred,
you don't need semen to prove a rape occurred.''
   Breen rejected the idea, saying prosecutors had never before
suggested the theory.
   Since Dotson was first released from prison he has had several
scrapes with the law. He was jailed in 1987 for violating parole
and being convicted of drunken driving.
   On Christmas Eve, Thompson freed Dotson again in what the
governor called a ``last-chance deal.''
   Two days later, Dotson was arrested in a bar fight and in
February, the prison review board ordered him to serve six months
for a second parole violation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881004-0148 </DOCNO>
