<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-BurlingtonNorthern     10-04 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Burlington Northern,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blackmun Rejects Request to Block Possible Rail Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Supreme Court justice on Tuesday rejected an
emergency request by the Burlington Northern Railroad Co. designed
to block a possible strike against its 29,000-mile system.
   Justice Harry A. Blackmun refused to reinstate an anti-strike
injunction that was lifted on Sept. 30 by the 8th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals based in St. Louis.
   Burlington Northern said the appeals court order could mean
strike activities will be resumed against the railroad pending
further court appeals in a dispute between the railroad and the
United Transportation Union.
   The dispute was triggered by Burlington Northern's plan to sell
a section of its line in Montana and Idaho to the Montana Rail
Link, a new corporation.
   This type of transaction recently was exempted from review by
the Interstate Commerce Commission.
   The union threatened to strike after failing to block the sale
or get the railroad to negotiate over the planned sale.
   The 8th Circuit court last May refused to enjoin the union from
striking, but that ruling did not take effect until Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
