<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MyersonTrial     10-04 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Myerson Trial,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opening Arguments Begin In Myerson Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Miss America Bess Myerson and her
co-defendants in a divorce-fixing conspiracy trial ``decided they
could buy and sell justice,'' a federal prosecutor claimed Tuesday.
   ``This is a case about money, greed and abuse of power,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney David Lawrence told the jury in his opening
statement.
   Miss Myerson, 64, Miss America 1945, was the city's cultural
affairs commissioner before the scandal _ known locally as the
``Bess Mess'' _ forced her resignation.
   Describing Miss Myerson as ``one of the celebrities of New
York,'' Lawrence told the jurors: ``This case is about whether such
privileged people are above the law.''
   Also on trial are Miss Myerson's boyfriend, Carl ``Andy''
Capasso, 43, and former state Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel,
75, who presided over part of Capasso's bitter divorce from his
wife Nancy.
   The three face five counts each of conspiracy, mail fraud and
bribe-related charges for an alleged scheme to slash Capasso's
weekly child support and alimony payments.
   Miss Myerson is accused of giving a $19,000-a-year city job to
Mrs. Gabel's daughter, Sukhreet, who was then 34, to get the judge
to reduce Capasso's temporary support payments to his wife.
   Miss Myerson also is charged with obstructing justice for
allegedly trying to keep Sukhreet Gabel from testifying truthfully
before a federal grand jury.
   Capasso's attorney insisted in his opening that the case was
unjustified, stemming from a scorned wife's allegations.
   ``There was no fury as intense and mean-spirited as that of
Nancy Capasso,'' lawyer Jay Goldberg told the jury.
   Miss Myerson was named a co-respondent in the Capasso divorce.
   ``They are not on trial because of their affair,'' said
Lawrence. ``They are not on trial because of Mr. Capasso's divorce.
They are on trial because of the use of a city position, of the
city payroll, to pay for a bribe.''
   Ms. Gabel, who has been described in court papers as emotionally
fragile, will testify for the government, said Lawrence.
   ``At times, ladies and gentlemen, Sukhreet Gabel may not be a
pretty picture. In fact, some of the things she has to say will
shock you,'' said Lawrence, without elaborating.
   He said Ms. Gabel initially refused to cooperate with
prosecutors but eventually agreed to testify ``even if that meant
her testimony might be damaging to her mother.''
   Lawrence described Capasso and Miss Myerson as ``a millionaire
sewer contractor and his mistress who readily shared his wealth.''
Once a leading city sewer and water contractor, Capasso is serving
a three-year prison term for an unrelated tax conviction.
   Mrs. Gabel, he said, ``sold the courthouse,'' not for money but
out of ``concern that she had for her 34-year-old daughter, her
only child.''
   ``Myerson and Capasso's obsession with the divorce coincided
with Judge Gabel's obsession for finding employment for her
daughter,'' said the prosecutor.
   If convicted of all charges, Miss Myerson would face a maximum
penalty of 30 years in prison and $513,000 in fines. Capasso and
Mrs. Gabel would face up to 25 years in prison and $263,000 in
fines.
</TEXT>
