<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     10-04 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Four Towns; Four Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels staged
simultaneous attacks on army positions in four eastern towns, and
one soldier and three guerrillas were killed, the military said
Tuesday.
   Col. Inocente Orlando Montano, commander of the 6th Infantry
Brigade in the city of Usulutan, said 75 guerrillas accompanied by
about 150 unarmed civilian supporters attacked army posts on the
edge of the city Monday night.
   One soldier and two guerrillas were killed, a gasoline station
was destroyed and several homes were damaged, he said by telephone.
   Usulutan, a provincial capital, is 68 miles east of San Salvador.
   About the same time, the rebels attacked an army post in
Chinameca, 75 miles east of San Salvador in San Miguel province,
military sources there said. One guerrilla was killed, they said.
   Rebels also carried out attacks in two other Usulutan cities,
Jucuapa and Jiquilisco, but no deaths or injuries were reported,
Montano said.
   They destroyed a number of electrical installations in the
province, cutting service, he said.
   On the outskirts of San Salvador, guerrillas destroyed four
electricity poles but no major outages were reported.
   The leftist rebels frequently attack the electrical system to
cause disruptions and force the U.S.-backed government to spend
money on repairs.
   About 65,000 people, the majority of them civilians, have been
killed in the nearly 9-year-old war.
</TEXT>
