<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--ConservationPayments     10-04 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Conservation Payments,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers to Get $1.2 Billion from Conservation Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About $1.2 billion in cash payments soon will
be made to farmers under the Conservation Reserve Program, the
Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   Milton Hertz, executive vice president of the department's
Commodity Credit Corp., said the payments are rental fees for land
contracts signed in the 1986, 1987 and 1988 fiscal years.
   Under the program, farmers agree to take highly erodible
cropland from production for 10 years. In return, USDA helps pay
for planting the land to protective grass or trees and provides
annual rental payments over the 10-year contract period.
   The goal under the program is to take 40 million to 45 million
acres of highly erodible land from crop production by 1990. More
than 25.5 million acres have have been officially enrolled, and an
additional 3.4 million acres were offered by farmers in a recent
signup.
</TEXT>
