<HEAD>Congressman's Brother-In-Law Tests Negative for AIDS Virus
^Eds: Note language in 5th graf, `During a ....'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother-in-law of Rep. Robert K. Dornan
has taken an AIDS test and received a clean bill of health,
disproving a statement by his sister that he was dying of AIDS, the
Los Angeles Times reported Tuesday.
   ``I had a feeling I was strong and healthy,'' said Douglas
Richard Hansen, 51, a landscape architect from San Diego, who said
he hasn't spoken to his sister for several years.
   Hansen, who had maintained since his name was first brought up
that he did not have the deadly disease, offered to take an AIDS
test to end the controversy. The test, arranged by the newspaper's
medical department, indicated no sign of the infection by the AIDS
virus.
   During a contentious town hall meeting with homosexual leaders
in Garden Grove last month, Hansen's sister, Sallie Dornan, yelled,
``Shut up, fag'' to a gay rights activist.
   Later, Mrs. Dornan emotionally apologized and said the remark
came out of anger over the fact that one of her four brothers was
dying of AIDS.
   A relative who saw the news reports called Hansen to tell him
about the meeting.
   Neither Dornan, a Republican, nor his wife would comment Monday
on the test results. Mrs. Dornan is campaign manager for her
husband's re-election bid in the 38th Congressional District.
   Dornan's chief of staff, Brian Bennett, said of the results:
``We're very glad of that, then. That's excellent.''
   He added: ``This has absolutely nothing to do with Congressman
Bob Dornan. This is between his wife and her brother.''
   Hansen said he has forgiven his sister for the remarks she made
about him at the meeting. He had said earlier he had not heard from
his sister in several years and had not gotten along with her
husband since a dispute the two had more than 30 years ago.
   ``I know she's a good woman,'' Hansen said of his sister. ``I'll
love her till I die. And when and if that turkey husband of hers
tumbles off his little pedestal, I'll be there to catch my sister.
But he can keep falling.''
</TEXT>
