<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CadetsStricken     10-04 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Stricken,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Graduates Gather To Defend Police Academy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AGAWAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Graduates of a police academy that is under
fire for a recent rash of cadet illnesses met Tuesday to defend the
institution against accusations of abusive physical training.
   ``The training is necessarily tough,'' said a spokeswoman for
the group, Amherst Patrolman Colleen Griswold. ``It brings out your
inner strength. ... It does not turn you into a Gestapo henchman.''
   Griswold read from a statement while 28 other graduates from a
half-dozen classes stood behind her on the steps of the Agawam
academy.
   At least 16 cadets were hospitalized for dehydration and
exhaustion after one trainee collapsed on the first day of
training, Sept. 19. The academy was closed on the third day of
training and classes were moved to a National Guard Armory because
of suspicions surrounding the drinking water.
   The water has been declared untainted by state environmental
officials and attention has turned toward the degree of physical
exertion demanded of the cadets.
   One of the cadets, Timothy Shepard of Pittsfield, remained in a
coma at a Pittsburgh hospital Tuesday, 15 days after his collapse
and a week after a liver transplant, although his sister-in-law
said he appeared to turn his head and recognize his mother and
pregnant wife.
   ``He may be starting to come out of the coma,'' said Becky
Shepard.
   The former cadets said they were mystified by the maladies that
hit a third of a class of 50 cadets under the leadership of one
state trooper who had formerly served as second-in-command and an
assistant who had previously taught water safety at the academy.
   The commandant, John M. Richardson, and his assistant, Charles
Blake Gilmore, were reassigned Tuesday at their request.
   Griswold called Gilmore as ``a qualified, sensitive individual.
... I am terrified of water and he made me feel comfortable in it.''
   She also had no complaints about Richardson from her 14-week
class, which ended in January. She was the only woman to graduate
from her class, which lost a dozen cadets during the course from an
original group of 42.
   A cadet who dropped out of the current training program said
last week that the recruits exercised for more than 10 hours the
first day on only a few small cups of water. Cadets who dropped out
of previous classes spoke of being pushed to their emotional and
physical limits.
   Griswold defended the academy's so-called stress training and
said she was never denied water or pushed beyond her limits. ``The
training is physically demanding but not physically abusive,'' she
said.
   ``Some people come here young and immature, never having been
yelled at on the street or in their lives,'' Griswold said. The
training ``helps us to be able to have patience at trying moments.''
   As police officers, she said, ``we know how much patience it
takes not to lash out when people call you vicious names, insult
your mother, spit on you or strike you. We learned to stand fast
and tolerate that in this very program that has come under fire.''
   The academy's training practices will come under review later
this week by a panel of doctors, exercise researchers and law
enforcement administrators appointed by Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   A team of investigators from the state attorney general's office
already is questioning witnesses about the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
