<HEAD>Doctor Says Lowry Suffering From Ulcer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Mike Lowry, Democratic Senate candidate
in Washington state, has an ulcer and is expected to remain
hospitalized in Chicago until later this week, according to a
statement released by his congressional office Tuesday.
   Lowry had been given two units of blood and was in good
condition at the intensive care unit of Resurrection Medical
Center, Dr. Stan Maslanka, Jr. said in the statement.
   Maslanka said there were no indications of any ``long-term''
problems and Lowry should be able to return to work in three or
four days.
   Lowry, 49, was on his way back from a weekend of campaigning
when he collapsed aboard a late-night ``red eye'' flight from
Seattle to Washington, D.C., early Monday. He was taken from the
United Airlines flight at O'Hare Airport in Chicago and carried by
ambulance to the hospital where tests showed he might have loss
blood.
   ``We have to monitor the blood count (oxygen level) to make sure
it doesn't drop,'' Maslanka said. ``I expect that his health will
be perfect again and I don't expect he'll have a recurrence if he
follows (diet) instructions I give him.''
   Kathleen Murphy, a Lowry spokeswoman who was in Chicago, said he
was in good condition and his spirits were high, but he was bored.
   ``He has his mind on a lot of things, including national health
care,'' she said.
   Staffers said Lowry had complained for several weeks of
bronchitis, the flu or a cold and had been unable to recover
because of his hectic schedule.
</TEXT>
