<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VinylChurch     10-04 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vinyl Church,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Members Debate Vinyl Siding On Historic Structure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The minister of a 218-year-old church
says he's deeply disappointed his parishioners have decided to go
ahead with plans to cover the historic building with vinyl siding.
   ``They might as well polyurethane the tombstones or put
AstroTurf in the front yard,'' the Rev. John N. Svendsen of
Westminster Congregational Church said after Monday night's 9-3
vote.
   ``But I also realize ... that the most important thing is that
the gospel of Jesus Christ will be preached, whether the church is
vinyl or painted,'' Svendsen said. ``And that will not change.''
   Church members decided in August to put vinyl siding on the
quaint, white church, the fourth-oldest church or meeting house in
Connecticut, as a way to preserve the building without the expense
of painting so often.
   But historians contend the move will harm the church's
appearance and could ultimately be destructive by hiding structural
problems such as moisture damage.
   Work is expected to begin in November and will cost about $8,000.
   The church was founded in 1770 by Capt. Sherebiah Butts and his
seven sons. Forty to 50 people attend services regularly today,
although only about 12 are voting members.
   Four large pillars grace the portico and a cross sits atop a
squared steeple. The church has been altered significantly several
times since it was built, but retains many original touches,
including a hanging balcony, wide-board flooring and hand-hewn
details in wooden pews.
   Outside stands a granite whipping post, once used for public
discipline. Behind the church, more than two dozen Revolutionary
War soldiers are buried.
   Representatives of the Canterbury Historical Society and the
Connecticut Historical Society urged the church's voting members
Monday night to abandon the vinyl plan, Svendsen said.
   The Canterbury Historical Society had offered to donate $5,000
toward a paint job, Svendsen said.
   ``We're not destroying the church. We're preserving it for
future generations,'' said A. Earl MacLeod, the church's deacon
emeritus. He said vinyl siding would cost about half as much as
painting and last as many as 40 years. A paint job lasts seven to
10 years.
   But Christopher P. Bickford, director of the Connecticut
Historical Society and a resident of Canterbury, said serious
historical and aesthetic damage would be wrought by vinyl siding.
   ``Eastern Connecticut is changing so very rapidly we ought to
try to hold onto those historical sites that are more or less
intact,'' Bickford said. ``Anyone who looks at a historical
building that has been covered (with siding) it just isn't the same
building. It becomes encased and mummified.''
   Susan Chandler, a historical architect with the Connecticut
Historical Commission, said vinyl siding can ultimately lead to the
destruction of historical buildings.
   ``There is a high potential for structural deterioration due to
the impervious nature of the new materials _ moisture, rot,
infestation,'' Chandler said. She said the siding can mean such
damage is undetected and ``you can get to the point of almost total
structural failure.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881004-0163 </DOCNO>
