<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rice Researcher Wins World Food Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Robert F. Chandler Jr., an agricultural
researcher and founding director of the International Rice Research
Institute in the Philippines, was awarded the $200,000 World Food
Prize Tuesday night.
   The prize, sponsored by the General Foods Fund, Inc., recognizes
outstanding contributors to improving the quality, quantity or
availability of food in the world.
   ``Under Dr. Chandler's guidance, IRRI developed and distributed
new varieties of rice with double and triple the yield potential of
traditional rice,'' General Foods Fund said in a news release.
``Largely because of this, famine in Asia was averted in the
1970s.''
   Chandler, who resides in Clermont, Fla., and Raymond, Maine, is
a former president of the University of New Hampshire.
</TEXT>
