<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1744EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DebateStakes     10-04 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate Stakes,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle In Spotlight As Debate Tests Dukakis Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debate between vice presidential
candidates will go a long way toward determining whether George
Bush was wise when he picked Dan Quayle for a running mate _ and
whether Michael Dukakis was wise to make a major issue of it.
   Not that Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd Bentsen
isn't sharing top billing in the 90-minute encounter in Omaha, with
all the potential political profits and perils that go with it.
   But after a campaign of controversy and criticism, Quayle is the
man in the spotlight.
   A positive performance by the 41-year-old Indiana senator, and
Bush's bid to spice his ticket with a handsome representative of a
younger generation will seem vindicated. Bentsen could seem every
bit of the 26 years older that he is.
   Republicans would then breathe a sigh of relief and hope nothing
happens before Election Day to reverse their seeming edge in the
campaign for the White House.
   A poor performance by Quayle, and the post-debate debate will
turn on whether Bush can somehow contain the resultant damage.
   Dukakis would step up the steady drumbeat of criticism that Bush
had picked a man not fit to be a heartbeat away from the White
House and trumpet the steady, mature experience of his man Bentsen.
   Bush took his lumps earlier in the campaign for picking Quayle.
His senior aides went to pains to tell reporters that the vice
president made his choice without their approval _ a sure sign that
he wouldn't have gotten it. The controversy over Quayle's
Vietnam-era service in the National Guard, his mediocre academic
record and the general furor produced a few suggestions that he
should consider leaving the ticket.
   He didn't and Bush stood by his man.
   Dukakis hasn't let up, though, in a less-noticed but still risky
campaign gamble.
   Traditional political tactics dictate that a candidate avoid
public disputes with a staff aide to a rival and that the man at
the top of the ticket not be drawn into a dispute with someone
further down.
   The reason is obvious _ as Walter F. Mondale found out in 1984
when he sought to brutalize Bush for offering blind loyalty to
Ronald Reagan. Bush, then the understudy on the GOP ticket, was
delighted to maintain a public quarrel with the leading Democrat,
leaving Reagan free to remain above the fray.
   Dukakis' aides insist that Quayle's selection gives them an
excellent issue, a window on the type of decision Bush would make
as president. But if Quayle performs well in the debate it could
well be that they missed their issue all along.
   Televised vice presidential debates are a relatively new
phenomenon in presidential campaigning. The first one was in 1976,
when Republican Bob Dole, trying to deflect a question about the
Watergate scandal, blurted out that World War I, World War II and
Korea were ``Democrat wars.''
   Democrat Walter F. Mondale replied that Dole had richly earned
his reputation as a hatchet-man, and the controversy that followed
was blamed by some Republicans for contributing to the narrow GOP
defeat that fall.''
   Four years ago a vice president named Bush debated his rival,
Democrat Geraldine Ferraro. The session is best remembered for
Bush's morning-after boast that he'd ``kicked a little ass.''
   Bush and the Republicans would be quite happy if this year's
debate produced nothing particularly memorable _ and if Quayle
avoided the temptation to brag about it afterwards.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Espo covers the presidential campaign for
The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881004-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-StealthFighter 1stLd-Writethru a0669 10-04 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stealth Fighter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0669,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phantom Airplane Remains Under Wraps as Unveiling Scrubbed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 6th graf, ``The Washington,'' with newspaper
report</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department decided at the last
moment Tuesday to cancel an unveiling of its Stealth jet fighter,
forcing a senator to scrub a news conference and the Pentagon's
spokesman to reassert an official shroud of secrecy over the
radar-evading plane.
   By the time the behind-the-scenes maneuverings ended, there was
little doubt an airplane that officially doesn't exist, does.
   Doug Fuller, a spokesman for Sen. Chic Hecht, R-Nev., said the
senator had planned to discuss the Stealth fighter program with
reporter Tuesday afternoon after the Pentagon released details
about the plane for the first time. According to defense sources,
the Stealth fighters built for the Air Force are based at a tightly
guarded facility in Hecht's state.
   ``He was going to discuss the program as a whole,'' said Fuller,
but the news conference was canceled after Hecht received a
telephone call from the Pentagon.
   ``We really haven't received much in the way of an explanation,
other than word from DOD that the department's release of
information has been put on indefinite hold,'' Fuller said. ``The
senator will respect that, of course. He's not going to release
information on his own.''
   The Washington Times had reported in Tuesday editions that the
Pentagon planned to release a short detail sheet and photograph of
the Stealth fighter this week, possibly as early as Tuesday.
   Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman, found himself unable
to acknowledge the department had been close to releasing
information on the jet, to explain why a public unveiling had been
canceled or to confirm there is such a thing as a Stealth fighter.
   ``I do not know of any briefing that is currently under
consideration to take place at any time in the foreseeable future
with regard to any special aircraft,'' Howard told reporters. ``I
can't provide any additional information to you. I'm sorry.''
   At another point, though, without referring to a Stealth
fighter, Howard said: ``I think you all understand that there are
proposals that arise from time to time from various levels within
this building and within the services to do briefings on this or
that weapon system and the like, and not all those proposals are
ultimately approved.
   ``In this case, I think the results are fairly obvious.''
   According to military and industry sources, the United States
secretly began building Stealth jet fighters in the mid-1970s and
now maintains more than 50 of the single-seat planes at the Nevada
base. The plane has been dubbed the F-19 by various industry
officials but reportedly also carries the military designation of
F-117A.
   The Pentagon and Air Force have never acknowledged the
airplane's existence, even when pressed about mysterious crashes
over the years.
   According to the sources, the planes are flown only at night and
are kept at a high state of readiness for use as ``aerial shock
troops,'' capable of slipping behind enemy lines without being
detected and creating confusion with unexpected bombing runs.
   Defense sources who requested anonymity said Tuesday the idea of
unveiling the plane had been debated at the highest levels of the
Defense Department and on Capitol Hill before being rejected ``for
the time being.''
   ``There were concerns at the top of the military hierarchy. And
there was a bipartisan view that this was not the most auspicious
time for this. Maybe later,'' said one official. Asked whether the
plane be unveiled after the presidential election, he replied:
``Possibly.''
   The sources said a proposal to show off the plane had been
advanced for several reasons.
   First, explained one official, the Air Force already has
announced it will unveil its new Stealth bomber next month and that
plane is based on more recent technological developments than the
fighter. The planes use special designs and materials to reduce
their exposure to radar.
   ``It doesn't make sense to let people see one and not the
other,'' the official noted.
   Moreover, the source continued, disclosing the fighter and its
successful record could help strengthen support on Capitol Hill for
the new wing of bombers.
   The sources said another factor supporting disclosure involved
an upcoming legal fight. Production line workers at a Lockheed
Corp. plant in Burbank, Calif., where the Stealth fighters are said
to be built, have gone to court with charges they are being
sickened by exposure to dangerous chemicals.
   Pentagon officials have concluded the court fight is likely to
shatter the secrecy surrounding the plane.
   Howard appeared to lend weight to that argument Tuesday. Again
without referring specifically to the plane or to Lockheed, he
said: ``The litigation is one of the problems, but I just cannot
take this further.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
