<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AmtrakCrash     10-04 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amtrak Crash,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Conrail Can't Get Paid By Amtrak For Claims From Fatal
Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conrail cannot seek indemnification from
Amtrak for damage claims arising from the deaths of 16 people last
year when a Conrail engine was hit by an Amtrak passenger train, a
federal judge ruled.
   U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch ruled that the indemnification
agreement between Amtrak and Conrail cannot be enforced because of
evidence that gross and willful negligence by the Conrail crew
caused the Jan. 4, 1987 accident near Chase, Md.
   The collision occurred north of Baltimore after the Conrail
engineer and brakeman ignored a series of railroad signals before
the freight engine entered the path of an oncoming high-speed
Amtrak passenger train.
   If upheld, the ruling signed late Monday means that Conrail
would be solely responsible for defending more than 60 wrongful
death and personal injury suits that seek millions of dollars in
damages.
   ``Conrail is studying the decision and has no comment,''
spokeswoman Pat Linskey said Tuesday.
   Conrail had sought to force Amtrak to defend the suits and pay
any damages awarded under the terms of the Northeast Corridor
Freight Operating Agreement that provides that Amtrak pay for
claims ``irrespective of any negligence of fault of Conrail.''
   Gasch said that it was unclear, based on the language of the
agreement and the negotiating history, whether the parties intended
it to apply to cases of gross negligence.
   But even if the agreement were clear, ``public policy will not
allow enforcement of indemnification provisions that appear to
cover such extreme misconduct because serious and significant
disincentives to railroad safety would ensure,'' Gasch said.
   Gasch noted that the Conrail engineer, Ricky Lynn Gates, who
pleaded guilty to manslaughter and received a five-year prison
term, admitted the crew had used marijuana before the accident and
violated a number of safety procedures.
</TEXT>
