<HEAD>Fire Damages Home Being Built For Merv Griffin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA QUINTA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire damaged a $1.75 million house
under construction for producer-entrepreneur Merv Griffin at a
desert country club Tuesday, and fire officials estimated damage at
$1 million.
   The cause of the fire was not immediately determined, officials
said.
   The fire was reported just before 7 a.m. in the PGA West Country
Club development near Palm Springs, said Tim Spann, spokesman for
the Riverside County Fire Department.
   The house, about 110 miles east of Los Angeles, was 80 percent
complete when it burned, ``And a little more than half of it was
destroyed,'' said fire Capt. Brenda Seabert.
   Griffin, the talk show host-turned TV producer-turned hotel
mogul, has many homes, once saying real estate is ``a nice
complement to show business.''
   Griffin, 63, taped his last ``Merv Griffin Show'' in September
1986, ending a 24-year career as a television talk show host. He
sold his production company soon afterward, but still produces
television movies, specials, comedy series and game shows,
including the successful ``Wheel of Fortune.''
