<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-Governors     10-04 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Governors,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Many Democrats Ready To Defect</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan argued Tuesday that even
though voters might be ``a little cautious'' about voting
Republican this fall, the election will ultimately be a referendum
on the future of the Democratic Party.
   ``It's way too early to say that this is the realignment
election,'' Reagan said in remarks prepared for a speech to the
Governors' Club, a group of GOP state chief executives. ``But I do
think many rank-and-file Democrats are getting in a mood to say to
their party leadership: `You've gone too far to the left. Return to
the political mainstream.'''
   The president addressed the club's fund-raising dinner, expected
to glean $750,000 for the Republican National Committee.
   He cited GOP gains from 1984 in states like Texas and North
Carolina. This year, he said, ``I've been out on the campaign trail
lately and I'm just starting to wonder if this year there isn't
something in the air.''
   Since the convention, Reagan has gleaned millions of dollars for
the GOP with his speaking appearances on behalf of Vice President
George Bush's quest for the White House.
   A one-time Democrat himself, Reagan acknowledged that it's
difficult to get people to change their loyalties.
   ``There's plenty of disenchantment out there with that other
party, but we have to realize that people are still a little
cautious about our party,'' Reagan said.
   The president did not detail what might make voters tentative
about the Republicans. But he argued that many Democrats have been
attracted by his party's long-time anti-tax and anti-big government
stands, as well as ``a whole range of social issues from the Pledge
of Allegiance to school prayer to the radical agenda of some
far-left legal groups.''
   Bush has repeatedly criticized Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis for vetoing a state law that would have forced
Massachusetts teachers to lead their students in reciting the
Pledge each day.
   Reagan said ``this campaign may be starting to break out as a
referendum on liberalism itself, a referendum on the direction in
which the liberals have taken the once-proud Democratic Party.''
   ``The public agrees with us when we say we are for the death
penalty, school prayer, tough law enforcement and against liberal
organizations like the ACLU that always seem to be searching for
technicalities to exonerate criminals,'' Reagan argued, echoing
Bush's criticism of Dukakis for being a self-proclaimed
``card-carrying member'' of the American Civil Liberties Union.
   ``Rank-and-file Democrats are going to say `no' to the liberal
leadership (of the Democratic Party) by saying `yes' to George Bush
and the Republican Party,'' Reagan told his partisan audience.
</TEXT>
