<DOCNO> AP881004-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1849EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CBS-TimesPoll     10-04 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS-Times Poll,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Helping Dukakis in CBS-Times Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national poll Tuesday said the Democratic
presidential ticket was benefiting from doubts about Republican
vice presidential nominee Sen. Dan Quayle. It put the race at
essentially a dead heat.
   The Republican ticket of George Bush and Quayle drew the support
of 48 percent of the probable voters in the CBS News-New York Times
poll, while the Democrats, Michael Dukakis and Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
got 46 percent.
   When the 1,034 respondents were asked what if they were voting
only for the presidential nominees, without their running mates,
the support for Dukakis declined to 43 percent, CBS reported.
Bush's remained at 48 percent.
   That finding indicated that Quayle, while not cutting into
Bush's own support, was pushing some undecided voters to Dukakis.
Quayle, of Indiana, and Bentsen, of Texas, meet in their only
debate of the campaign Wednesday night.
   In another measure of concern about Quayle, respondents were
split evenly on whether he understands the complicated problems a
president has to deal with: Forty-one percent said he does, but 40
percent said not.
   On Bentsen, by contrast, 71 percent said he does understand the
problems a president must confront, and only 13 percent said not.
   The 48-46 race was a statistical dead heat given the poll's
margin of error or plus or minus three percentage points. A
CBS-Times poll done Sept. 21-23 put the race at 49 percent for Bush
and Quayle to 44 percent for Dukakis and Bentsen, also a
statistical tie given the error margin.
   The new survey was conducted Saturday through Monday.
</TEXT>
