<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TV-Frank'sPlace     10-04 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV-Frank's Place,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Cancels `Frank's Place; Fox Dumps `The Late Show'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Frank's Place,'' the critically acclaimed but
low- rated comedy starring Tim Reid as the owner of a Creole
restaurant in New Orleans, was canceled Tuesday by the CBS
television network.
   ``Frank's Place'' was named best comedy by the Television
Critics Association in August. Later that month, its
creator-producer Hugh Wilson won an Emmy for writing. Reid, the
show's co-executive producer, was nominated for an Emmy as lead
actor in a comedy.
   CBS Entertainment President Kim LeMasters did not put the show
on the network's fall schedule but promised it would be added later
when a suitable time period could be found. But he said in a
statement released by CBS on Tuesday that it would not return.
   While it had support from CBS, television critics and a broad
spectrum of the entertainment community, LeMasters said,
``Unfortunately, the viewing audience simply failed to respond to
it.''
   The show started out on Monday nights, but was later moved in
CBS' ill-fated attempt to program comedies on Tuesday night. Then
it was shunted off to the low-rated Saturday lineup where it has
languished in or near last place in the Nielsens. Its last
broadcast was last Saturday.
   In another development, Fox Broadcasting Co. is scrapping its
on-again, off-again ``The Late Show'' after two troubled years.
   In Los Angeles, Fox spokesman Brad Turell said word on a
replacement for the `The Late Show' should come later this week.
   ``The Late Show,'' the first effort by the network, made its
debut in October 1986 with Joan Rivers as the host. The show was
plagued by low ratings and Rivers was fired in May 1987.
   Arsenio Hall became the permanent host in summer 1987, after a
series of rotating hosts. It was replaced with ``The Wilton North
Report,'' which was panned by the critics and ignored by the
audience.
   It was canceled after four weeks and replaced by a new version
of ``The Late Show'' with comedians Jeff Joseph and John Mulrooney
as rotating hosts.
   In April, Ross Shafer, a former Seattle radio and television
personality and comedian, became host.
</TEXT>
