<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Elections 1stLd-Writethru   10-04 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0673,0787</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parties Trade Accusations As Election Campaign Starts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS grafs 1-3 and SUBS 5 grafs for 20th `The Jerusalem
Post' with description of ads</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's election campaign began in earnest
Tuesday with both major parties trading accusations about an
``Israeli Watergate'' and running television ads to woo undecided
voters.
   Politicians came out swinging at the end of the Jewish holiday
period, ending weeks of low-key campaigning for the Nov. 1 election.
   The campaign's first confrontation between the right-wing Likud
bloc and the left-of-center Labor Party focused on what has been
called the ``Israeli Watergate,'' after the scandal that forced
President Nixon to resign in 1974.
   Likud accused Labor of bugging Likud campaign headquarters and
of tapping the home phone of campaign chairman Moshe Arens, a
Cabinet minister and former ambassador to the United States.
   ``This is a serious affair,'' said Likud spokesman Danny Naveh.
``We have serious suspicions that this is an Israeli Watergate, and
that Labor is responsible.''
   Asked about evidence, Naveh said Arens heard clicking in his
line and the minister's wife saw prowlers in her yard last week.
   Shimon Peres, the Labor Party chief and foreign minister in the
coalition government formed with Likud after a 1984 election
stalemate, denounced the allegations as ridiculous and without
foundation.
   ``This is puppet theater, and I don't see any real person there
on stage,'' Peres during a campaign swing in northern Israel.
   Added Ezer Weizman, Labor's campaign leader: ``They are in a
panic because our campaign is better than theirs.''
   Naveh also said that Labor hired two former agents of Israel's
Shin Bet security service to spy on Likud. Labor officials denied
the allegation, saying the two were consultants providing security
for party facilities.
   Likud officials asked Attorney General Yosef Harish to
investigate Labor, Israel radio said. Harish said he would consider
the request.
   Israeli commentators predicted the affair would not have a
far-reaching impact.
   ``This mutual mudslinging is just part of the campaign heating
up,'' said Emanuel Gutmann, a political science professor at Hebrew
University in Jerusalem. ``I wouldn't get excited about it.''
   Earlier in the campaign, a squabble broke out over a recorded
Labor Party telephone message with the sounds of sirens and
breaking glass that suggested Shamir's policies would lead to war.
   ``Shamir said `no' to the peace with Egypt, he said `no' to King
Hussein. Shamir said `yes' to the inflation, `yes' to the
intefadeh, he will say `yes' to the next war,'' the announcer said.
   Enraged Likud activists kept the telephone line busy.
   Intefadeh is the Arabic term used to describe the 10-month
Palestinian uprising in Israel's occupied territories.
   Also Tuesday, the parties launched television campaign ads
designed to sway undecided voters, estimated by polls at more than
25 percent of the electorate.
   The ads will play a particularly important role because the
state-owned Israel TV and radio stations are banned from
broadcasting interviews with candidates in the final 30 days before
the vote.
   In their television spots, Shamir and Peres referred to the
Palestinian uprising only briefly, although both parties have
called Middle East peace the crucial issue of the campaign.
   Both men laid claim to Israel's economic recovery, and Peres
took credit for Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon in 1985.
   Likud presented slick spots with an upbeat jingle, flag-waving
children and Shamir calling for a fair campaign. Little mention was
made of Labor or its policies.
   Labor was more aggressive, contrasting its positions to Likud's.
A stern-voiced announcer said hyperinflation and entanglement in
Lebanon came after Likud had been in the government seven years.
   Israel radio said each side had prepared uncomplimentary film
clips and would use them if the other side engaged in ``character
assassination.''
   Israeli voters will be exposed to about 1,000 minutes of
television campaign spots before the election. Clusters of ads are
run in a 45-minute period after the evening news.
   Each of the 28 parties running for 120 seats in the Knesset is
allotted 10 minutes of television time. In addition, parties now
represented in parliament get six minutes for each seat. Labor and
Likud have more than four hours each of free television time.
   Radio ads begin Wednesday.
   Elihu Katz, a pollster and founding director of Israel
television, criticized the ban on TV and radio coverage of
candidates, saying voters were being deprived of valuable
information.
   But he said the campaign ads ``waste a huge amount of money. The
large parties have so much time they could run quiz shows and soap
operas.''
</TEXT>
