<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-04 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Showers Fall in Upper Michigan, Chill Weather in the Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers dotted many parts of the country Tuesday and
temperatures slipped lower as autumn began to make itself felt.
Farmers in the northern Plains and Upper Mississippi Valley were
advised to watch for nighttime freezing.
   The worst weather was in Upper Michigan, where brisk northerly
winds blowing across lakes Michigan and Superior combined with
temperatures in the mid 30s to create a wind chill as low as 11
degrees. The cool air and moisture also brought snow showers, sleet
and light rain to the area.
   Showers fell over western Oklahoma, the Texas Panhandle and
western Kansas. In the East, rain lingered along the coasts of
North Carolina, Virginia and the New England. Florida had scattered
thunderstorms.
   Clear skies and cool temperatures spread across the northern
Plains and Upper Mississippi Valley, prompting freeze advisories
for Tuesday night for Iowa, Minnesota, northern Illinois, northeast
Kansas, southwest Nebraska, most of Wisconsin and Upper Michigan
and northwest Lower Michigan.
   In the West, rain and fog spread over western Oregon and
Washington.
   Temperatures Tuesday afternoon only reached the 30s in northwest
Nebraska, western Kansas and eastern Colorado, and the 40s in the
northern Plains, the upper Mississippi Valley and Great Lakes, and
northern New England.
   Temperatures were in the 70s in most of Texas, the lower
Mississippi Valley and the Gulf Coast states, the southern Atlantic
coast, the Southwest and parts of California, and in the 80s in
southern Florida and the desert Southwest.
   The rest of the country had temperatures in the 50s and 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 35
degrees at Imperial, Neb., to 98 degrees at Phoenix and Yuma, Ariz.
   The low early Tuesday was 17 degrees at Bismarck, N.D.
   Showers were forecast for Wednesday in New England, the lower
Great Lakes and northern Appalachians, with scattered showers and
thunderstorms in southern Florida. It will be cloudy in the Pacific
Northwest, cloudy to partly cloudy over the western Plains and
sunny elsewhere.
   Wednesday's highs were expected in the 40s from the Great Lakes
to the northern Appalachians and in northern New England; in the
70s from coastal California to the central and southern Rockies, in
southern Texas and along the Gulf Coast to northern Florida,
Georgia and South Carolina; in the 80s in southern Florida, the
Southwest and California's inland valleys, with temperatures up to
105 degrees in the desert.
   The rest of the nation will be seasonably cool, with highs in
the 50s and 60s.
</TEXT>
