<1ST_LINE>r w AM-D.C.Jail     10-04 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-D.C. Jail,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>District of Columbia Rejecting New Jail Inmates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia Department of
Corrections closed the city's crowded prison system to new inmates
Tuesday to comply with a court order.
   City Corrections Director Hallem Williams said the policy means
that the federal government is responsible for finding places to
incarcerate new prisoners. He said he could provide no specifics
about arrangements.
   But a spokesman for the U.S. Marshals Service, Steve Boyle, said
officials from the Justice Department were ``still trying to decide
how to resolve the problem.''
   The city stopped admitting new inmates to its jail because of an
order issued last Thursday by U.S. District Judge William B. Bryant
that the district reduce its jail population to under 1,694
prisoners. That order took effect at noon Tuesday, when there were
1,942 prisoners at the jail, according to Williams.
   ``At this juncture we have no remaining alternatives to deal
with today's crisis,'' said Williams. ``We are in a crisis
situation. Everywhere we step, there is a minefield.''
   The action also meant that new inmates were also being barred
from the city's Lorton Correctional Complex in nearby Fairfax
County, Va.
   A separate appeals court ruling, also issued last Thursday,
requires the city to reduce the population at Lorton's Central
facility to 1,166 by Nov. 1. There were 1,406 inmates at Lorton on
Tuesday.
   Corrections officials were scheduled to present their plan for
alleviating overcrowding to Bryant on Wednesday morning.
   On Monday, district Mayor Marion Barry authorized the early
release of 350 prisoners from the entire system by Nov. 11,
Williams announced at a news conference Tuesday.
   About 130 inmates will be sent to other jurisdictions, such as
the state of Washington, over the next three weeks.
   And the city is setting up a program in which it pays
contractors to post bond of $2,000 or less and then monitor certain
poor inmates awaiting trial, at a cost to the district of up to
$300,000.
   Williams said the city had not choice but to take the actions.
   ``It's not a situation where there's a winner or a loser,'' he
said. ``It's a situation where there are lots of losers.''
</TEXT>
