<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ProstitutionIndictments     10-04 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prostitution Indictments,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former City Chief Indicted for Sex With Teens</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former mayoral candidate who was the
city's chief administrator for 10 years has been indicted with 13
others for having sex with teen-age girls at a brothel.
   The indictments Monday followed a 16-month investigation into an
operation police say earned $20,000 a week by providing prostitutes
as young as 14 to customers in the San Francisco Bay area, Los
Angeles, Idaho and Washington.
   Roger Boas, chief executive under former Mayors George Moscone
and Dianne Feinstein, was allegedly identified by five underage
prostitutes as the regular client they knew as ``George.'' The
67-year-old car dealer and politician later was picked out of a
photo lineup in front of a grand jury.
   Boas, who also served from 1962 to 1973 as a city supervisor,
ran for mayor last year, coming in a close third.
   In a three-minute appearance before reporters Tuesday, Boas did
not deny involvement with prostitutes and refused to answer
questions on the subject. He hinted he was being targeted unfairly
by District Attorney Arlo Smith.
   ``During my entire life, I have always done my utmost to be
constructive, honest and productive,'' he said. ``For my family's
sake ... I am truly saddened that someone in the criminal justice
system tried to convict me in the media using leaks, rumors and
innuendo in advance of the legal process.''
   His attorney, John Keker, said he expected Boas to be acquitted
of all charges.
   Boas, his attorney and Smith would not disclose specifics of the
indictment. The San Francisco Chronicle and the San Francisco
Examiner reported on the indictments extensively, quoting
unidentified City Hall sources.
   Boas reportedly faces 18 counts of unlawful sex with minors
during the last three years.
   Those indicted faced possible felony charges that could carry up
to three years in prison.
   The girls told police they had been coached to act as young as
possible with their clients, who they were told paid a premium for
sex with minors.
   A 32-year-old police officer, Patrick Miyagishima, reportedly
faces two counts of having unlawful sex with a minor.
   ``I'm not even admitting my client was there (at the brothel),''
said Miyagishima's attorney, William Murphy.
   A prominent jeweler, John Azevedo, 46, was charged with four
counts of having unlawful sex with minors, according to his
attorney, Patrick Hallinan.
   Hallinan acknowledged that Azevedo had sex with prostitutes
``four or five times'' at his store during the past four years. But
the lawyer said his client had no idea they were so young.
   ``This is a terrible, terrible personal tragedy for my client
that's motivated so clearly only by the district attorney's desire
to cover the fact that he is really out to get Boas,'' Hallinan
said.
</TEXT>
