<DOCNO> AP881004-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1921EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AutoSales     10-04 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1988 Model Year Is 3rd Best</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers posted their third-best sales year in
history Tuesday, as car and light truck buyers in the United States
drove away more than 15.6 million vehicles during the 1988 model
year, the companies reported.
   With a few of the small-volume foreign makers holding sales
figures until Wednesday, companies selling cars and light trucks in
the United States said they sold 0.7 percent more vehicles in 1988
than the 15.5 million vehicles sold during the 1987 model year.
   ``That's pretty good, all things considered, when they (were)
expected to be flat or down a bit,'' said analyst Mary Anne Sudol
of Fitch Investors Service Inc. of New York.
   ``I think it's particularly surprising in light of what the
initial expectations were post-Oct. 19 of last year'' when the
stock market crashed, said analyst Douglas Laughlin of Bear, Sterns
& Co. of New York. ``I was looking more for 14 million in that
period. I had to consistently raise it through the period.''
   The 1988 model year ran behind 1986, when 16.1 million vehicles
left showrooms, and 1985 when 15.7 million cars and light trucks
were sold.
   While the annual total was upbeat, sales during the last 10-day
period were sharply lower than a year ago, when end-of-model-year
fire sales and lingering incentives attracted people to dealerships.
   Sales of U.S.-made cars fell 9.1 percent to 250,416 from 275,461
during the Sept. 21-30 period this year, compared with the same
period last year. There were nine selling days in both periods.
   U.S.-made truck sales, meanwhile, gained slightly in late
September, rising to 131,915 in the period this year, compared with
130,144 at the same time last year, a 1.4 percent increase.
   For the month, sales of domestically made trucks rose 5.3
percent, to 319,326 vehicles compared with 303,202 during September
1987. The boost in U.S.-made trucks apparently came at the expense
of foreign truck makers.
   Sales of light trucks made overseas slipped 27.4 percent last
month compared with the same month last year.
   ``Clearly there are some sales that are showing up as truck
sales that used to be car sales,'' Laughlin said. ``Minivans are in
particular a replacement for station wagons.
   ``At the same time, there seems to be a growing consumer trend
to sport utility vehicles in much the same way there was toward
muscle cars in the '60s and '70s,'' he added.
   Foreign and domestic automakers said they sold 792,295 cars last
month, a 8.1 percent decrease from the 862,391 cars sold during
September of last year.
   General Motors Corp. showed the largest car sales decline in
late September, dropping 15 percent to 116,028 cars this year
compared with 136,483 during the same period last year. Ford Motor
Co.'s late September sales fell to 70,813 cars, down 14.3 percent
from 82,606 during the period last year.
   Chrysler Corp. showed the smallest late-September decline,
falling 4.5 percent to 33,314 cars this year compared with 34,898
last year.
   For the calendar year, Chrysler has reported an 11.6 percent
sales increase compared to the first nine months of last year.
During that same time, Ford's sales have risen 7.2 percent and GM's
have fallen 0.7 percent.
   But Sudol said the Chrysler figures may be a little deceiving.
   ``In 1987, they had a lot of down time for plant retooling so
that makes it a little easier'' to show increased sales in 1988
compared to the year before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
