<DOCNO> AP881004-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zaire-AIDS     10-04 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zaire-AIDS,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Authorities Seeking to Check Spread of AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINSHASA, Zaire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Central African country is using
everything from comic books to theater to make its population more
aware of AIDS, and the program seems to be working, officials said.
   Although the deadly, incurable disease is most common among male
homosexuals in the West, the incidence is high among heterosexuals
in Africa. Doctors disagree about the reasons.
   Dr. N'galy Bosenge, director of Zaire's national AIDS committee,
said Zaire is preparing its first major random survey of the AIDS
infection rate.
   In an interview Monday, N'galy said a pilot study may begin in
late October to determine whether enough blood samples can be
obtained to permit a representative survey.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome, or AIDS, is caused by a
virus that attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims
defenseless against infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their unborn offspring.
   Zaire began a national AIDS education program last year, using
comic books, popular music, theater and television.
   Until then, officials had been reluctant to talk with Western
journalists about the disease or publicize the danger among their
own people.
   Dennis Chandler of the U.S. Agency for International development
praised Zaire's education program and said: ``A survey found
knowledge of AIDS in the Kinshasa region was as high as that found
in the United States.''
   ``Condom sales have increased from virtually nil to 100,000
monthly,'' according to a survey in Kinshasa and a few other
regions, Chandler said.
   N'galy said Zaire had cooperated with scientists researching the
AIDS problem, but claims that the disease originated in Zaire and
descriptions of this country as the ``AIDS epicenter'' made
officials wary of publicity.
   ``When we first reported that from 6-8 percent of the people
surveyed in Kinshasa were sero-positive it was regarded as a
national catastrophe,'' he said.
   Authorities also hesitated because they lacked verifiable data.
N'galy said that explained why Zaire had reported only 300 cases to
the World Health Organization while health authorities were
convinced the total was many times that.
   The new random survey of 10,000 Kinshasa residents will seek to
determine the true AIDS rate, he said.
   Previous surveys have found rates ranging from 6-8 percent among
the staff of a Kinshasa hospital to 3-4 percent at a large factory
and a bank. N'galy said he could not explain the difference and the
rates could not be considered representative of the general
population, which he said probably was somewhere between.
   According to N'galy, a principal aim of the new study is ``to
evaluate the success of our aids education program. The most
important thing is to check the rate of AIDS infection. We are
confident that people understand the need for change, but it is a
long-term effort.''
   Current studies of pregnant women and blood donors suggest the
incidence is not rising among the general population because
comparisons with surveys taken several years ago found differences
statistically insignificant, N'galy said.
   He said a survey in one remote village indicated the AIDS
infection level remained under 1 percent and did not change in 10
years.
   Tests of prostitutes in Kinshasa, however, indicated an increase
in the infection rate from 27 percent to 40, N'galy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
