<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviets-Arms     10-04 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Arms,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Drop Requirement for Conventional Arms Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said Tuesday it has
dropped a demand that blocked agreement on a new forum for
negotiating reduced conventional military forces in Europe.
   Yuri B. Kashlev, chief Soviet delegate to the Helsinki review
conference, said in an interview that the Kremlin has agreed that
tactical nuclear weapons need not be among weapons included in new
talks between NATO and the Warsaw Pact.
   Kashlev said the Soviets also have agreed not to make a
distinction between attack aircraft and air defense forces in the
written mandate for the new negotiations.
   ``We will make the difference in the talks, but we decided to
meet NATO halfway,'' Kashlev declared. He said agreement came in
conversations last week at the United Nations in New York between
Eduard A. Shevardnadze, the Soviet foreign minister, and
counterparts from NATO countries.
   American officials said Moscow had not formally presented its
position in protracted bargaining for new talks among 23 nations
designed to replace the Mutual and Balanced Force Reduction
negotiations, which have dragged on in Vienna without agreement for
nearly 15 years.
   Negotiations on the new forum are being conducted at the Vienna
conference, one of several held to review compliance with the 1975
Helsinki agreements on European security and cooperation signed by
the United States, Canada and all European nations except Albania.
   Such a forum cannot begin work until a mandate is agreed upon by
the Eastern and North Atlantic alliances, and until the 35 Helsinki
signatories produce a final document at the Vienna review session,
which began in November 1986.
   Also remaining to be settled is a formula for liaison with the
12 neutral or non-aligned nations that signed the Helsinki accords
but are not included in the arms negotiations.
   Kashlev predicted Tuesday: ``The mandate can be completed in the
next two to three weeks.''
   In order to produce a final document for the Vienna conference,
East and West must find mutually acceptable language on human
rights and economic copoperation, and agree on how many more review
meetings to hold.
   Western diplomats say a major problem is Soviet insistence on
holding a follow-up conference on human rights in Moscow.
   In Kashlev's view, refusing to do so would constitute ``a
boycott of Soviet democratization'' being carried out by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   The United States and Britain argue that the Soviet Union still
does not meet criteria for the host of a human rights conference.
   ``It is difficult to think of a human rights conference in
Moscow while there are political prisoners in the Soviet Union,''
U.S. Ambassador Warren Zimmermann said an interview.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
