<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Losev     10-04 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Losev,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass Director Dead at Age 61</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sergei A. Losev, general director of the Soviet
Union's official news agency Tass, died suddenly at age 61, the
news agency announced Tuesday.
   Losev died Monday, Tass said without giving a cause of death.
   ``Soviet journalism has suffered a grievous loss,'' said an
obituary note signed by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Losev had been in charge of the news agency since 1979.
   The Tass announcement praised Losev as a ``man of great
spiritual generosity'' who ``devoted all of his energy and
experience to the work given him by the party and government.
   ``His sense of purpose, industry and humaneness won him deep
respect from all who knew him,'' Tass said.
   Losev joined Tass in 1950 after graduating from the Moscow
Institute of International Relations, and worked as a correspondent
and bureau chief in the United States and Israel.
   In 1973 he became assistant director of Tass.
   Losev was a member of the Communist Party's Central Auditing
Commission, a delegate to the last two Communist Party congresses
and the June party conference. He had been a member of the Supreme
Soviet as well.
