<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Stuart-Hine     10-04 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Stuart-Hine,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Friend Of Veep Bush Dies In English Nursing Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEVENOAKS, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lola Stuart-Hine, the woman who taught
U.S. Vice President George Bush to play tennis when he was growing
up, has died at age 91 in an English nursing home, staff at the
facility reported Tuesday.
   Mrs. Stuart-Hine died peacefully Monday night, said Julie
Holland, a supervisor at the Heritage nursing home at Sevenoaks, 22
miles southeast of London. Ms. Holland did not know the cause of
death.
   Ross de Havilland, Mrs. Stuart-Hine's nephew, confirmed the
death of his aunt Tuesday but refused to comment further.
   The elderly woman, a close friend of the Bush family, had lived
in New York City for many years before coming to the 30-patient
Heritage home two years ago, Ms. Holland said.
   After sending a telegram to Bush last month wishing him good
luck as the Republican Party presidential candidate, Mrs.
Stuart-Hine received a personal letter from him that was ``the last
real joy of her life,'' said her friend Gordon Macmillan.
   Mrs. Stuart-Hine was the last surviving child of the Victorian
British composer Leslie Stuart, whose anthem ``Soldiers of the
Queen'' sent British soldiers marching off to the 1899-1902 Boer
War in South Africa.
   Stuart's musical ``Flora Dora,'' which became a hit on Broadway
in the late 1890s, was based on his daughter Lola, 2 years old at
the time.
   She grew up to become a model for the Molyneux fashion house in
Paris during the 1920s and married American banker Francis
Worthington Hine.
   The couple settled near the Bush family estate at Kennebunkport,
Maine, where Mrs. Stuart-Hine taught the young George Bush how to
handle a tennis racket. He referred to her as ``Aunt Lola,''
although they were not related.
   The couple had no children. On her husband's side, Mrs.
Stuart-Hine was related to Hollywood stars Olivia de Havilland and
her sister, Joan Fontaine.
</TEXT>
