<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TextileBill 2ndLd-Writethru a0748 10-04 0923</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Textile Bill, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0748,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Sustains Reagan's Textile Import Veto</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf pvs bgng, `Textile and,' to
UPDATE with Reagan statement that he's pleased his veto was
sustained</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday narrowly sustained
President Reagan's veto of tightened textile and apparel import
curbs, bowing to claims that the legislation would mean price
increases amounting to a fresh tax on consumers.
   ``Stand up for consumers, stand up for America, support your
president's veto,'' declared Rep. William Frenzel, R-Minn., minutes
before the House voted 272-152 in favor of overriding the veto.
   The total in favor was 11 votes short of the support from
two-thirds of the lawmakers present and voting that textile
industry supporters had needed.
   Textile and apparel workers bused in from various points along
the East Coast watched grim-faced from the galleries as the House,
with at most two weeks before congressional adjournment, appeared
to end the battle for textile import legislation for the rest of
the year.
   Reagan, however, was pleased by the House vote, according to a
statement released Tuesday evening by the White House.
   ``With the defeat of this protectionist legislation, we remain
committed to expanding the business, investment and consumer
opportunities for Americans,'' the statement said.
   ``By sustaining the veto, the House has once again reaffirmed
America's commitment to the free market and free international
trade,'' Reagan added.
   The bill, designed to protect American industry against foreign
competition, would freeze 1988 textile and apparel imports at last
year's level and limit growth to 1 percent annually beginning in
January.
   It also would clamp a similar cap on nonrubber footwear imports,
with no provision for future increases.
   Countries that increased purchases of American farm goods would
get larger shares of the U.S. textile and apparel market. The bill
also would establish a pilot program under which the government
would auction off import licenses and it would create a special
quota for imported silk neckties.
   Waving American flags and holding up multicolored umbrellas,
textile and apparel workers rallied under murky skies on the
windswept steps of the Capitol at noon, chanting, ``Save our jobs,
save our jobs.''
   Some watched the debate from the galleries later and Rep. Ken
Gray, D-Ill., the presiding officer, warned them to be quiet when
they applauded some pro-override oratory. After that they looked on
in silence.
   ``I cry out for our country,'' said Rep. Butler Derrick, D-S.C.,
chief sponsor of the bill. He said free trade was leading the
nation down the same economic path that eroded the financial power
of the British Empire.
   Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., one of the bill's fiercest critics,
contended, however, that it would prove costly to consumers.
   ``It imposes a tax on American consumers of about $20 billion a
year,'' he said.
   Rep. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, whose home-state shoe plants have
been hammered hard by imports, appealed to the House to ignore
``the ideological rot of an obsolete free-trade policy'' and enact
``this sensible trade bill.''
   A Democratic critic of the measure, Rep. Tom Downey of New York,
said that if the House were ``to do this by secret ballot there
would be no doubt about the outcome. To override the president's
veto makes no sense.''
   ``Open markets make everybody richer,'' he said.
   In vetoing the measure Sept. 28, Reagan said it represented
``protectionism at its worst,'' would raise prices, narrow consumer
choices and invite retaliation against American exports. Some of
the most prolific producers of textiles and apparel are among the
top customers of U.S. agriculture.
   Textile industry supporters say their goods are being squeezed
off store shelves by a flood of imported goods produced by Asian
textile mills and apparel plants. They point to a 17 percent
increase in imports in the 1980s and wide layoffs, including 29,000
lost last year.
   Textile industry earnings fell 12 percent in the first quarter
of this year, sponsors say.
   Critics, however, say the textile industry is flourishing,
largely because of a wave of automation over the last few years
that sharpened its competitive edge. They say that facelift, more
than overseas competition, is responsible for layoffs.
Manufacturers already are protected by 1,400 quotas covering 42
countries plus high tariffs.
   Reagan vetoed a similar measure in December 1985 and sponsors
were unable to muster the support they needed in the override
attempt in August 1986.
   The House approved the current bill, 263-156, a year ago and the
Senate approved it, 59-36, two weeks ago. The House voted, 248-150,
last week to accept Senate changes in the legislation and send it
to Reagan's desk.
   Joining the administration in its opposition to the measure were
an array of importers and retailers as well as industries wary of
trade protectionism lest it unleash retaliation against the goods
that they send overseas.
   Supporters included the textile, apparel and shoe industries and
the labor unions that represent their employees: the Amalgamated
Textile and Apparel Workers Union and the International Ladies
Garment Workers Union.
   Support for the measure cuts across partisan lines not only
within Congress but among rank-and-file supporters.
   Stella McGovern, an employee of a Philadelphia upholstery plant
for the last 12 years, arrived for the Capitol rally wearing
campaign buttons not only for the Dukakis-Bentsen Democratic
presidential ticket but for Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa.
   ``I like Heinz and I also like (Republican Sen. Arlen)
Specter,'' she said. ``because he (Heinz) is for the people and he
votes for the trade legislation ... It's the bills he votes for.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
