<HEAD>Hundreds of Police Raid Jerusalem's Arab Neighborhoods</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Elections Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of police swept through Arab
neighborhoods of the holy city Tuesday, arresting dozens of alleged
protest organizers and tax evaders, a police spokesman said.
   In the occupied territories, Arab hospital officials said
Israeli soldiers shot and wounded eight Palestinians. Protesters
blocked roads and stoned troops from nearby rooftops.
   Soldiers were posted at Al-Ittihad hospital in the West Bank
town of Nablus to guard a critically wounded Palestinian who was
shot after he attacked a soldier with a knife in the city's open
air market, the army said.
   Officials at Al-Ittihad said 100 soldiers were deployed in and
around the hospital, but an army spokeswoman said only a few were
standing guard.
   At least 280 Palestinians have been killed since a rebellion
began last Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million living in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967
Middle East war.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, army chief of staff, said Tuesday that
fewer Palestinians have been killed and more wounded since troops
began using plastic bullets in August. Egypt, the United States and
Britain have condemned Israel's use of the ammunition.
   Police raided Jerusalem's Abu Tor and Silwan districts after
anti-Israel disturbances, police spokesman Rafi Levy said. Officers
have used tear gas with greater frequency to disperse
stone-throwing crowds in several neighborhoods.
   Last week, police shot and killed 19-year-old Jamal Mattar
during a riot in the Jabal Mukabar district. He was the first
Palestinian killed in 10 months of the uprising.
   Officials at Al-Ittihad Hospital said Tuesday that Yihyeh
Mabruka, 21, was in critical condition with bullet and knife wounds
in the abdomen and chest.
   The military spokeswoman said Mabruka was wanted by the army but
did not say why. Soldiers on patrol in the Nablus market spotted
Mabruka and tried to arrest him but the Palestinian pulled a knife
and lunged at the patrol leader before being shot, she said.
</TEXT>
