<HEAD>Bentsen Prepares in Private; Democrats Prod Quayle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top seven grafs new with Statehouse rally, EDITS remainder to
tighten.
^With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen received a Texas send-off from cheering supporters in
front of the state capitol and headed Tuesday for his Omaha
showdown with Republican Dan Quayle.
   ``Tomorrow is a big day for us, and a big day for this
campaign,'' Bentsen told the crowd of about 1,500 people at the
Austin rally. ``And I can't think of a greater way to start it than
surrounded by friends here on the capitol steps of Texas,'' he said.
   ``I have 90 minutes to explain to America why Mike Dukakis and
Lloyd Bentsen should lead this country,'' he said, ``ninety minutes
to describe our vision of America, to tell the voters how Lloyd
Bentsen and Mike Dukakis plan to keep our economy and our military
number one.''
   Blasting the Republicans for trying ``time and time again'' to
cut Social Security, he also touched on Democratic themes of
education and health and on what he said was ``proven and tested
leadership.''
   ``George Bush and Dan Quayle hear no questions and offer no
answers,'' he said. ``They tell us to lower our sites, to live on
our past, rest on our laurels.''
   The Texas senator left the scene beneath a cloud of red and
white balloons and with the speakers shouting the theme from the
old television show ``Rawhide.''
   Before heading for Nebraska, Bentsen spent most of Tuesday in an
Austin hotel drilling for Wednesday night's vice presidential
debate with informal run-throughs and private study aimed at
getting ready for a prime-time audience.
   Susan Estrich, Michael Dukakis' campaign manager who was helping
Bentsen in his final preparations, said of the preparattions:
``We're not teaching him new positions on issues. ... I think
that's what the Quayle people have to do.
   ``You certainly don't have to teach him scripts on the issues,
which I assume they are doing on the other side.''
   Rep. Dennis Eckart, D-Ohio, played Quayle in mock debates on
Monday. He injected some humor into the session by leaving the
room, returning in a Ronald Reagan mask and wishing Bentsen luck
from a 3-by-5 card, said campaign spokeswoman Ellen Moskowitz.
   Eckart had to return to Washington on Monday night for a vote in
the House, and Mike McCurry, Bentsen's campaign press secretary,
was playing Quayle on Tuesday.
   McCurry said Bentsen was looking for ``the best way of making a
point memorable or punchy,'' but was having trouble with the time
limits.
   ``The red light goes off frequently,'' he said.
   ``It's all a matter of getting ready to present it in two-minute
answers and one-minute rebuttals,'' Estrich said. ``Our counsel to
him has been to be himself.''
   Some of Dukakis' top advisers were helping Bentsen prepare,
including Estrich and media adviser Tom Donilon. Campaign chairman
Paul Brountas planned to meet Bentsen in Omaha, Moskowitz said.
   The Texas senator also will have a crowd of Capitol Hill
colleagues supporting him in Omaha.
   The Democratic campaign has chartered a jet from Washington to
fly in about 40 members of Congress, including many of his Senate
friends. Some of them will also work afterward to get out the
Democratic viewpoint, or ``spin,'' on the results of the 90-minute
debate, Moskowitz said.
</TEXT>
