<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YonkersDeseg 1stLd-Writethru a0664 10-04 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0664,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Decides Next Move for Yonkers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with hearing, judge designating land
for low-income housing.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge bypassed a defiant Yonkers City
Council Tuesday and designated a site for low-income housing to
replace one the Roman Catholic Church did not want to give up.
   Should the council fail to come up with an alternative by Oct.
12, and should the new location pass muster by the U.S. Department
of Housing and Urban Development, the judge ordered the city to
acquire it ``under penalty of contempt.''
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand previously used a contempt
order to force the Council to endorse a plan to build 800 units of
affordable housing throughout the state's fourth-largest city. He
imposed fines that doubled daily until reaching $1 million,
confronting the city with layoffs and cutbacks.
   Despite the endorsement vote, a council majority still opposes
the 800 units as well as 200 units of low-income housing in a
predominantly white area. Sand intended the construction as a
remedy to his 1985 finding that the city intentionally segregated
housing and schools for 40 years.
   ``Isn't it a fact that the Council assumes no responsibility,
but to take a purely negative position to be against whatever it is
the parties or court proposes?'' Sand repeatedly asked city
attorney Michael Sculnick at a hearing Tuesday.
   Sculnick replied that there was neither a sufficient majority on
the Council to designate a site nor was there a desire to
participate in choosing an alternative site for 22 units of
low-income housing to replace property located on St. Joseph's
Seminary.
   ``It is hypocritical for the city to proclaim its desire not to
use the seminary site against the wishes of the archdiocese while
refusing to take any positive action that would obviate the
problem,'' Sand said.
   Sand gave the city a week to choose alternative sites and
ordered HUD to do a preliminary review of any property the Council
proposes to determine its suitability.
   A very preliminary review of the site designated by Sand
indicated it was feasible, said John Herald, HUD's attorney.
   Sand did not immediately threaten the City Council with contempt
for failing to choose an alternative site. But he openly expressed
anger as he has not done through eight years of the case.
   ``What perhaps is the most distressing and offensive aspect of
the position taken by the city is its willingness to use the
seminary site and the church-state issue as a ploy to defeat or
indefinitely delay the fulfillment of the city's obligation'' to
build affordable housing, Sand said.
   The church challenged condemnation of its property, and a
federal appeals panel told Sand to hold a hearing to determine
whether there were other sites. The Council argued that until the
church-state issue was resolved, it would do nothing to cooperate
with the desegregation order. It said if another site were chosen
to replace the seminary site, that would invalidate the whole plan
it had agreed to.
   The site designated by Sand had been proposed by Yonkers Mayor
Nicholas Wasicsko at a City Council meeting last week, but the
council refused to vote on it. After court, Wasicsko said there was
a chance the Council would choose another site, but he wasn't
optimistic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
