<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Police     10-04 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Police,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawrence Police Become Third in Massachusetts to Endorse Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers in Lawrence voted Tuesday
afternoon to endorse Vice President George Bush's Republican
campaign for the presidency.
   The vote, taken at the Lawrence police station among members of
the police union, was 73 for Bush, 5 for Democratic presidential
nominee Michael S. Dukakis and 6 with no preference, said Officer
Charles Carroll, the union steward.
   Carroll said the police sentiment against Gov. Dukakis involves
his stance on crime, his opposition to the death penalty and
criticism of the state furlough program for convicts.
   Last month, police officers in Boston and in Springfield
endorsed Bush for president.
   Lawrence is the city where Willie Horton killed Joey Fournier,
17, and was convicted of first-degree murder.
   While serving his sentence, Horton escaped while on a furlough
from state prison. Later, he was arrested and convicted in Maryland
on charges of raping a woman and terrorizing her and her finance.
   Public outcry over the Horton case prompted Massachusetts
lawmakers to ban furloughs for inmates convicted of first-degree
murder.
</TEXT>
