<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     10-04 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Begin `Street Freeze' Policy in Cape Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police sealed off sections of
Cape Town Tuesday, blocking streets with armored vehicles while
detectives searched pedestrians and vehicles in a ``street-freeze''
operation.
   A policeman using a loudspeaker told pedestrians the action was
routine and that officers were searching for suspicious parcels.
   Authorities began street-freeze operations following an increase
in the number of bombings in white-ruled South Africa.
   In other developments Tuesday:
   _A policeman fatally shot a black worker who allegedly attacked
another man with a screwdriver outside the luxury Sun Hotel in
Johannesburg. Police identified the slain man as John Mhkize and
said he was a member of the Hotel and Restaurant Workers Union that
has been on strike at the hotel.
   _At the United Nations in New York, Secretary of State George P.
Shultz criticized congressionally imposed sanctions against South
Africa, saying the main victims have been black businesses and
workers. He spoke to representatives of the Organization of African
Unity attending the General Assembly session.
   Four bombings in South Africa over the past four days prompted
police to respond with the street-freeze plan. Last month bombings
averaged about one a day.
   The government has blamed most of the bombings on the outlawed
African National Congress, saying the black guerrilla organization
is trying to disrupt the October 26 municipal elections.
   Government opponents have noted some of the bombing targets were
organizations or individuals opposed to the policy of apartheid and
bombs have exploded in areas frequented only by blacks. They said
that indicated white vigilantes or secret units of the security
forces might be responsible.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   Police gave few details about Mhkize's death. They said he was
shot after he attacked a man near the entrance of the hotel and
then went into the lobby.
   About 3,000 employees of the Southern Sun hotel chain are
striking to protest the dismissal of some workers who did not show
up for work on June 16, the anniversary of the 1976 riots in the
black township of Soweto. Many blacks observe June 16 as a memorial
holiday.
   The Southern Sun management began a lock-out of striking workers
on Monday and said they would be dismissed on Friday if they did
not return to work.
   Shultz, in his address to the OAU delegates, repeated his stand
that mandatory sanctions deprive the United States of the leverage
it needs to press for an end to South Africa's apartheid system.
   He said American businessmen forced to sell their holdings in
South Africa have done so, at bargain prices, to the ``South
African industrial and financial elite,'' and that is the ``wrong
signal'' for the United States to be sending.
   ``We believe that a more fruitful approach is to help the
victims of apartheid build their bargaining power through
assistance for education, economic opportunities and community
development for South Africans,'' Shultz said.
   The secretary said the political outlook for South Africa is not
encouraging.
   ``We remain deeply concerned that unless the accelerating cycle
of violence _ practiced by both the government and its opponents _
is stopped, South Africa will continue its descent into a siege
mentality and garrison state in which all South Africans become
losers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
