<HEAD>Jackson Urges Voter Turnout For Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson urged Cleveland's
heavily Democratic black community Tuesday night to recognize
differences between Vice President George Bush and Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis and support the Democratic presidential ticket.
   Jackson's appearance at the Ebenezer Baptist Church in Cleveland
came the same day Dukakis stopped in Toledo to tour a Jeep plant.
   ``We tend to look at these two candidates and we can't see much
of a difference,'' Jackson told about 300 people at a voter
registration rally in the church. ``I've seen them both up close
and, take my word for it, there is a difference. When Dukakis
stands for a health plan for the common people, he has earned your
vote.''
   He said Bush ``stands against civil liberties, civil rights,
workers' rights and women's rights. He is a threat to our future.''
   After his remarks, he left the church and told reporters that he
is patched up any difference he had with the Dukakis campaign. The
former Democratic presidential candidate, who was Dukakis' chief
rival in the spring primaries, said his job now is ``to be
inspirational and to register new voters.''
