<2ND_LINE>AM-Pennsylvania Polls,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls Call Different Winners But Presidential Race Too Close To
Call</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and Michael Dukakis split the
lead in a pair of Pennsylvania polls, but the margins of error
closed the gap in both surveys.
   A survey of likely voters for the Philadelphia Daily News and
the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette showed Bush leading Dukakis 48 percent
to 42 percent. The sampling error among those 595 people questioned
last Friday and Saturday was plus or minus 4 points, however.
   A survey of likely voters for Philadelphia television station
WCAU-TV gave Dukakis the lead _ 46 percent to 45 percent _ with 9
percent undecided.
   But the sampling error of plus or minus 3.5 percentage points
meant neither candidate had a clear lead in the battle for
Pennsylvania's 25 electoral votes.
   The WCAU poll surveyed 837 registered voters statewide by
telephone from last Thursday through Saturday.
</TEXT>
