<DOCNO> AP881004-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Iraq     10-04 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iraq,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Insists Shatt-al-Arab, Persian Gulf Must Be Navigable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iraqi foreign minister said Tuesday
that the latest Iran-Iraq peace talks have gone well but insisted
the Shatt-al-Arab waterway and Persian Gulf must be navigable if
negotiations are to progress.
   The talks that ran Aug. 25 to Sept. 13 in Geneva and shifted to
New York last weekend.
   Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz of Iraq told the 43rd General
Assembly that Iran ``accepted the (Security Council's peace)
resolution only because of a crushing military defeat and in the
context of a struggle for power inside Iran.''
   He said this made Baghdad suspicious of Iran's motives as to
whether Iran sincerely wanted a lasting peace treaty with Iraq.
   ``This suspicious position ... was followed by ... (the Iranian
delegation's) insistence on provisions which impose a de facto arms
embargo on Iraq at sea,'' said Aziz, referring to Iran's searches
of neutral ships in the gulf for war cargo bound for Iraq.
   Iraq insists the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which forms part of the
two countries' southern border, must be cleared of sunken ships and
silt accumulated during the eight-year war.
   ``Shatt-al-Arab is Iraq's only outlet to the high seas,'' said
Aziz.
   He denied this was a precondition, saying the demand was spelled
out to the Security Council throughout proceedings that led to
peace talks opening in Geneva on Aug. 25. A U.N.-monitored
cease-fire went into effect on Aug. 20.
   Baghdad says Iran's policy of searching ships violates the
cease-fire, which calls for a halt to all military actions on air,
sea and land.
   Iran insists it has the right as a nation at war to search the
ships and says peace talks should be limited to the issues in
Resolution 598, with no extraneous concerns such as Shatt-al-Arab.
   Aziz met with Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar before
addressing the General Assembly. He said both hope that a date will
be decided soon on resuming peace talks in Geneva.
   Asked if Perez de Cuellar introduced new proposals, he answered:
``We are discussing all possible ideas ... on how to make further
progress, and the discussions went well with his excellency.''
   Last Saturday, Aziz met with Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati for direct peace talks, but the session soon shifted to
indirect talks, with the secretary-general and his special
mediator, Swedish U.N. Ambassador Jan K. Eliasson.
   On Friday and Monday, Aziz and Velayati met separately with the
secretary-general, and their aides met Monday.
   From the statements made by both delegations during the weekend
and from Aziz's speech Tuesday, no indication emerged of progress
on the major issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
