<DOCNO> AP881004-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Brazil-Constitution     10-04 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Constitution,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazil to Enact New Constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Sarney told the nation
Tuesday night that the enactment of a new constitution will
complete Brazil's transition to democracy.
   The constitution is to be adopted Wednesday, replacing
authoritarian laws handed down 20 years ago by the military chiefs
who ruled Brazil from 1964 to 1985.
   In a nationwide television address, Sarney said: ``This is a
historic date for our country. The enactment of the new
constitution brings us to the end of a long path .... My mission of
helping the country through its transition to democracy is
fulfilled.''
   But Brazilians don't know how their life will be affected by the
new charter, a 245-article document that touches on issues ranging
from interest rates to mining rights and land reform.
   Sarney had fought some measures included in the charter, but he
said Tuesday he would be ``the constitution's greatest servant.''
   The president of the Constituent Assembly, Rep. Ulysses
Guimaraes, said the constitution ``will consolidate a
representative and participatory democracy.'' The 559-member,
two-chamber Congress that was elected in 1986 worked for 19 months
as a Constituent Assembly to produce the charter.
   It decentralizes the government's power, abolishes the
president's power to impose laws by decree, ends censorship, makes
torture a crime and broadens workers' rights to unionize and strike.
   It also regulates education, divorce, the rights of native
Indians and the activities of oil and mining companies.
   Foreign-owned mining companies will have four years to hand over
majority control to permanent residents of Brazil while domestic
companies will receive unspecified ``privileges'' from the
government. Those measures were seen as a victory for leftists.
   But right-wing members of Congress scored with land-reform
provisions that make ``productive land'' not subject to
expropriation.
   One of the most controversial articles limits ``real'' interest
rates to 12 percent a year. But it doesn't specify what ``real''
interest rates are and it has been suggested another law will be
needed to make the limit effective.
   Some legislators say the real interest is above the inflation
rate, which the government has said will register 800 percent this
year. Many banks and credit associations now charge more than 1,000
percent interest.
   Guimaraes, considered the architect of the constitution, said
Monday the charter would be respected by all, including the armed
forces.
   ``The military period left deep marks,'' he said. ``There is an
awareness that the regime is good, and from the armed forces we
have heard only words of support and confidence in the stability of
democracy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
