<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NegligenceSuit     10-04 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Negligence Suit,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Awarded $7.2 Million in Negligence Suit Against Health Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old girl was awarded more than $7
million by a jury that concluded she suffered brain damage,
cerebral palsy and blindness because of city hospital negligence
around the time of her birth.
   ``What made this case so tragic was the fact that the hospital
had several opportunities to save the child from her dreadful fate,
but it failed so obviously and miserably,'' Thomas A. Moore, the
lawyer for the child's family, said.
   Moore said Bellevue Hospital and its physicians made mistakes
and misdiagnoses in caring for the girl's mother, Ora Stewart.
   Two days before her child was born, Ms. Stewart visited the
hospital's emergency room complaining of a vaginal discharge, but
was sent home, the lawyer said. The next morning she returned to
Bellevue with labor pains five minutes apart, but again was sent
home, he said.
   Ms. Stewart gave birth to the child, Shavon Skinner, the
following day in her apartment. Because of complications, the
newborn had trouble breathing and, after she was rushed to
Bellevue, went untreated for more than 24 hours even though she was
having seizures, the lawyer maintained.
   Fred Winters, a spokesman for the city Health and Hospitals
Corp., said the agency had not yet closely examined the jury's
finding, but there appeared to be grounds for an appeal and ``the
award may be excessive.''
   After deliberating for three days, the Manhattan state Supreme
Court jury awarded $4.945 million for medical expenses and other
care for Shavon Skinner; $750,000 for her pain and suffering; and
$1.5 million for Shavon's loss of enjoyment of life, for a total
award of $7.195 million, Moore said.
   During her pregnancy, Ms. Stewart was an employee of the city
Department of Social Services, which entitled her to free medical
care and hospitalization in a city hospital, Moore said.
   Ms. Stewart received regular prenatal care at a city clinic. She
was 29 years old when Shavon was born and was considered a
``high-risk patient'' because of hypertension and an overweight
problem, Moore said.
   Since the girl's birth, Ms. Stewart has been on an extended
leave of absence to take care of Shavon, the lawyer said.
   The negligence suit was filed against the city in 1980, several
months after Shavon's birth, Moore said.
</TEXT>
