<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChezHelene     10-04 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chez Helene,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-TV-Frank's Place</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Real Frank's Place Expects a Long Run</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Frank's Place,'' has been canceled, but the
restaurant that inspired it is still cooking.
   ``That's sad,'' Chef Austin Leslie, owner of Chez Helene, said
Tuesday after learning that the critically acclaimed CBS comedy had
been canceled. ``It won't hurt us though, I'm still a star around
here.''
   Leslie said the on again-off again series provided him with more
fun than customers or fame. ``It did well for me and we had some
good times over it, but I was on a roll before it and I'm still on
a roll,'' he said.
   Chez Helene's Creole, soul, French, and Cajun food has appealed
to black and white New Orleanians for a long time, but Leslie said
he did see an increase in tourists because of the television show.
   ``I think it showed some people from around the United States
that they could come into the black community and enjoy
themselves,'' he said. ``It also gave the taxi drivers another
place to tell people about. They would tell tourists to try the
real Frank's Place,'' he said.
   Leslie said he never tried to copy the show that had copied him.
   ``Some people said, `why don't you change the name of the
restaurant?' But I didn't. I did use the Frank's Place theme during
the (Republican National) convention, but we're still the same as
we ever were,'' he said.
   Frank's Place brought more than excitement to Chez Helene,
however. Leslie said star Tim Reid visited the restaurant several
times after his original scouting trip when it was selected as a
model for the fictional restaurant.
   ``He came in a couple of more times including the time they shot
Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous here. And, Hugh Wilson, the
producer brought all the writers in after carnival. He presented me
with a jacket,'' he said.
   Leslie said news of the cancellation by CBS surprised him since
everyone he talked to said they liked the show. ``They said they
liked to watch it but could never find it because the network moved
it around so much,'' he said.
   Chez Helene, which has been in operation since 1942, will
continue to dish out everything from fried chicken to gumbo, he
said.
   ``I'm just glad I kept my head through it all. Glad I kept my
perspective. It didn't put me on the map, I was already on the map.
It made us a little bit more famous, but I always thought we'd have
a long run right here in New Orleans,'' he said.
</TEXT>
