<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SubmarinerConviction     10-04 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Submariner Conviction,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Submariner Gets Four-Plus Years Confinement For Mishandling
Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy submariner convicted by court-martial of
mishandling secret photographs and documents was sentenced Tuesday
to four years confinement and kicked out of the Navy, officials
said.
   Chief Petty Officer David Fleming, an 18-year Navy veteran, also
was reduced to the lowest possible rank before being given a bad
conduct discharge, said Lt. Sonja Headley, a spokeswoman at the
Navy's submarine base on Point Loma.
   Fleming, 35, had faced up to 16 years in prison after being
found guilty Monday by a six-member court-martial board of
mishandling 16 secret photographs and documents by keeping them at
his home. He was photography chief aboard the submarine La Jolla at
the time of the offenses.
   After a four-day trial in a high-security Point Loma courtroom,
he also was found guilty of stealing six training documents,
soliciting his wife to destroy evidence and dereliction of duty.
   Fleming contended that cramped quarters aboard the San
Diego-based La Jolla led him to develop photographs at home. He
argued that his behavior was no different from other submariners
with similar responsibilities.
   ``I am being prosecuted under the letter of the law for obeying
the spirit of the law,'' Fleming said after the guilty verdicts
Monday.
   Fleming was convicted under espionage statutes that allege he
knew keeping the photos could damage national security. No evidence
of such damage was offered in court, sources told The San Diego
Union.
   Fleming and several other chief petty officers who testified for
the defense said security procedures on the La Jolla were sloppy,
especially when the submarine was deployed.
   Fleming originally was charged with mishandling 28 photographs.
He earlier pleaded guilty to four counts of mishandling classified
documents and the theft of the same four documents, which were
training manuals.
   Six counts of mishandling secrets were dropped at the beginning
of the trial. Fleming was found innocent on two counts of
mishandling classified documents and innocent on one count of
stealing a secret document.
</TEXT>
