<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrushFire     10-04 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brush Fire,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Setting Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been charged with
setting a 12,000-acre wildfire that continues to burn in the San
Bernardino Mountains and is under investigation in 23 other arson
blazes, officials announced Tuesday.
   James Lonczak, 41, of Covina was charged Monday in Los Angeles
federal court with setting the Sept. 28 fire in the San Bernardino
Mountains that has consumed 12,000 acres and cost $2 million to
fight, prosecutors said.
   An affidavit filed with the criminal complaint states Lonczak is
also under investigation for allegedly setting 23 other arson
wildfires, said Mary McMenimen, spokeswoman for the U.S. Attorney's
Office.
   Lonczak pleaded innocent to the charge at arraignment Monday and
is being held without bail pending an Oct. 18 hearing, she said.
   Mary Bethke, a spokeswoman with the U.S. Forest Service, said
Sunday's arrest of Lonczak was the result of a three-month
investigation by the agency and the California Department of
Forestry
   The fire has been contained, but fire officials said they don't
expect to extinguish the blaze until Thursday, said U.S. Forest
Service spokeswoman Lindsay Maierhofer.
   Flames from the fire were fanned last week by gusty Santa Ana
winds of up to 60 mph. The fire closed nearby Interstate 15 for a
time and forced hundreds of people to evacuate homes.
   One ranch home and a shed were destroyed. Property losses
totaled about $250,000, officials said.
   Cost of battling the fire was estimated at nearly $2 million,
Ms. Maierhofer said.
</TEXT>
