<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Brazil-Hijacker     10-04 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Hijacker,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijacker of Brazilian Boeing Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 28-year-old man who hijacked a
Brazilian jet with 100 people aboard last week and later was
wounded by police gunfire died Tuesday after a five-hour police
interrogation, hospital officials said.
   Raimundo Conceicao, whom officials described as a ``psychopath''
shortly after the piracy, died of kidney failure, according to a
medical report released by Santa Genoveva Hospital in Goiania, 850
miles northwest of Rio.
   On Sept. 29, Conceicao burst into the cockpit of a Brazilian
airliner on a flight from the Western Amazon regions to Rio and
demanded that the plane fly to the federal capital of Brasilia. He
reportedly told negotiators he wanted to crash the plane into a
government building to ``settle accounts'' with the government
because of what he called its recessive economic policies.
   The plane was forced to land 125 miles southwest of Brasilia in
Goiania, where Conceicao shot and killed the co-pilot and wounded
two other people before being shot by police as he prepared to
change planes.
   He underwent surgery the same day to stop internal bleeding
caused by the bullet wounds.
   On Sunday, police questioned Conceicao intensely for five hours
about the hijacking. Late Monday afternoon, he was rushed to the
intensive care unit with soaring blood pressure.
   Conceicao's condition had been improving, and the medical report
said the cause of the sudden deterioration in his condition were
not known.
   A hospital doctor, who spoke on condition that he not be
identified, said, however, that the upward surge in blood pressure
could have been caused by a build-up of intestinal gases during the
lengthy interrogation.
   Doctors refused to let police talk to Conceicao on Monday,
saying his health had deteriorated. The contents of Conceicao's
police deposition were not made public.
   On Monday, government officials announced that passengers at
major Brazilian airports now will have their baggage checked before
boarding domestic flights. Previously, only those boarding
international flights were subject to police checks.
</TEXT>
