<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietJournals     10-04 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Journals,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politburo Orders Two New Publications to Inform Citizens, Party
Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Politburo, endorsing greater openness
in public affairs, ordered two new publications established to
provide more information about the Communist Party and government,
Tass reported Tuesday.
   The official news agency reported the Politburo also reviewed
plans for a Central Committee meeting devoted to agriculture, but
did not say when the conference would be held.
   It said the Politburo ordered plans drawn up for an overhaul of
management in the farm sector, traditionally one of the weakest
performers in the Soviet economy.
   Tass said one publication will cover the activities of the
Communist Party's policy-making Central Committee and the other
will be produced by the Council of Ministers, the Soviet Cabinet.
   It said the 12-member Politburo made the decision during a
meeting Monday. No reason was given for the delayed report.
   At a nationwide Communist Party conference in June and July some
delegates said they were told little about the actions of the
Central Committee and they did not even know the responsibilities
of individual party leaders.
   Tass reported the Politburo ordered the publication of a journal
to be called ``News of the CC of the CPSU'' _ Central Committee of
the Communist Party of the Soviet Union.
   ``It is planned that it will officially publish the decisions of
top party organs and draft resolutions on major issues of party and
public affairs,'' the agency said.
   A newspaper to be called ``Government News'' will be established
to inform the public on how the government's economic, social and
cultural decisions are being carried out and on the progress of
perestroika, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's drive for reforms,
according to Tass.
   ``It was stressed at the (Politburo) meeting that the
publication of the journal and the newspaper will be in line with
the party's policy of deepening the democratism of the political
system of our society and promote greater openness in state
affairs,'' Tass said.
   It did not say when the publications would first appear, how
often they would be published or the number of copies to be
printed. It was unclear how their content would differ from
existing Soviet publications, many of which are controlled by the
Central Committee or government.
   Tass said the journal will report periodically on the activities
of the Central Committee and print transcripts of important party
meetings and conferences, information about party elections,
biographies of leaders and historical material from party archives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
