<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Pillsbury 2ndLd-Writethru a0760 10-04 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0760,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury's Stock Skyrockets Following Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Pillsbury court moves to
block the takeover; picks up 5th graf: `Ian A. ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co.'s stock skyrocketed Tuesday
after Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC launched a surprise $5.17
billion tender offer, and the food conglomerate moved to block the
proposal in state courts.
   The bid, which caught the nation's fourth-largest food company
off guard, offers Pillsbury stockholders $60 cash for each of 86.2
million common shares outstanding.
   On Wall Street, Pillsbury stock soared $18 a share to $57 in
heavy trading composite New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Pillsbury said in a statement late in the day that its board
would review the offer ``at an appropriate time.'' A spokesman said
Pillsbury was not approached by the British liquor, food and
retailing giant before the takeover offer was announced.
   Pillsbury also said in a later statement it had sued to block
the acquisition in 13 states, contending a buyout by Grand Met
would violate state liquor laws prohibiting liquor manufacturers
from owning retail liquor outlets, namely some of Pillsbury's
restaurants.
   Courts in the states of Texas, Oklahoma, New Mexico, Michigan,
Kansas, Pennsylvania and Missouri already have issued temporary
restraining orders enjoining Grand Met from acquiring any Pillsbury
stock, and a Delaware court has rejected Grand Met's effort to stop
those actions, Pillsbury said.
   Ian A. Martin, Grand Metropolitan's chief executive for U.S.
operations, said he tried unsuccessfully to contact Pillsbury
Chairman Philip L. Smith after arriving in Minneapolis Tuesday
morning. He said he did not want the offer to be interpreted as a
hostile takeover.
   ``We are very interested in doing this thing in a gentlemanly
manner,'' he said. ``The sooner we get in a conversation with them,
the happier we'll be.''
   Although the bid came as a surprise, Pillsbury had been viewed
as a potential takeover target because of its lackluster
performance and turnover in its top management.
   In July, Smith, then chairman of rival General Foods Corp.,
replaced William H. Spoor as Pillsbury's chairman. Spoor came out
of retirement earlier this year to run the company on an interim
basis after the former chairman, John Stafford, resigned under
pressure.
   The company has been trying to rebound from the effect of a
restructuring that caused its profit to fall to $69.3 million in
fiscal 1988, on sales of $6.2 billion.
   Analysts called the Grand Metropolitan offer a fair price.
   ``It's going to be a bid that Pillsbury management is going to
have difficulty defending against,'' said John M. McMillen, an
analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York. ``I think
they'll fight it initially _ attempt to fight it _ but I think it's
a losing battle.''
   Stephen Carnes, an analyst with Piper Jaffray & Hopwood in
Minneapolis, said Grand Metropolitan indicated its offer was
negotiable, and he predicted the price would rise.
   ``We put a top price at $70 (a share), not higher than that,''
Carnes said.
   ``I think Pillsbury management is going to have a tough time
snubbing this offer off,'' he said. ``This is a premium price.''
   Grand Metropolitan said in a filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission that if the bid succeeded it planned to sell
off Pillsbury's Steak & Ale and Bennigan's restaurant operations.
Distron Distribution, Pillsbury's in-house distribution system for
its Burger King restaurants, also would be sold, the filing said.
   The struggling restaurant division provides about half of
Pillsbury's revenues.
   Pillsbury management has been under pressure to either boost
revenues at Burger King, the world's second-largest restaurant
chain, or sell it. But Grand Metropolitan executives are bullish on
Burger King's prospects.
   ``We believe Burger King's problems have been overrated,'' said
Martin.
   The London-based Grand Metropolitan, maker of Smirnoff vodka and
J&B Scotch, is intent on focusing on its foods, liquor and
retailing operations and expanding its operations in North America.
   On Friday it announced it was selling its Inter-Continental
hotel chain to a Japanese concern and earmarked the $2.27 billion
in cash it received for acquisitions.
   With annual sales of about $10 billion, Grand Metropolitan's
businesses also include hotels, Alpo petfood and Pearle vision
centers.
   Analysts speculated Grand Metropolitan was most interested in
Pillsbury for its Green Giant vegetable, Haagen-Dazs ice cream and
Van de Kamp's frozen fish operations.
   Martin agreed there were good prospects for marketing
Pillsbury's food products overseas, especially its microwavable
foods.
   Grand Metropolitan also is embroiled in a contested bid for
Irish Distillers Group PLC, Ireland's leading whisky maker, for
which Grand Metropolitan has offered around $465 million.
</TEXT>
