<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five top U.S. military chaplains are
presently all pastors of the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America.
   That the five have emerged as heads of the military chaplaincies
is a ``historic moment'' for the denomination, says its officer for
federal chaplaincies, Chaplain Loyd W. Lyngdal.
   The five are Rear Adm. Alvin B. Koeneman, Navy chief of
chaplains; Maj. Gen. Norris L. Einertson, chief of Army chaplains;
Maj. Gen. Stuart E. Barstad, chief of Air Force chaplains; Capt.
Walter A. Hiskett, Marine chief of chaplains, and Chaplain Herbert
B. Cleveland, director of chaplain services for the Veterans
Administration.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints says the Book of Momon, viewed as a companion to the Bible,
now is published in 80 languages.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GARDEN GROVE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An interdenominational organization
that works to uphold the nation's religious qualities, the
Religious Heritage of America, has named the Rev. Charles R.
Swindoll as ``Clergyman oot enough.
   Schools pass the extra costs on to parents and, because parents
have little money, to the parents' work units.
   ``Most work units go along because if they don't the school may
refuse to take their workers' children,'' said one Beijing worker
with a 7-year-old daughter.
   ``The State Education Commission opposes charging fees, but the
situation is quite complicated,'' a commission spokesman, Yuan
Yongtang, told The Associated Press. In many cases, he said, the
schools have no other choice if they want to stay open.
   Yuan said the commission does not keep track of what schools
charge. But a spate of reports in the official press in recent
weeks hints at the extent of the problem.
   The Liberation Road Primary School in the eastern city of
Lianyugang, for example, panicked parents when it demanded their
work units supply 1,000 to 3,000 yuan ($270 to $810) for each
student. China Youth News said some units refused and many students
were kept from class.
   ``This is overt extortion,'' it quoted one parent as saying.
   The People's Daily, the Communist Party newspaper, published a
picture of a dozen elementary school children in the central city
of Wuhan standing outside their school gate with signs around their
necks reading, ``We want to study.'' They had been banned from
class after their parents' work units refused to pay school fees,
the size of which was not given.
   An official at the Wuhan Foreign Affairs Office, who identified
himself as Comrade Yang, said other schools in Wuhan also barred
students because of inability to pay fees that he said generally
range from 30 yuan ($8) to 100 yuan ($27).
   Yang said the Wuhan city government ordered schools in September
to accept all school-age children. He added that he believed all
students were in class by month's end.
   The State Education Commission also declared in September that
``excessive fees'' would not be permitted, but set no specific
ceilings. There is no limit on the donations a school can accept,
so schools that have good relations with parents' work units agree
quietly on what is needed and call it a donation.
   Problems arise only when the work units balk.
   ``We have good relations with several work units,'' said Mrs.
Gao of Hujialou Primary School. ``They fix windows or doors or give
us a little money.'' One unit donated cooking equipment for the
cafeteria, she said. She refused to give the amount of annual
donations.
   Many schools also set up small factories on their grounds, with
teachers and staff as workers.
   ``No. 80 Middle School assembles calculators,'' Mrs. Gao said
with envy. ``Our teaching staff here is very small so we can't
spare anyone to do this sort of work.''
   But Hujialou does send a teacher to a nearby factory to keep its
books, with most of the teacher's factory salary going to the
school.
</TEXT>
