<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Sade ADV14-16   10-04 0821</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Sade, ADV 14-16,0851</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14-16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct 14-16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: The Smooth, Sexy Vocals of Sade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one looks or sounds quite like Sade, so it
should come as no surprise that her entry into show business came
under unusual circumstances.
   ``I was driving along with a friend in London and we both said,
`God, it's misty.' We went to visit somebody and `Misty' was
playing on the radio. Someone than asked me if I was going to see
`Misty in Roots' (a reggae band) tomorrow.
   ``I went and I met these boys that I was at school with. They
said they've got a group. Was I interested in singing? Do I know
any singers who could just rehearse? They pursuaded me that I
should join them.''
   The rest, as they say, is pop history: three platinum albums,
five Top 10 singles and total record sales of over 20 million. But
in the beginning...
   ``I remember my first concert,'' she recalled. ``Our stage was
built on empty beer crates. I had to stand still because my heels
got stuck in the cracks. It's not easy.''
   But how many singers make it seem as easy as Sade? Her relaxed
vocals, influenced by Marvin Gaye and Nina Simone among others,
helped make ``Smooth Operator'' a hit single in 1984, while
``Diamond Life,'' became the all-time best-selling debut album for
a female British singer.
   Sade, the singer, should be distinguished from ``Sade,'' her
group, composed of Stuart Matthewman on guitar and saxophone,
Andrew Hale on keyboards and Paul S. Denman on bass.
   ``Sade'' won a Grammy in 1985 for best new artist.
   ``I think anybody who is the least bit interested really knows
it's not just coming from me,'' the singer said. ``Rather than me
with a backing band of musicians, we're talking about a group of
people.''
   One problem at first was songwriting; no one in the group had
any experience.
   ``Stewart and Andrew are musically well-educated. Paul and I are
ignorant,'' Sade said. ``It isn't hard to find the ability. It does
take a lot out of you. You fight with the songs. You fight to get
how you want it to feel or sound. The ability isn't that special.''
   Sade was typically low-key about her success.
   ``The ultimate goal is to simply get pressed onto vinyl. There
are not that many people who approach it that way.''
   She also downplayed the impact of her unique appearance.
   ``Occasionally, I get marriage proposals _ from women as well,''
Sade said with a laugh. ``You don't get to people's hearts by the
way you look. I don't think success can be sustained on an image
alone. Once someone's got a photograph of you, that's the end of
it.''
   ``Diamond Life'' was just the beginning. The next album, 1985's
``Promise,'' was an even bigger seller and yielded the hit single,
``Sweetest Taboo.''
   Sade has been active politically as well, appearing at
anti-apartheid concerts and a benefit for Nelson Mandela, the
imprisoned leader of the African National Congress.
   ``I've got a conscience,'' Sade said. ``I've been brought up to
be concerned not only about what affects me immediately. It's more
a question of compassion or consciousness. The oppression of any
people is important to me.''
   The latest album, ``Stronger Than Pride,'' took about a year to
make. Although the songs, written in Spain and London, have the
same gentle rhythms as the previous records, Sade insists that
``Pride'' is the group's most upbeat record.
   ``I thought it was a lot harder than the other albums,'' she
said. ``It depends on the volume, the context in which you listen.
`Turn My Back' through big speakers in a club may sound hard and
loud.''
   All four members contributed to the songs on ``Stronger Than
Pride.'' The title track, a Top 10 single, was inspired by a
conversation Sade had with a friend.
   ``We were talking about pride. I said one thing is stronger than
pride, and that's love. The sentiment is something I always felt.''
   Sade was born Helen Folasude Adu in 1959, the daughter of a
Nigerian teacher and his British wife. Her parents separated when
she was 4, and Sade moved with her mother to London's North End.
   At St. Martin's College in London, she studied fashion and had
created her own line of menswear before pursuing a career in music,
joining a jazz-funk band, ``Pride,'' in 1982.
   She has come a long way since performing on beer crates and
recently played to sell-out crowds here at Radio City Music Hall.
   ``It's easier for me to sing in front of the audience,'' she
said. ``In the studio, we've only just written the songs. Once you
start rehearsing, you actually do better. You're stimulated by the
audience. Your singing's more heartfelt.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct 14-16</NOTE>
