<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Ryman ADV14-16   10-04 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Ryman, ADV 14-16,0761</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14-16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 14-16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: He Went to Moscow to Record Album</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Obscure country music performer Bobby
Joe Ryman says he was honored as a ``little country boy'' to be
picked to do an album as the lone American singer on the only
Soviet record label.
   The 47-year-old Ryman, who performs nightly at a Nashville
restaurant, recorded the album ``Country Boy in Moscow'' in the
Soviet Union in early September.
   He's been told the record could sell up to 5 million copies when
it is released in the Soviet Union early next year. That's
considerably more than he sells at the Melrose House restaurant
where he peddles his cassette tapes for $6 to audiences no larger
than 200 per meal.
   His pictures sell for $2. He has a ``tip hat'' at the front of
the stage for customers to show their special appreciation of his
music.
   ``For a little country boy like me, I felt honored,'' he said as
he reflected on his eight-day visit to the Soviet Union.
   Melodyia Records of Moscow chose him in January to become the
only United States singer on the Soviet record label. Melodyia
officials heard him perform at a music industry convention in
Cannes, France, where he was singing to try to stir up some
overseas bookings.
   Within a few days, the Soviets had decided to add the
silver-haired former building contractor to their roster. Eight
months later, he traveled to the Soviet Union under his first
recording contract with a record label.
   ``It feels wonderful, great,'' he said about his selection.
``It's a dream. I couldn't sleep. You just don't have the words to
explain it or why it happened.''
   He and a dozen American musicians, backup singers and record
producer Stan Cornelius flew to Moscow where they were joined by
Soviet singer Laima Vaikule who also performed on the album.
   Songs on the album include ``To All the Girls I've Loved
Before,'' ``Singin' the Blues,'' ``We Could'' and ``She's Not You.''
   ``To All the Girls I've Loved Before'' was a hit by Willie
Nelson and Julio Iglesias. ``Singin' the Blues'' was recorded by
the late country star Marty Robbins. ``We Could'' was a hit by
Little Jimmy Dickens and later Charley Pride, and ``She's Not You''
was one of Elvis Presley's records.
   It has not been determined yet if the album will be available in
this country.
   Ryman and Vaikule also did a music video to accompany the song
``We Could.''
   ``That was the highlight of the trip,'' Ryman said as he counted
proceeds at the restaurant. ``My heart pounded.''
   He also remembers with special fondness the remarks of the
Soviet video crew. ``The greatest thing said to me was when they
said I should be the ambassador of love and goodwill. That was an
honor.''
   He recorded mostly in English but learned a little Russian. The
new language was one of the difficulties of the joint project.
   ``It was hard for me,'' Ryman recalled. ``I can't speak English
too well, let alone Russian.''
   An interpreter was provided to aid communication.
   ``I found that if you get the younger Russians looking at you,
and you talk pretty good to them, they'll understand.''
   Ryman, a native of Nashville, personally financed his previous
album, ``The Seven Faces of Bobby Joe.'' Prior to that, he spent 28
years remodeling homes. One of his goals is to sing on Nashville's
Grand Ole Opry, the country music show that's been presented since
1925.
   The trip to Moscow left him with memories far surpassing any he
developed as a contractor. He visited Red Square and was the
subject of a documentary on Soviet television. He may return next
year to do a six-week concert tour with Vaikule.
   ``It was a beautiful experience,'' he said. ``The people were so
warm and loving. No one can come up with the words to describe the
Russian people. When they come up and put their arm around you and
say, `I love you,' it's amazing.
   ``They hated to see us leave. People were crying at the
airport.''
   Vaikule, described by Cornelius as a pop singer and dancer,
plans to come to Nashville later this year to record.
   ``She'll take the spotlight here like I did there,'' Ryman said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct 14-16</NOTE>
