<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-04 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0545</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have tested lows not seen in
two years amid indications that Saudi Arabia might boost their
output to try to pressure other OPEC oil producers to restrict
production.
   The November contract of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude skidded 31 cents a barrel Monday to settle at $13.06 a
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Crude prices had not
closed that low since August 1986.
   The price of crude has skidded $2 a barrel over the past five
weeks. But experts say consumers probably won't benefit
significantly unless crude holds at these depressed levels for an
extended period.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured
goods surged 3.1 percent in August, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Monday that orders rose $6.8
billion to a seasonally adjusted $226.6 billion, rebounding from a
3.6 percent decline in July, the worst in 18 months.
   The overall orders number has been influenced in recent months
by wide swings in orders for transportation equipment, particularly
aircraft.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economists blame rising interest rates and
overbuilding in some regions for a 0.6 percent decline in
construction spending in August.
   The Commerce Department said Monday that building activity
declined to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $396.1 billion in
August, following a revised 0.7 percent gain in July. The July
figure had been preliminarily reported as a strong 1.2 percent gain.
   For the first eight months of the year, activity was up only 0.4
percent over the same period in 1987, failing to keep pace with the
1.4 percent increase in construction costs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department has set
fuel-economy standards for 1989 passenger cars at 26.5 miles per
gallon of gasoline, a level the nation's two largest automakers say
they could meet without layoffs and production cuts.
   The department's decision disclosed Monday kept the fuel economy
average required for each auto manufacturer from increasing to the
27.5 mpg enacted by Congress in 1975. Since 1986, the automakers
have been required to meet a 26 mpg standard.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ninety percent of Americans believe the
government should require automakers to build cars with greater
fuel-efficiency, according to a poll commissioned by
environmentalists.
   Two-thirds of the respondents believe they will see another
energy crisis that could bring back gasoline lines, but nearly
three-quarters oppose a 30-cent increase in the gasoline tax aimed
at discouraging consumption, according to the survey released
Monday by the Analysis Group Inc., a New Haven, Conn.-based polling
firm.
   The poll was conducted for The Communications Consortium, a
public relations firm representing environmental groups.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has closed a chapter in the
largest municipal bond default in U.S. history, dismissing claims
by investors who lost money from the Washington Public Power Supply
System's doomed nuclear power project.
   The court let stand on Monday a ruling that dismissed some key
investor claims triggered by the $2.25 billion bond default. It
also rejected an appeal by the bond counsel in the case seeking
additional legal protection.
</TEXT>
