<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0530</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has expanded its study of
drug testing in the work place and agreed to consider, for the
second time in two years, the authority of states to deny
unemployment benefits to people who refuse to work on their Sabbath.
   In the drug testing case, the justices said Monday they will
decide whether a railroad routinely may require its employees to
take such tests.
   In the benefits case, Illinois officials declined to pay
unemployment benefits to a man whose refusal to work was not based
on the doctrine of any established religious body but on his
personal Christian belief.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has rejected a challenge to
the bankruptcy reorganization of Manville Corp., a building
materials manufacturer that once produced asbestos products.
   The court, without comment Monday, denied an appeal by a company
that distributed asbestos made by Manville, which changed its name
in 1981 from Johns-Manville Corp.
   The distributor, MacArthur Co., said the bankruptcy proceedings
unfairly denied it adequate financial protection.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.P. Scherer Corp. management has hired an
investment banker to explore the possible sale of the company, a
reversal that marks an apparent victory for dissident shareholders
led by the company founder's daughter.
   The company said Monday that 10 members of the Scherer board of
directors had voted unanimously to hire Goldman, Sachs & Co. to
look into a variety of alternatives, including sale to a third
party or a management buyout.
   Karla Scherer Fink, Scherer's largest shareholder and daughter
of the company's late founder, had pressured the board to sell the
company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. says it plans to sell its eight
broadcast television stations, partly to reduce its debt that has
grown to $929 million with its recent purchase of a leading
electronic information concern.
   Knight-Ridder, which also owns 30 daily newspapers, had acquired
the television stations in four separate transactions over the past
decade for an aggregate price of $291 million.
   The company declined to say Monday how much it expected to get
for the stations, but one analyst estimates the price could reach
$400 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Association of Securities Dealers
says that despite its opposition to market-wide trading halts, the
group would go along with one at the request of the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
   Although the NASD, which governs the over-the-counter stock
market, repeated its objections in detail, the new position by its
board of governors on Monday is seen as removing an important
obstacle to SEC approval of a proposed one-year experiment with a
trading halt rule.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices sagged in light trading Monday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials dropped 7.65 to 2,105.26.
   Bond prices rose modestly in light trading.
   The dollar weakened in foreign exchange.
   Hog and pork belly prices plummeted at the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange. Grain prices rose, soybeans were mixed, oil prices
tumbled, live cattle prices rallied and feeder cattle were mixed.
</TEXT>
