<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     10-04 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Factory Orders Surge; Oil Prices Continue To Plunge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have declined to levels not seen since August
1986 and the government has reported a strong rise in factory
orders, signaling what some experts say will be continued
non-inflationary growth for the U.S. economy.
   The jump in factory orders reported Monday by the Commerce
Department indicates the economy continues expanding at a healthy
clip, while lower oil prices should dampen the inflation that
accompanies rapid growth, economists said.
   But experts cautioned that consumers probably would not benefit
significantly from the drop in crude oil prices unless they
remained at the currently depressed levels for an extended period.
   Oil prices have skidded $2 a barrel over the past five weeks to
their lowest point since August 1986. On Monday, the November
contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude,
fell 31 cents to $13.06 a barrel on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods surged 3.1
percent in August, the Commerce Department said.
   Although factory orders tend to swing erratically from one month
to the next, analysts said the underlying trend is strong.
   ``There has been some question in the (financial) markets as to
whether manufacturing is stalling out. ...But with the orders
situation as strong as it is, it's clear to us manufacturing
remains on a solid track,'' said Stephen S. Roach, an economist
with Morgan Stanley & Co. ``I think the economy as a whole is
continuing to display very good momentum.''
   Jerry Jasinowski, chief economist of the National Association of
Manufacturers, said members of his trade group remained optimistic,
at least for the rest of 1988.
   ``Manufacturers in general don't see any slowdown in their
orders over the next three to four months,'' he said.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped
7.65 to 2,105.26 in light trading on Monday. Bond prices rose,
while the dollar weakened.
   In another report, the Commerce Department said construction
spending in August fell 0.6 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of $396.1 billion.
   Economists said rising interest rates and high vacancy rates for
many kinds of buildings have kept this sector sluggish.
</TEXT>
