<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Scherer Bjt   10-04 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scherer, Bjt,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scherer Board Taps Banking Firm to Look into Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forces trying to keep R.P. Scherer Corp. off the
auction block may have have lost a round in their fight as the
company's board of directors takes a step toward a possible sale.
   On Monday, the gelatin capsule maker announced its board voted
unanimously Friday to hire the investment banker Goldman, Sachs &
Co. to look into a variety of alternatives, including sale of the
company to a third party or to management.
   For months, the board has been involved in a fight over control
of the company, split between forces backing President and Chief
Executive Officer Peter Fink, who has opposed any sale, and
dissident shareholders led by his estranged wife, Karla Scherer
Fink, who also is the daughter of the company's late founder.
   The dissident group also successfully blocked several management
stock-option proposals. Mrs. Fink controls about 33 percent of the
company's shares.
   A proxy fight over the issue last August, in which the
dissidents ousted at least one director who opposed their plans,
has spilled over into the Court of Chancery in Delaware, where
Scherer is incorporated.
   Scherer spokeswoman Jayne Colombo declined to say Monday whether
the vote by Fink and others to explore a possible sale represented
a shift in their positions.
   Analyst Dean Gulis of William C. Roney & Co. of Detroit said the
decision could represent such a move, but he also said recent
action in the over-the-counter market, where Scherer stock is
traded, ``represented a very attractive price for this stock.''
   During the past several months, while the corporate wrangling
has been going on, Scherer stock has been trading in the mid- to
upper-$20 range.
   Scherer stock closed at $28.75 a share on Monday, up 25 cents
from Friday's close in national over-the-counter trading.
   ``I think it (Friday's decision) is just a recognition that,
`OK, we have a big chunk of the stock that wants to sell the
company and fine, let's see if we can sell the company,''' Gulis
said.
   Friday's vote by 10 board members did not include a ballot from
one board member, whose seat is in dispute.
   In addition to sale, the board said in a news release the firm
would look into merger and recapitalization. Fink said the decision
to hire Goldman, Sachs did not mean necessarily that the company
would be sold.
   The board is to meet again Oct. 25 and will review findings of
the firm's investigation.
   Pending before the court in Delaware are complaints by directors
John Scherer, Frederick Frank and Theodore Souris, who have said
they favor selling the 2,800-employee company, and Peter A. Dow,
who has backed keeping the company. Dow, who was running for
re-election, said some votes for him were not counted in the August
board election.
   Also on Monday, Fink announced that Scherer Chairman Wilber
Hadley Mack, 78, had retired after serving as the company's
chairman since January 1980. In the announcement, Fink said Mack
would remain on the company's board and a member of its executive
committee.
</TEXT>
