<1ST_LINE>r f PM-USLoanGuarantees     10-04 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US Loan Guarantees,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Bank Pushes Guarantees for Private Loans
^Eds: For Release at 10 a.m. EDT; Time set by source. A version
moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Export-Import Bank, by guaranteeing
commercial banks' loans to Third World countries, may be able to
encourage banks to step up financing world trade, the government
bank's president, John A. Bohn Jr., told Congress.
   ``U.S. commercial banks ... have turned away from supporting
exports to large segments of the globe,'' he said in remarks
prepared for delivery today to the subcommittee on exports of the
House Committee on Small Business.
   Some bankers say they will only make more loans to the Third
World _ which already owes over $1.2 trillion to banks and has
fallen far behind on repayments _ if they get government guarantees.
   At last week's meeting of the International Monetary Fund in
Berlin, Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady and other Western
leaders came out strongly against shifting responsibility for risky
loans to the shoulders of governments and their taxpayers.
   For the year that began Oct. 1, Congress has authorized the
Export-Import Bank to make only $695 million worth of direct loans
but to guarantee $10.2 billion in loans by private banks.
   Bohn explained that commercial banks now have more stringent
rules to make sure that they have enough capital for international
loans and that they have set aside enough reserves to protect their
depositors. So commercial banks have little appetite or capacity to
take risks in some countries, he added.
   Many banks have dropped out of trade finance altogether, others
will only help their biggest and best customers, he noted. Bohn
would like to encourage small American businesses to export more.
   He said a Los Angeles commercial bank recently approved a $15
million line of credit for the Los Angeles Local Development Corp.
to make working capital loans that may be guaranteed by the
Export-Import Bank.
   ``We believe this ... may show the commercial banking community
a way to participate once again profitably in trade finance,'' Bohn
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
