<DOCNO> AP881004-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     10-04 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0322</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged lower today, extending
its decline of the past two sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 14 points
over the past two sessions, was off another 0.71 at 2,104.55 after
30 minutes of trading.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of about 5 to 4
among issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 377 up,
488 down and 504 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.48 million shares at 10 a.m.
on Wall Street, compared with 16.51 million shares at the same
point Monday.
   Stock investors have taken a cautious approach to the market in
recent weeks as they try to project what lies ahead for the economy.
   While recent economic reports have indicated growth is
proceeding at a moderate pace, some concerns remain that growth
could stimulate inflation.
   That has served to limit stock price gains, as it is widely
expected that the Federal Reserve would encourage higher interest
rates if inflation appeared to pick up.
   Higher rates make returns on fixed-income investments such as
Treasury notes and bonds more attractive compared with stocks.
   Among the early active issues on the NYSE, Manville was up \ at
2, Phelps Dodge was up 1{ at 42{, Zayre was unchanged at 26\ and
Coca-Cola was off \ at 42~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.20 at 153.03. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite
market index was down 0.14 at 299.86.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 7.65 to
2,105.26.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 4 on the
NYSE, with 527 up, 947 down and 445 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 130.38 million shares, against 175.75
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
