<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Pillsbury 3rdLd-Writethru   10-04 0825</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0852</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Met Offers $5.17 Billion For Pillsbury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES grafs 11-23 with details, Delaware court filing,
quotes; uppicks 21st graf pvs: ``Pillsbury has ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. says it was caught by surprise
when the British giant Grand Metropolitan PLC launched a
$60-a-share takeover bid for the food conglomerate.
   The offer would be worth about $5.17 billion based on
Pillsbury's roughly 86.2 million common shares outstanding.
   It was first outlined in an advertisement in today's New York
Times and discussed later by Grand Met officials at a London news
conference.
   Craig Carver, an analyst for Dain Bosworth Inc. in Minneapolis,
said the bid was ``a heck of a good offer,'' but other analysts
predicted other offers might surface.
   ``I would say top dollar is in the $70 (a share) range. This
just might be the first volley,'' said Stephen Carnes, an analyst
wth Piper Jaffray & Hopwood in Minneapolis.
   Pillsbury stock closed at $39 a share Monday, up $1.12{ on New
York Stock Exchange. Trading in Pillsbury was delayed today, but
there were indications the stock would open above $57 a share.
   Johnny Thompson, a Pillsbury spokesman, said Pillsbury's
management was not approached by Grand Met and that he only learned
of the offer after being contacted by the news media late Monday.
   ``We've received nothing and we've been contacted by no one,''
Thompson said, ``and until something like that happens we're in no
position to make a comment.''
   Clive Strowger, chief executive of Grand Met's food division,
said the company launched the surprise bid because ``there was no
indication that its (Pillsbury's) management was interested in
receiving a friendly approach.''
   At the London news conference, Grand Met officials said Ian
Martin, chief executive of Grand Met's U.S. operations, had
traveled to Minneapolis and hoped to meet with top Pillsbury
management later today.
   ``We are prepared to enter into negotiations immediately with
respect to all aspects of our proposal, including price,'' Martin
said in a letter delivered today to Pillsbury Chairman Philip L.
Smith.
   Pillsbury, the nation's fourth-largest food conglomerate,
produces Green Giant vegetables, Haagen-Dazs ice creams and Van de
Kamp's frozen fish. Its restaurant operations include the Steak &
Ale and Bennigan's chains.
   The offer by Grant Met, a diversified food, retailing and hotel
company that is the world's largest spirits company, was
conditioned on a majority of Pillsbury shares being tendered, on
Pillsbury shareholders approving the merger and the Pillsbury board
of directors invalidating the company's takeover defenses.
   Grand Met said it began litigation on Monday in Delaware
Chancery Court seeking to invalidate Pillsbury's ``poison pill''
takeover defense, which would make an unsolicited merger
prohibitively expensive.
   Pillsbury has been the target of lively takeover speculation in
recent months, due to management turmoil and sagging earnings that
have helped depress its stock price.
   The company, which gets about half of its total revenue from its
restaurant operations, including the troubled Burger King fast-food
chain, has been attempting to rebound from the impact of a
restructuring that caused its profit to fall to $69.3 million in
fiscal 1988, on sales of $6.2 billion.
   The profit decline stemmed largely from a restructuring charge
associated with the sale of its Godfather's Pizza chain and a
number of other restaurant operations and consolidations.
   Pillsbury tapped Smith, the former chairman of rival General
Foods Corp., as its new chairman in July. He replaced William H.
Spoor, who came out of retirement earlier this year to run the
company on an interim basis after former chairman John Stafford
resigned under pressure.
   In his letter to Smith, Martin said Grand Met would make
Minneapolis the world headquarters of the company's international
foods group.
   He also said Grand Met sees ``great promise in (the) Burger King
business,'' which has ``great prospects for improved profitability
in the United States and for expansion in ... international
markets.''
   Pillsbury management has been under pressure to either boost
sagging revenues at Burger King or divest the unit, which is the
world's second-largest restaurant chain.
   Grand Met, with annual sales of about $10 billion, makes
Smirnoff vodka and J & B Scotch and has interests in food,
retailing and hotels. Its other businesses include Alpo petfood and
Pearle vision centers.
   Last Friday the company announced the sale of its
Inter-Continental hotel chain to Seibu Saison Group of Japan for
$2.27 billion in cash, from which it expected to net about $845
million after taxes. Grand Met said it planned to use the procceds
for further acquisitions.
   ``Pillsbury has strong, powerful consumer brands, and that is
something very dear to our hearts,'' Grand Met Chairman Allen
Sheppard told the London news conference.
   The company has said its strategy is to focus on foods, liquor
and retailing and to expand its operations in North America.
   Grand Met currently is embroiled in a contested bid for Irish
Distillers Group PLC, Ireland's leading whisky maker, for which
Grand Met has offered around $465 million.
</TEXT>
