<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Soviets-Hollywood     10-04 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Soviets-Hollywood,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hollywood Film Company Says It Will Take Part in $300 Million
Venture</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   MOSCOW (AP ) _ A Hollywood film and investment company says it
has agreed to fund half of a $300 million trade-culture-sports
complex at an unidentified Moscow location in a joint venture with
a Soviet cooperative.
   FresFilm has been assured that it will be able to take its
profits from the project out of the Soviet Union in foreign
currency, president Tom Meehan told a Tuesday news conference at
the Union of Cinematographers.
   Soviet restrictions on removing foreign currency stymie many
joint ventures. Companies can earn millions of rubles selling
long-sought Western goods in the Soviet Union, but find it
extremely difficult to convert that fortune into a currency that
has a value on the world market.
   The complex to be built by FresFilm and Cooperative Circle, its
Soviet partner, will start with a small store and then a hotel for
foreigners, Meehan said. He believes hard currency earned from the
foreigners at the hotel will permit repatriation of his group's
profits.
   Eventually, the joint venture's projects are to include a
world-class arts center, sport facilities, conference halls, a
library, an amusement park, an art gallery and a television studio,
Meehan said.
   FresFilm, which is headquartered in Hollywood, Calif.,
previously agreed to produce four movies with Soviet government
film studios, including one on Napoleon's invasion of Russia.
</TEXT>
