<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GouldChairman 1stLd-Writethru f0028 10-04 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gould Chairman, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0028,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferguson Replaces McDonald As Gould Chairman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to update with company announcing relocation</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gould Inc. said James F. McDonald has resigned as
chairman and chief executive in connection with Gould's acquisition
by Japan's Nippon Mining Co.
   McDonald will join the board of Gould NavCom Systems Inc., a
subsidiary that will have complete autonomy from the Japanse
parent. That separation is required by the Pentagon because the
unit is a major defense contractor.
   C. David Ferguson, 46, a 25-year veteran of the company, was
named Monday to replace McDonald. He was most recently executive
vice president of Gould's materials and components division.
   The company also announced today it was moving its corporate
headquarters from the Chicago suburb of Rolling Meadows to
Eastlake, Ohio, near Cleveland, where most of Gould's remaining
properties are located. The relocation is expected to be completed
in 1990 and include the addition of about 25 jobs.
   Gould already has divested itself of most of its defense units.
It continues to own Navcom, which is tied up in a dispute with the
federal government over a fixed pricing contract.
