<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0460</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market languished today in moderate
trading, as a key blue-chip index edged higher while some broader
market measures slipped.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 7.65 points
on Monday and 14 points over the past two sessions, was up 0.36 at
2,105.62 at noontime.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of about 6 to 5
among issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 545 up,
682 down and 535 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 76.52 million shares at noon on
Wall Street, compared with 64.95 million shares at the same point
Monday.
   ``It's still an uphill battle,'' said Jack Baker, head of block
trading for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``As long as the bond
market stays here and dollar stays here, we can probably hold at
2,100 (on the Dow Jones industrials).''
   Gene Jay Seagle, vice president and director of technical
research at Gruntal Financial Inc., said, ``The market may be
drifting, but there are a number of stocks that aren't.''
   He noted Pillsbury was the most actively traded issue on the New
York Stock Exchange today, rocketing 18{ to 57{ after it received a
takeover bid at $60 a share from a British firm, Grand Metropolitan
PLC.
   Seagle said the bid may remind investors that there are some
sizeably undervalued stocks available.
   ``This message ought to again be heard by the street that stocks
in the United States are selling on a lower value basis than the
rest of the world seems to consider fair,'' he said.
   Stock investors here have taken a cautious approach to the
market in recent weeks as they try to anticipate what lies ahead
for the economy.
   While recent economic reports have indicated growth is
proceeding at a moderate pace, some concerns remain that growth
could stimulate inflation.
   Those concerns have limited stock price gains, as it is widely
expected that the Federal Reserve would encourage higher interest
rates if inflation were to pick up.
   Higher interest rates make returns on fixed-income investments
such as Treasury notes and bonds more attractive compared with
stocks.
   Other companies with big food holdings were also up. Philip
Morris was up 1[ at 98[, R.J. Nabisco was up } at 56] and Quaker
Oats was up 1[ at 55[.
   Inco Ltd. rose 2 to 31 after announcing a recapitalization plan
that includes a special dividend of $10 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.04 at 153.19. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite
market index was down 0.47 at 299.53.
