<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-UnitedStates     10-04 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-United States,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guarded EEC Response To U.S. Statement On Farm Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community gave a
cautious response Tuesday to a U.S. offer to discuss short-term
measures on world agriculture reform.
   A spokeswoman for the European Commission, acting for the EEC,
said the U.S. offer was an apparent effort to unblock the current
impasse in the Uruguay round of trade liberalization talks.
   The spokeswoman, who requested anonymity, said that the EEC
welcomed any effort to undertake short-term reforms in agriculture,
but it would have to study the U.S. offer, made at a meeting of
trade ministers in Pakistan, and ``see what the U.S. position
means.''
   ``There will be additional discussions on this,'' she said.
   Until now, the U.S. has argued for the long-term elimination of
farm subsidies and resisted pleas for short-term reforms.
   The EEC believes that ending subsidies is unrealistic and
prefers a gradual and less radical approach which would also have
some immediate effect in restoring order to markets in farm
products.
</TEXT>
