<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0403</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with higher closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London stock exchange closed
higher Tuesday after recovering from falls sparked by a flood of
major corporate news.
   Traders said the market's early weakness reflected concern about
a 479 million-pound ($812 million) rights issue and bid by Grand
Metropolitan PLC for Pillsbury Co. of the United States and the
government-ordered reduction of the Kuwait Investment Office's
stake in British Petroleum.
   Several dealers were at a loss to pinpoint the drift higher.
   But others said shares recovered amid a lack of selling pressure
and because few bargain hunters took advantage of the market's low
levels.
   Some dealers were encouraged by the fact share prices didn't
fall even further in the morning.
   ``I can see no reason why we're going better, except that we've
simply reversed engines after this morning's slide,'' one equity
salesman said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 4.7
points, or 0.3 percent, higher at 1,807.3, slightly below the day's
best level of 1808.2. The index lost as much as 15.6 points in
early dealings.
   At the close, the narrower Financial Times 30-share index was up
1.8 points at 1,457.6.
   Volume was still at relatively slack levels, with 440.0 million
shares changing hands, compared with the 337.4 million shares
traded Monday.
   Wall Street was largely overlooked by London players, several
dealers said.
   The market's early weakness reflected concern about the Grand
Met rights issue to fund an unsolicited $5.12 billion tender offer
for Pillsbury, dealers said.
   Shares in Grand Met were among the major movers, falling 32
pence to 454 pence on the news. Grand Met shares were heavily
traded, with stock exchange figures showing 14 million shares
traded by the close.
   Sentiment also turned sour as the British government ordered the
Kuwait Investment Office to sharply reduce its holding in British
Petroleum to 9.9 percent from the current 21.68 percent over a
period of around 12 months.
   The announcement triggered a flurry of heavy trading in British
Petroleum shares.
   Dealers said the decision had been expected, but many analysts
had predicted the Kuwaitis would only be required to reduce their
holding to around 15 percent.
   British Petroleum shares finished unchanged at 237 on volume of
14 million shares, after dropping to a low of 227.
</TEXT>
