<1ST_LINE>r f BC-RamadaSuit     10-04 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ramada Suit,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ramada To Respond to Shareholder Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramada Inc. plans to respond in court to a
lawsuit filed by its second-largest shareholder, a company
spokesman said Tuesday.
   Joe Cole, Ramada's vice president of corporate communications,
said the company was refusing further comment on Donald Callender's
suit seeking $371 million in damages.
   Callender, who sold his Marie Callender's Pie Shops to Ramada in
1986 for cash and stock, charged in the suit filed Monday in Orange
County Superior Court in Santa Ana, Calif., that Ramada's directors
shortchanged stockholders and the company by rejecting a
$10-a-share buyout offer from an affiliate of the Hyatt hotel chain.
   The $371 million is the same price HCC Corp. of Chicago offered
last month for all outstanding Ramada stock that it did not own.
HCC is owned by the Pritzker family of Chicago, Ramada's largest
stockholder.
   On Sept. 16, the directors of Ramada rejected that price as
``grossly inadequate and unfair.''
   Randall Waier, an attorney in Santa Ana who represents
Callender, said the suit would permit participation by Ramada's
more than 33,000 shareholders.
   ``My response is, everyone's entitled to their own opinion,''
said John R. Norton III, a Ramada director.
   He said Ramada's directors believed that their rejection of the
HCC offer was in the shareholders' best interests.
   Securities analysts have valued Ramada at $11 to $13 a share. In
the past five years, the high for Ramada's stock has been $11.88,
but Ramada shares have traded as low as $4 in the past year.
Earnings per share have suffered as operating income at Ramada has
fallen during three of the past four years.
   Waier said the suit charges that directors ``breached their
fiduciary duty'' to stockholders in several ways.
   ``We contend that some of the board members are in a conflict of
interest in that they are officers of Ramada and they took their
interests over those of the shareholders,'' he said. ``We perceive
their motivation is to perpetuate themselves in office.''
   Three of Ramada's 10 directors are executives at Ramada. They
are Richard Snell, chairman and president; Paul Rubeli, executive
vice president of the gaming group; and Thomas Martin, executive
vice president of the restaurant group.
   The suit also says the directors used inadequate data in their
decision.
   The board said it based its decision in part on an opinion from
Salomon Brothers Inc., a Wall Street investment company acting as
Ramada's financial adviser. Norton said that the adviser's opinion
was only ``one of the considerations'' but that he was unable to
reveal other sources.
   A Securities and Exchange Commission filing by HCC on Thursday
said that Ramada was considering restructuring and other
alternatives to the Pritzker offer.
   ``If the company's mismanaged, what are they going to
restructure?'' Callender said in a telephone conversation from a
Marie Callender's in Newport Beach, Calif.
   The stockholder's lawsuit is the fourth that Callender has
brought against Ramada. Callender and Ramada have been embroiled in
bitter disagreements during the past year. Both sides are suing
each other over pie royalties and charges of mismanagement.
   In 1986, Ramada entered a five-year contract with Callender's
consulting company to assist the Marie Callender's chain. Several
weeks ago, Callender claimed, Ramada broke off the contract for the
135 restaurants.
   One of Callender's suits, based on what he calls the wrongful
termination of that contract, asks the court to drop restrictions
that require Callender to hold his Ramada stock for five years,
Waier said. Callender wants to sell the stock he received two years
ago in the Marie Callender's deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881004-0252 </DOCNO>
