<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SunSpinoff     10-04 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sun Spinoff,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stockholders Approve Splitting Nation's 10th Largest Oil Firm Into
Two Parts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stockholders of the Sun Co., the nation's
10th largest oil firm, Tuesday overwhelmingly approved a major
restructuring proposal that spins off its $4.2 billion domestic gas
exploration and production into a separate operation and cuts 1,300
jobs.
   At the same time, the new structure retains the refining and
marketing of petroleum into a slimmed-down business.
   Under the plan, adopted at a special meeting in nearby King of
Prussia, shareholders will receive one common share of the new Sun
Exploration & Production Co. for each common share of Sun,
effective Nov. 1.
   Record date for distribution is Oct. 14.
   Stockholders representing less than 1.5 percent of Sun's 106
million outstanding shares opposed the plan, Sun spokesman Ray
Enderle said. He could not provide specific figures.
   In 1987 Sun Co. reported more than $9.1 billion in revenues. It
had some 20,000 employees in the United States and eight other
countries.
   Both new firms plan to reduce employment within a year _ Sun
Exploration trimming 800 from the 4,000 workers it is getting in
the restructuring and Sun Co. cutting approximately 500 from its
headquarters staff.
   Sun Exploration, in the spinoff, will become the largest
independent oil and gas producer in North America, Enderle said. As
an integrated company that combined exploration, production,
refining and marketing, Sun Co. was the 10th largest U.S. oil
company.
   Sun stock has been selling at around $57. It had shot up above
$60 when the restructuring announcement was made last July.
   The stock of each of the new firms is expected to start off at
around $28 to $30.
   ``We were attempting to achieve an increased value for our
shareholders,'' said Fred Huffman, Sun Co. director of investor
relations. ``By becoming two companies the total value of the stock
together will be more than it is alone.
   ``Since July 1 we have outperformed in the stock market other
major oil companies, and it is anticipated that shareholder value
will continue to be enhanced.''
   Andrew Gray III, an oil industry analyst, said he thinks
stockholders will benefit from the spinoff.
   ``You'll have two purer-type companies (and) you will have a
purer play,'' he said.
   Under a previously announced Internal Revenue Service ruling
neither Sun nor its shareholders will incur any federal income tax
liability from the distribution.
   Robert Hauptfuhrer, Sun president and chief operating officer,
will become chairman and chief executive officer of the new
exploration firm that will be based in Dallas, Texas. Robert
McClements Jr., remains chairman and CEO of Sun Co. headquartered
in the Philadelphia suburb of Radnor with assets of around $8.5
billion.
   Sun officials expect the restructuring to produce about $65
million in after-tax savings for Sun Exploration each year and
around $15 million for Sun Co., mostly through payroll reductions.
   Sun has five refineries in Pennsylvania, Ohio, Oklahoma, Puerto
Rico and Canada, mines coal in five states and sells gasoline,
under the Sunoco brand, at more than 6,000 stations in 23 states.
   It will add another 1,000 outlets and a Philadelphia refinery
when it completes its recent purchase of the Atlantic Petroleum
Corp. of Valley Forge, Pa.
   Also part of the deal is a 986-mile products pipeline system
that runs from Philadelphia to Pittsburgh and into New York state
at Rochester and Tonawanda.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
