<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Venezuela-Oil     10-04 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Venezuela-Oil,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low oil prices to hurt Venezuela's debt payment capacity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia's move to shock fellow
OPEC members into cutting oil output by forcing prices down
undoubtedly will affect Venezuela's ability to service its foreign
debt, Venezuelan Energy and Mines Minister Julio Cesar Gil said
Tuesday.
   Gil told a news conference the current ``price war'' could bring
prices down temporarily to two-year lows of below $10 a barrel.
   ``We are arriving at (price) levels of 1986...Undoubtedly this
will compromise the payment of the debt,'' Gil said.
   He said any decision regarding debt payments would be made by
the Finance Ministry.
   ``I do not know what price level Venezuela can bear,'' Gil said.
   When oil prices fell in 1986, Venezuela called for
renegotiations on its $35 billion foreign debt and stopped making
principal payments on its $20.34 billion of refinanced public debt
while talks were held.
   ``Perhaps prices will reach a level we haven't seen in two
years. This could be encouraging for (OPEC) to arrive at an
agreement'' on curbing output, he said.
   He said Saudi Arabia warned other OPEC members of its decision
to force prices down during the Sept.25-26 meeting in Madrid of
OPEC's price monitoring committee.
   ``We understand Saudi Arabia's desire to bring discipline to the
market through shock treatment but the affects do not please us.''
   He said a joint meeting in the third week of October of OPEC's
long-term strategy committee and the price committee is likely to
last longer than the meeting of the price committee alone.
   ``There are more countries and more matters to discuss,'' he
said. He said the site of the meeting has not yet been decided.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
