<DOCNO> AP881004-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 1547EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-AutoSales     10-04 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Auto Sales,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1988 Model Year: Looking Better Than Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three automakers in the United States
wound up the 1988 model year on a down note, with domestically made
car and truck sales dipping 9 percent in late September, the
companies said Tuesday.
   But for the 1988 model year, foreign and domestic car makers
were poised on what could be the one of the best years in
automotive sales history.
   During the last 10-day period of the 1988 model year _ Sept.
21-30 _ General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp.
reported selling 346,948 cars and light trucks, down from the
381,013 vehicles they sold during the same period in 1987.
   There were nine selling days in both periods.
   For the model year, the Big Three reported sales jumped 3
percent, to 10,774,342 vehicles in the period Oct. 1, 1987-Sept.
30, 1988, compared with 10,428,653 cars and light trucks sold
during the 1987 model year.
   There were 308 selling days in the 1988 model year, one more
than the year before.
   At the beginning of the model year, industry analysts predicted
the auto industry would be doing well to sell 15 million cars and
light trucks. But in the last few months of the model year, those
estimates were revised upward to about 15.5 million vehicles _
roughly two-thirds cars and one-third light trucks.
   That would make it the third-best model year on record, behind
the 16 million sold in 1986 and the 15.7 million sold the year
before that, and a few thousand vehicles ahead of the 1987 model
year.
   GM suffered the biggest percentage loss on sales of U.S.-made
cars in late September, dropping 15 percent to 116,028 in the 1988
period compared with 136,483 cars during the same time last year.
   Ford said it sold 70,813 cars in late September, down 14.3
percent from the 82,606 cars it sold during the same period last
year. But for the model year, Ford's car sales were up 2.9 percent,
rising to 2,140,289 in 1988 from 2,073,845 in the the last model
year.
   Sales of Chrysler's U.S.-built cars fell the least among the Big
Three late last month, dropping to 33,314 this year from 34,898
during the period last year, a 4.5 percent decline.
</TEXT>
