<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     10-04 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0172</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished lower today for the
third consecutive session. Trading was moderate.
   Analysts said worries about interest rates and the outlook for
corporate profits continue to weigh on stock prices.
   But some issues, the most prominent of which are actual or
potential takeover targets, managed to post gains.
   Investors have taken a cautious approach to the market in recent
weeks as they try to anticipate what lies ahead for the economy.
   While recent economic reports have indicated growth is
proceeding at a moderate pace, some concerns remain that continued
growth could stimulate inflation and prompt the Federal Reserve to
encourage higher interest rates.
   Higher interest rates make returns on fixed-income investments
such as Treasury notes and bonds more attractive compared with
stocks.
   The market is already looking ahead to the September
unemployment report set for release on Friday for the latest clue
on the health of the economy.
</TEXT>
