<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-04 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher Against Pound and Mark</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed in an active session
Tuesday, but traders attributed the currency's spotty gains to
technical factors rather than fundamental strength.
   Gold prices were mixed. Republic National Bank quoted bullion at
$397.60 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EDT, up from $396.95 late Monday.
   Traders said the market was inclined to sell dollars, but a drop
in the British pound prevented the U.S. currency from falling
across the board. The dollar posted its best gains on the day
against the pound and the West German mark.
   The British government's decision to order the Kuwaiti
Investment Office to sharply reduce its holding in British
Petroleum Co. PLC sparked speculation that Kuwait might sell
significant amounts of sterling. Those fears worked to weaken the
pound and firm the dollar.
   Separately, the dollar initially seesawed on rumors swirling
around Saudi Arabia's status within the OPEC cartel. Saudi Arabia
has threatened to flood world markets with its crude oil to punish
other oil producing nations that have ignored quotas by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   Bob Morrissey, a senior trader at the Bank of Boston in New
York, said there also was talk that Saudi Arabia ``might be
dropping out of OPEC. But when those rumors were denied, it brought
the dollar back up.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.75 yen to a closing 133.15 yen from
Monday's 133.90. Later, in London, it was quoted at a higher rate
of 133.20 yen. In New York, the dollar closed at 133.31 yen, down
from 133.68 yen on Monday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6945 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6990 late Monday. In New
York, it cost $1.6952 to buy one pound, less expensive than
Monday's $1.7019.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday,
included: 1.8646 West German marks, up from 1.8617; 1.5827 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5820; 6.3460 French francs, up from 6.3420;
1,389.50 Italian lire, up from 1,387.00, and 1.2082 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2097.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,
included: 1.8610 West German marks, up from 1.8608; 1.5775 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5785; 6.3285 French francs, down from 6.3350;
2.0950 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1010; 1,385.875 Italian lire,
down from 1,397.95; and 1.20965 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2104.
   Gold prices rose on the New York Commodity Exchange to $398.10 a
troy ounce, from Monday's $397.50.
   But in London, gold fell to a late bid price of $397.45 a troy
ounce, compared with late Monday's $397.75. The metal also moved
lower in Zurich, where gold closed at a bid $396.90 an ounce,
compared with $397 late Monday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose $4.32 to close at $402.23 an
ounce.
   Silver prices were unchanged on New York's Comex, closing at
$6.248 a troy ounce. Silver prices rose in London to a late bid
price of $6.23 a troy ounce, compared with Monday's $6.22.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
