<DOCNO> AP881004-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MassTransit     10-04 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mass Transit,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kiley Calls for Increase in Mass Transit's Share of Gas Tax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investment in the nation's mass transit systems
should be doubled and the best way to do it is to earmark more of
the federal gasoline tax, the head of the nation's largest transit
system said Tuesday.
   Only 1 cent per gallon of the federal gasoline tax now goes to
support mass transit and it needs to be at least 7 cents to create
a stable funding base for transit systems nationwide, according to
Robert Kiley, chairman of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority.
   ``In 1987, the auto industry spent $5 billion promoting itself
through television advertising,'' Kiley said. ``That, my friends,
is nearly 25 percent more than we spent on capital improvements for
public transportation.''
   He made his remarks in Montreal at the annual meeting of the
American Public Transit Association, whose members include the
managers of virtually every transit system in this country and
Canada as well as representatives of the businesses that supply the
transit industry.
   The federal gasoline tax, now at 9 cents per gallon, raises
about $9 billion a year, $8 billion of which goes to the interstate
highways. The tax, which was imposed 29 years ago at 4 cents a
gallon, was created solely to finance the building of the
47,000-mile interstate system. It was raised by 5 cents in 1983 and
a penny was earmarked for mass transit.
   With the interstates finished, the federal gasoline tax is to
expire in 1991.
   ``That means that the 9-cent gasoline tax will be up for grabs,
so to speak,'' Kiley said.
   Kiley, speaking as chairman of the Transit 2000 task force, an
APTA committee developing longterm transportation initiatives,
recommended that:
   _The tax be extended.
   _Mass transit retain the penny now reserved for public
transportation.
   _Two cents be added to the gasoline tax to replace the $2
billion in
   transit aid that is subject to federal budget battles each year.
   _Another 4 cents to pay for new buses, subways, and construction
of new rail systems.
   With dedicated taxes to replace the $2 billion that is
appropriated each year, that money could be used to reduce the
federal deficit, Kiley said.
   Kiley said he would seek support for the Transit 2000
recommendation from the National League of Cities and the U.S.
Conference of Mayors.
   Reapportionment of the federal gasoline tax will become a major
issue for the next Congress and president as the nation's great
road building era comes to an end, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881004-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Netherlands-Takeovers     10-04 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Netherlands-Takeovers,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch Institutions Offer `White Knight' Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four of the largest financial
institutions in the Netherlands announced a plan Tuesday to act
together to help defend Dutch companies against hostile tender
offers deemed to be priced too low.
   The four partners include the two largest Dutch insurers,
Nationale-Nederlanden NV and Aegon NV, the third lartest banking
group, Amsterdam-Rotterdam Bank NV, and the collective pension
funds of the big electronics concern NV Philips
Gloeilampenfabrieken.
   The aim of the venture is ``to prevent quoted Dutch companies
from falling victim to a hostile takeover priced at unacceptably
low levels,'' Amsterdam-Rotterdam Bank, as spokesman for the group,
said in a brief statement.
   The group would act only if requested by a company being pursued
in a takeover fight.
   A spokesman said the partners initiated the venture in part to
help protect Dutch companies from forays by foreign companies in
advance of the 1992 deadline for creating a single market
encompassing the 12 nations in the European Economic Community.
   But the white-knight service offered by the four institutions is
not purely of an altruistic nature, but also is seen as a
potentially major profit source, said H.W. Wolf, a spokesman for
the bank.
   The intention of the venture is to defeat hostile tender offers
either through a competing tender offer or on the open market, Wolf
said.
   Shares acquired in that process, however, would not be held as a
long-term investment or for merger purposes by the group. Rather
they would be fairly quickly sold back into the stock market, with
the intention of making a profit on the transaction, Wolf said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
