<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Finish Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gave ground Tuesday for the
third consecutive session as concerns about interest rates weighed
on prices and more than offset the scattered gains that resulted
from takeover speculation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, off more than 14
points over the past two sessions, lost another 3.20 points to
close at 2,102.06.
   Declining issues outnumbered gainers by about 7-to-6 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
658 issues up, 778 down and 524 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 157.76 million shares,
up from 130.38 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
184.92 million shares.
   ``It's still an uphill battle,'' said Jack Baker, head of block
trading for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``As long as the bond
market stays here and dollar stays here, we can probably hold at
2,100 (on the Dow Jones industrials).''
   Bond prices held firm Tuesday while the dollar finished mixed in
foreign exchange trading.
   Rao Chalasani, chief investment strategist for Prescott, Ball &
Turben in Cleveland, said stock prices are suffering because of the
near-9 percent yields available on 30-year Treasury bonds.
   He said investors also face the prospect of more modest
corporate earnings gains for the forseeable future than they saw in
the second quarter.
   On the other hand, he said stocks are drawing some support from
proposed stock buybacks and buyouts and from demand from foreign
investors.
   That was clearly illustrated Tuesday as Pillsbury was the most
active issues on the NYSE, rocketing 18 to 57 after receiving a
takeover bid of $60 a share from Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   Gene Jay Seagle, vice president and director of technical
research at Gruntal Financial Inc., said the bid may remind
investors that there are some significantly undervalued stocks
available.
   ``This message ought to again be heard by the Street that stocks
in the United States are selling on a lower value basis than the
rest of the world seems to consider fair,'' he said.
   Stock investors here have taken a cautious approach to the
market in recent weeks as they try to anticipate what lies ahead
for the economy.
   They are looking toward Friday's scheduled release of the
September unemployment report for the latest shred of evidence on
the economy's health.
   While recent reports have indicated growth is proceeding at a
moderate pace, some concerns remain that even that could stimulate
inflation and prompt the Federal Reserve to encourage higher
interest rates.
   Among other active issues Tuesday on the NYSE, Manville rose 1[
to 2~. Its reorganization plan appeared to move a step closer to
fruition after the Supreme Court refused Monday to hear an appeal.
   Inco Ltd. rose 1~ to 30~ after announcing a recapitalization
plan that includes a special dividend of $10 a share.
   Among widely-held stocks, International Business Machines fell ]
to 114{, Eastman Kodak fell [ to 45} and General Electric fell ] to
42~.
   On the American Stock Exchange, Texas Air was the most active
stock, slipping [ to 14\. It announced a $50 million agreement to
allow Scandinavian Airlines System to lease New York area airport
gates and giving SAS the option to buy up to 10 percent of Texas
Air's stock.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market fell $5.17 billion, or 0.19
percent, in value.
   The NYSE index slipped 0.30 to 152.93.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index fell 0.72 to 310.42, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was down 0.76 to 270.62.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 0.38
to 299.62. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market fell 0.28 to 384.20.
</TEXT>
