<1ST_LINE>r f AM-RailMill     10-04 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rail Mill,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Bid Accepted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Warren Bentz on Tuesday
signed an order accepting Bethlehem Steel Corp.'s $20 cash bid for
a modern, idled rail mill that federal lenders seized from
financially troubled Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp.
   Bethlehem officials have said they would operate the
Westmoreland County mill in conjunction with Bethlehem's rail mill
in Steelton. But it is not clear when the Monessen plant might be
reactivated.
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh closed it because of slack demand for
transportation rail.
   The transfer of the property could face a legal hurdle, however.
Attorney Ken Simon said in Pittsburgh that Monessen and its school
district will appeal to U.S. District Court to block the deal
unless Bentz's order provides for the payment of several hundred
thousand dollars in delinquent property taxes.
   The order addresses the tax issue, but the exact terms will not
be available publicly until the document is filed in bankruptcy
court in Pittsburgh as early as Wednesday, according to Bentz's
office.
   The U.S. Economic Development Administration foreclosed on the
rail mill after bondholders forced the agency to pay $90 million in
principal and interest. The EDA had guaranteed a loan to
Wheeling-Pittsburgh for the construction of the mill and pollution
controls at three sites, including Monessen, said EDA spokeswoman
Elaine Dudley.
   The Monessen project was one of five steel industry projects
that soured for the federal lending agency, she said. Of five
companies that participated in the Steel Loan Program in the late
1970s, three no longer exist and the remainder, Wheeling-Pittsburgh
and LTV Steel Co., are reorganizing under Chapter 11 of federal
bankruptcy laws.
</TEXT>
