<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Dictionary     10-04 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Dictionary,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Big Book Of Words Is Coming: The 2nd Oxford English Dictionary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's largest dictionary of the English
language will be published five months from now and everyone who is
interested will want to have one _ if they can pick it up.
   The second edition of ``The Oxford English Dictionary'' _ known
to word buffs as the OED _ will have 22,000 pages, fill 20 volumes,
weigh 137 pounds (62.5 kg) and be priced at about $2,500.
   ``We are sure we will sell a lot because the dictionary is the
standard work of reference on the English language and any
substantial library will have to have it,'' said Ludo Craddock,
promotions executive of the Oxford University Press.
   The publishing house, founded in 1584, describes the dictionary
as its most adventurous project since it started the first edition
in the 19th century and completed it in 1928.
   It has put the vocabulary of English since 1150 A.D. on a
computer, creating a data base for the language that can be
continuously updated and eventually be made accessible to any
subscriber with a home computer.
   The cost was estimated at approximately $10 million when details
were first announced in May 1984.
   The 1,100-page first volume of the monumental work to be printed
and bound was sent to the seven-day Frankfurt Book Fair in West
Germany, which opened Tuesday.
   ``The first volume we got ready is actually volume two. Volume
one contains a 68-page introduction which wasn't ready in time,''
Craddock said.
   ``It's a 12-month production job just to print and bind the
first run of the dictionary,'' he said.
   The first edition of the OED had 44 million words of text and
the second has 59 million, composed from 350 million printed
characters.
   There are 290,500 main entries on different words, an increase
of 15 percent on the first edition.
   In addition, there are 157,000 combinations and derivatives and
169,000 phrases making a total of 616,500 ``word forms'' which are
defined. The 1928 edition had 414,825.
   The dictionary contains 2,412,400 quotations illustrating how
writers used the words and the first known use of each word.
   The OED was first published in parts between 1884 and 1928 and a
supplement of new words and words missed the first time around was
added in 1933. Together they made up 13 volumes.
   The last of four additional volumes, including the 1933
supplement and 69,000 modern words added to the lexicon, was
finished in 1986 by New Zealander Robert Burchfield, who took 29
years to finish it. The publishers had expected it to take seven
years.
   Since Burchfield's four volumes, 5,000 new words have been added
_ ``most of them at the beginning of the alphabet as Burchfield was
continually adding as he progressed,'' said Craddock.
   James Murray, a Scottish village tailor's son, was the
dictionary's original editor.
   Computerizing the new OED has taken five years under the
supervision of the dictionary's co-editors, John Simpson and Edmund
Weiner. The computer science department of the University of
Waterloo in Ontario, Canada, helped to devise the software and the
British arm of International Business Machines provided the
hardware.
   According to Craddock, the new OED is ``more than five times the
size of any other dictionary of the English language.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881004-0272 </DOCNO>
