<HEAD>Singer Completes Divestiture Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Singer Co. said Tuesday it had
completed its $2 billion divestiture program with the sale of its
Kearfott Division to Astronautics Corp. of America.
   Singer was acquired by Bilzerian Partners in February for about
$1 billion.
   The new owners embarked on a divestiture plan that has seen the
company sell eight units since May.
   ``Our plan from the outset of the acquisition was to retain
Singer businesses with approximately $400 million of annual
revenues,'' said Paul A. Bilzerian, Singer chairman and chief
executive officer.
   The company said the sales have brought in more money than the
acquisition cost, including debt, interest expense and other
expenses.
   The Kearfott Division, based in Little Falls, N.J., is involved
in making equipment used in guidance and navigation systems.
   Astronautics is based in Milwaukee and is involved in making
aircraft instruments and flight control systems.
   What's left at Singer is a company involved principally in
defense-related work with total sales expected to exceed $400
million in 1988. The company also has a 27 percent interest in SSMC
Inc., a joint venture in Japan with Mitsubishi.
</TEXT>
