<HEAD>Judge Approves Reorganization Plan For Placid Oil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge has approved a
reorganization plan for Placid Oil Co., owned by the trust estates
of the Hunt brothers of Dallas.
   In approving the plan, Judge Harold Abramson paved the way for
the Hunts and their lenders to settle a two-year dispute over $1.5
billion in bank loans. The previously announced reorganization plan
had been proposed by William Herbert Hunt, Nelson Bunker Hunt,
Lamar Hunt and 17 of their creditor banks.
   It calls for $663 million in payments and a seven-year note for
$140 million, to be secured by profits from producing properties.
   The Hunts have paid $223.5 million and will raise another $200
million through the sale of their interest in Thanksgiving Tower, a
downtown Dallas office building, and through Placid's stake in the
Black Lake natural gas field in Louisiana.
   The Hunts' North Sea oil and gas operations will secure a
10-year loan with Dutch banks, to raise another $240 million.
   The judge approved the reorganization plan on Friday. A Hunt
spokesman said the transactions are expected to close in several
weeks and will complete the settlement and release Placid from
Chapter 11 bankruptcy.
   In a separate reoganization plan approved last month, the other
half of the Hunts' $1.5 billion in bank debts was settled.
   That $750 million settlement for the three Hunt trusts, the
former sole owners of Penrod Drilling Co., discharged the trusts
from Chapter 11 bankruptcy.
</TEXT>
