<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Fruehauf-Varity     10-04 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fruehauf-Varity,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fruehauf In Buyout Talks With Varity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fruehauf Corp., a truck-trailer manufacturer, has
signed a letter of intent to discuss a possible stock-swap
acquisition by Varity Corp., a Toronto-based heavy machinery maker,
the companies said Tuesday.
   Under the proposed transaction, announced after the close of
stock trading, Fruehauf stockholders would receive two shares of
Varity stock for each share of Fruehauf, and Fruehauf would become
a Varity subsidiary.
   Varity spokesman J.R. Nowling said further details would not be
released. He said a letter of intent to pursue the merger will
expire Oct. 31 if no agreement is reached.
   Fruehauf's publicly-traded Class B stock closed at $5.87{ a
share, up 12{ cents Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange. Varity
dipped 12{ cents to $2.62{ a share.
   The merger would be subject to approval by the boards of both
companies and the Fruehauf shareholders, the companies said.
   Varity, formerly Massey-Ferguson, said Aug. 31 it was interested
in acquiring Fruehauf's Kelsey-Hayes subsidiary and might buy the
parent company and spin off its truck-trailer manufacturing
business.
   Kelsey-Hayes, acquired by Fruehauf in 1973, manufactures auto
and truck wheels and industrial parts and is a leading supplier of
anti-lock braking systems.
   Fruehauf was left with big debts, high interest payments and
operating losses in its trailer and maritime operations following a
leveraged buyout by executives in December 1986 to ward off a
hostile takeover bid by New York raider Asher Edelman.
   For the first six months of 1988, Fruehauf had a net loss of
$27.1 million on revenue of $1.03 billion, compared with a loss of
$21.1 million on revenue of $1 billion in the same period a year
earlier.
   In June, Fruehauf sold its agricultural wheel division for $8.8
million and some land for $6.5 million. Money from both sales was
received in June and applied to long-term debt.
   Varity posted a profit of $33.5 million, or 13 cents a share, on
revenue of $1.14 billion in the six months ended July 31. The
profit included a one-time $14.4 million tax credit. In the same
period of 1987 the company lost $17.6 million, due partly to an
$8.6 million writedown, on revenue of $915.3 million.
</TEXT>
